<FIRST>r a AM-OilExplosion     05-03 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Explosion,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Truck Driver Critically Injured In Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire that started while a tank truck was
loading gasoline destroyed a fuel storage facility and 275,000
gallons of oil, burning the vehicle's driver critically, officials
said.
   The fire sent up a column of smoke that could be seen for at
least 20 miles.
   Five hours after the blaze broke out, flames still were shooting
50 feet in the air, but fire officials said the fire was under
control and would be allowed to burn itself out overnight.
   Firefighters planned to be on the scene into the morning, said
Clarke County Fire Chief James Hansford.
   The fire at Lay's Petroleum Products, a Shell Oil Co. facility
which has four above-ground storage tanks, apparently was started
by the truck, Hansford said.
   The driver, James Coile, apparently gunned his engine several
times as he backed toward a filling area, sucking fumes into his
exhaust pipe and touching off the blaze, Hansford said.
   Coile, 48, of Danielsville was taken to St. Marys Hospital in
critical condition and airlifted to Humana Hospital in Augusta,
said a St. Marys spokesman.
   Hansford said the tank truck exploded, but all of the storage
tanks held.
   Also destroyed were a motor home, a warehouse containing 5,000
55-gallon drums of oil and the company's office building, Hansford
said.
   There was no immediate damage estimate.
</TEXT>
