<FIRST>u i PM-BorderSpat     05-03 0829</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Border Spat,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>India And Nepal Fuss and Feud at Border Point</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   SIRISIAR BRIDGE, On the Indian-Nepalese Border (AP) _ A friendly
sort of friction has set in at this crossing point between India,
the political and military giant of South Asia, and Nepal, a tiny
and landlocked kingdom.
   For more than a month, Nepal has been defying and exasperating
India by refusing to renegotiate trade agreements on India's terms.
   As a result, India has imposed a partial blockade and Nepal is
suffering severe shortages of fuel needed to operate motor
vehicles, provide electrical power and cook food.
   Medicines, baby food and other essential goods also are in short
supply.
   The problem is as tangled as the traffic jam of bullock carts,
horse-drawn carriages and bicycle-powered rickshaws trying to
negotiate the narrow wooden bridge over the Sirisiar River without
getting stuck in the cracks between the creaking planks.
   The bullocks' long, pointed horns scrape and snag on the
rickshaws' cloth canopies, much as the government officials in New
Delhi and Katmandu are scraping and snagging in the political
impasse.
   India, population 880 million, perceives Nepal as an ungrateful
neighbor, seeking preferential treatment for itself while refusing
to grant India reciprocal privileges.
   Nepal, population 17 million, sees India as a bit of a bully,
trying to thwart Nepalese efforts to diversify its trading partners.
   Officially speaking, the Indian blockade is not total.
Practically speaking, its effects come close to being total.
   ``This is not a blockade. You can see the trucks are moving,''
customs collector Asit Mitra said in the Indian border town of
Raxaul as a score of vehicles lumbered over the bridge to Nepal,
hauling burlap bags of salt, cases of baby formula and brand new _
but empty _ tanks for cooking gas.
   ``The goods are coming in, but not as they were,'' said Mayor
Vimal Srivastav, three miles up the road in the Nepalese town of
Birganj.
   At the Birganj customs yard, the goods are unloaded from Indian
trucks. But the porters are sleeping in the midday heat atop the
cartons they normally would be transferring to Nepalese trucks.
   The diesel and gasoline to run the trucks 75 miles north to
Katmandu, the Nepalese capital, no longer arrive from India, itself
a net importer of petroleum products.
   ``It's like you get the torch (flashlight), but not the
battery,'' said Pashupati Shaha, a hotel owner in Birganj.
   When the bilateral trade and transit treaties expired March 23
with no replacements in the offing, India closed 13 of the 15
official crossing points on the 1,095-mile border. Only Raxaul and
Jogbani remain open.
   Nepal wanted to renegotiate the two treaties separately, one
governing trade with India, the other covering vital transit rights
from Calcutta to the border for non-Indian imports. India sought a
single treaty to safeguard its own trade with Nepal.
   Nepal has little to offer foreign trading partners, apart from
goatskins and a few spices. But it imports machinery, housewares,
textiles and food in addition to pharmaceutical and petroleum
products.
   For the last two years, about 40 percent of Nepal's imports were
Indian. Fifteen years ago, more than 80 percent were Indian.
   Especially of concern to India are recent Nepalese efforts to
expand trade with China, India's longtime regional rival and the
only other country with direct land access to Nepal.
   India's pique heightened last fall when Nepal purchased
anti-aircraft guns and other weapons from China, prompting two
questions in New Delhi: Why was Nepal making purchases from China,
and why did the tiny Himalayan monarchy, which has about 35,000 men
under arms compared to India's 1.4 million, need anti-aircraft
guns, anyway?
   Nepal considers its trade and defense needs its own business.
   ``Trade has its own nature,'' Foreign Minister Shailendra Kumar
Upadhyaya told a reporter in Katmandu this week. ``Trade will
increase normally with any country with which we receive a fair
deal.''
   One more nettle is Nepal's decision requiring the 150,000
Indians in Nepal to obtain work permits, while India has made no
similar requirements of the estimated 5 million Nepalese in India.
   In addition, Birganj had long been a shopper's delight for
Indians, whose own country prides itself on self-sufficiency and
imports little of the Western and Japanese goods widely available
in Nepal.
   The Nepalese joke about their ability to sell just about
anything with a foreign label to Indian visitors.
   Shaha, the Birganj hotel owner, remarked, ``You can blame Nepal
for this. The Indians can find some of these things cheaper in
Calcutta and Madras, but they want to come to Nepal and buy. Some
merchants import saris from India, stamp `Made in Japan' on them,
and the Indians are very happy to buy.''
   ``The Nepalese will buy seven or eight times what they need of
something, import it through Calcutta, then smuggle it back across
the border to sell it in India,'' an Indian government official
said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
