<FIRST>r a PM-TroubledMayor     05-03 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Troubled Mayor,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Just Three Weeks After Election, LA Mayor Faces Political Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Mayor Tom Bradley won a fifth term three
weeks ago, it should have been a time of celebration for the
71-year-old sharecropper's son. Instead, he found himself facing
what's become the political crisis of his career.
   After 16 years of an administration free of personal scandal,
the usually bland and steady Bradley is the subject of a
conflict-of-interest probe for accepting thousands of dollars in
consulting fees from banks that did business with the city.
   He says he was unaware of the business ties when he accepted the
money.
   Bradley also is under fire because his daughter was employed by
a project to which he helped funnel nearly $400,000 of city money,
the Task Force for Africa-Los Angeles Relations. He said he was
unaware she had been hired.
   The allegations, which began surfacing at the end of the
campaign, have tarnished the nice-guy image of Bradley, a former
police lieutenant dubbed the Teflon Mayor for his ability to escape
blame for the city's gang, growth and pollution problems.
   Other mayors have had bigger problems. Political allies of New
York's Ed Koch have committed suicide or gone to prison. San
Antonio's Henry Cisneros admitted a close personal relationship
with a woman not his wife. Detroit's Coleman Young has been slapped
with a paternity suit by a former city employee.
   But for Bradley, probably the blandest of big-city mayors, it's
a major embarrassment.
   For politically dull Los Angeles it's a rare taste of a scandal
at the very top.
   Bradley has scrambled to defuse the controversy by placing his
investments _ which range from an estimated $101,000 to $1 million
_ in a blind trust.
   He has established an ethics panel _ which announced Monday it
won't investigate Bradley and will instead rewrite the city ethics
code to restore public trust in city government.
   Bradley also has retained lawyers from Manatt, Phelps,
Rothenberg and Phillips, a law firm of Democratic political
insiders that is handling the ethics defense of House Speaker Jim
Wright.
   He is refusing comment until a city investigation is completed.
But allegations surface daily.
   On Tuesday, the Herald Examiner reported that Far East National
Bank was allowed to hold $600,000 in city money for three months in
1987 without paying interest. It said the account was set up by
Bradley. Two months after the situation was discovered, Bradley
started earning $18,000 a year as a consultant to the bank. He has
since returned the money, saying he was unaware Far East had
business ties with the city.
   Bradley, the city's first black mayor, won a fifth term April
11, barely escaping a runoff with challenger Nate Holden and
drawing the lowest turnout in decades.
   ``Unquestionably the issues that have been raised over the
course of the last three weeks have raised some doubts in the minds
of some people,'' Bradley said.
   Supporters predict, however, he will survive the controversy.
   ``He's a super-quality guy. He has never done anything the least
bit questionable on anything,'' said Richard Riordan, president of
the Los Angeles Coliseum Commission and a Republican who supports
the Democratic Bradley.
   ``He's so perfect that people want to knock him off his hill and
find his imperfections,'' he added.
   Holden, who made headlines by buying back semi-automatic weapons
from the public, said: ``I think the quicker we get to the bottom
of this matter the better everything's going to be. Business at
City Hall is stopped. It's at a standstill.''
   In addition to examining Bradley's relationships with Far East
and the African task force, investigators are focusing on Valley
Federal Savings &amp; Loan Association. Bradley was paid at least
$71,000 to serve on its board while it did business with the city.
He resigned the post the day after his election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
