<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RaceSchool     05-03 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Race School,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pittsburgh School a Model Against Racism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Educators hope a new program will make a
middle school a model for race relations and improved academics.
   The restructured school _ to be called the Prospect Middle
School Center for Multiracial, Multicultural and Multiethnic
Education _ is to offer programs to encourage students to respect
other races and teach staff members how to instruct students of
other races, officials said Tuesday.
   ``Perhaps it will improve race relations throughout the entire
city,'' said Principal Robert Pipkin.
   ``It will be the model where we develop programs, policies and
practices for district-wide use,'' Pittsburgh School District
spokeswoman Pat Crawford said.
   Ms. Crawford said no new students or staff members would be
added to the present Prospect Middle School in the city's Mount
Washington neighborhood. She said the new programs are to begin
next fall.
   School Superintendent Richard C. Wallace said the idea came from
principals and consultants who studied city schools last fall.
   He said concerns about racism stemmed from occasional fights in
schools and the disproportionate number of black students who are
suspended or referred to special education classes.
   ``I wouldn't say it's at this point a serious problem, a crisis
situation, but we don't want it to get to that level,'' Wallace
said.
   Of about 39,600 public school students in Pittsburgh, 52 percent
are black and 48 percent are white, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
