<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--MoneyRots     05-03 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Money Rots,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmer's Life Savings Rots Underground</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The old Chinese habit of shunning banks has
caused an 82-year-old farmer to lose most of his life savings to
mildew, an official newspaper reported today.
   When Zhang Dexiang, who had buried his life savings of about
$1,200 in his courtyard five years ago, dug up the money recently
he discovered it was moldy ``almost beyond recognition,'' the China
Daily reported.
   The farmer in northeastern Liaoning province was only able to
salvage $400, which he exchanged for new bills at a local bank, it
said.
   China, which has a surplus of cash in its overheated economy, is
suffering from a shortage of funds for investment because many
people, fearing runaway inflation, traditionally refuse to put
their money in the bank.
   Personal caches like Zhang's account for an estimated $133
billion.
   The interest rate on one-year deposits was raised last year from
7.2 percent to 8.64 percent, but fails to keep pace with 36 percent
inflation.
</TEXT>
