<FIRST>u a AM-GoldTax 1stLd-Writethu a0769 05-03 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gold Tax, 1st Ld-Writethu, a0769,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nevadans Vote on $52 Million Tax, State Bond Debt Limit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with gold tax passing; minor editing
elsewhere to conform.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nevadans voted 3-1 Tuesday to approve a
$52 million mining tax hike, but balloting was close on a plan to
double the money Nevada can borrow for new state construction.
   With 25 percent of 609 precincts counted, the mining tax
proposal was favored 26,692-7,966. The vote on the construction
measure was 18,363 for and 17,051 against.
   Election officials around the state predicted low voter
turnouts, ranging from 30 to 40 percent of the more than 383,000
people eligible to vote.
   ``It's nothing great but it's steady,'' Carson City
Clerk-Recorder Alan Glover said of early voter turnout, which he
estimated at about 30 percent.
   Recent polls indicated the mining tax would win approval. Gov.
Bob Miller and key lawmakers warned that without approval of the
plan, the state would face fiscal chaos.
   Had the measure lost, officials said, the Legislature would be
in session an extra month slashing budgets and raising taxes to
make up for the loss of the anticipated mining tax revenues,
expected to be $52 million over a two-year period.
   The law would allow the state to impose a 5 percent tax on the
net proceeds of mines. The ballot question was the result of an
agreement struck during the 1987 Legislature between the mining
industry, lawmakers and then-Gov. Dick Bryan.
   The other question on the ballot would double the money Nevada
can borrow for new state construction. The governor's proposed
budget includes money generated by state bond sales for new prison
and university construction projects.
   Officials have argued that without doubling the constitutional
limit on bond debt to 2 percent of the assessed value of all
taxable land, Nevada will have to pay cash for such projects.
   But opponents argue that while Nevada needs the bond money,
lawmakers who wrote supporting and opposing arguments for the
proposal intentionally neglected to mention that the state must
repay new bond sales through higher property taxes.
</TEXT>
