<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TankerSpill     05-03 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dramatic Evidence of Wildlife Damage In Wake Of Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Spill-Protests, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of dead birds, snared in a giant
glob of sticky oil, line a beach 300 miles southwest of Valdez,
victims of the spreading crude that has devastated Alaska's coast
for weeks.
   While enviromentalists, government and Exxon officials trade
barbs over blame, the oil drifts inexorably, fouling the shoreline
and leaving dead, dying or dirtied birds, fish, otters, seals and
sea lions. Even Alaska's lumbering, powerful brown bears have been
seen prowling on oil-caked beaches.
   The oil is selective: It leap-frogs large stretches of coast,
then hits others with contamination ranging from a light film to
ankle-deep goo.
   ``We landed along a wide tidal basin, about six miles of
beach,'' said Ray Bane, superintendent of Katmai National Park.
``We found oil debris in large quantities throughout the tidal
zone. We saw 2,000 to 3,000 dead birds. ... You can't really tell
what they are. They're one big blob of oil.''
   Since March 24, when the tanker Exxon Valdez smashed into Bligh
Reef in Prince William Sound and leaked 10.1 million gallons of
crude through its shattered hull, the reports of destroyed wildlife
have multiplied steadily.
   The spill has reached Chignik, 525 miles southwest of Valdez,
and residents there are fearful the oil may interfere with their
salmon season, which begins next week.
   ``What we found, say in every 100-foot distance, was four to
eight dead murres on the average,'' Bane said of the sea birds.
``We also saw fresh bear tracks going back into the impacted areas.
There was evidence of foxes and other scavengers. We observed one
bear _ a sow and three yearlings _ that was in the contaminated
area, feeding on dead birds. ... We saw eagles carrying oil-covered
birds. We saw one eagle so coated in oil that it couldn't fly.''
   One state scientist said wind-whipped oil ``mousse'' was pounded
into a beach by wave action and buried a yard below the surface.
Another reported seeing otters surrounded by floating oil.
   Late Monday, Exxon offered a revised plan to clean up 364 miles
of tainted coastline by September, but environmentalists and Coast
Guard Adm. Paul Yost, the federal government's top official
monitoring the spill, immediately criticized it as inadequate.
   Dennis Kelso, Alaska's commissioner of environmental
conservation, said the proposal was ``a few pages of wishful
thinking ... (that) makes it appear as though cleaning those areas
is little more than a Sunday stroll on the beach.''
   Yost, who must approve the plan before it can go into effect,
called Exxon's strategy ``very thin.'' Yost briefly toured part of
the spill area Tuesday, visiting the USS Juneau, the Coast Gaurd's
command ship for the cleanup.
   Today, Yost was scheduled to take U.S. Transportation Secretary
Samuel Skinner on an inspection of the spill zone. At a speech
Tuesday in Washington, D.C., Skinner called the spill ``the most
significant environmental disaster this nation has ever faced.''
   On Thursday, he meets with Vice President Dan Quayle, who is
expected in Alaska after a 12-day tour of the Pacific.
   Exxon also faced a day of boycott Tuesday, as groups around the
country urged consumers to stop buying Exxon products. Consumer
activist Ralph Nader said in Washington that Exxon ``should not be
allowed to forget'' the spill and that a boycott would send the oil
giant a message.
   J. Edward Surette Jr., executive director of the Bay State
Gasoline Retailers Association in Billerica, Mass., said it was too
early to assess the boycott's impact.
   Exxon spokeswoman Sarah Johnson said 10,000 of its 7 million
credit cards have been cut up and returned since the spill.
   In Anchorage, 400 chanting and sign-waving protesters rallied in
front of Exxon's Alaska headquarters, calling for a boycott.
   The Exxon Valdez is undergoing preliminary repairs in Prince
William Sound and is to be towed next month to Portland, Ore., home
of the only drydock on the West Coast capable of handling the
987-foot ship.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
