<FIRST>u a PM-Names     05-03 0919</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0953</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIMI VALLEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pop superstar Michael Jackson donned
a disguise to do a little shopping and all it managed to do was
attract attention.
   Police were called to a jewelry store after employees reported a
suspicious person was casing the joint. The suspicious person
turned out to be the Grammy Award-winning singer wearing a wig,
fake mustache, false teeth and eyelashes.
   Jackson and an unidentified 12-year-old boy had gone into the
store Monday to look at rings.
   ``I asked him `Why are you wearing a false mustache?''' said
H.N. Edwards, a security guard for the Sycamore Plaza shopping
center. ``He said `I have to _ I'm in disguise _ I'm Michael
Jackson.' When he told me this, my first thought was this guy had
gotten off the elevator between floors.''
   Police Sgt. Ken Tacke and Officer Gordon Weeks said they
questioned Jackson, and asked him to remove his disguise and show
his identification.
   ``He told the police he has to wear a disguise when he goes
shopping or he would be mobbed by the crowds,'' Edwards said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The voices of the late Gov. Earl Long
and lawmakers from three decades ago reverberated through the
Capitol _ courtesy of actor Paul Newman and company.
   The cast and crew of the movie ``Blaze'' _ a portrayal of Long's
relationship with stripper Blaze Starr during the late 1950s _ took
over the House chamber shortly after lawmakers recessed at midnight
Monday.
   Although the chamber was sealed off to visitors, Newman was
heard all over the Capitol through the House sound system.
   Most of the day was spent on a scene in which Long, portrayed by
Newman, made an uninvited appearance on the House floor and
demanded the microphone to discuss black voting rights.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEVILLE, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Multimillionaire Malcolm S. Forbes kicked
off an eight-day balloon trip across Spain, saying he was
celebrating the 500th anniversary of the discovery of the New World
three years early.
   Accompanied by son Robert, the Forbes magazine publisher planned
to fly in a balloon shaped like the Santa Maria used by Christopher
Columbus' expedition to the New World in 1492 on behalf of the
Spanish crown.
   Forbes, 69, told reporters Tuesday that his Spain trip ``is an
original and fun way to contribute to the commemoration of the
discovery of the New World'' and ``foster friendship between the
Spanish and American people.''
   The balloon enthusiast said his trip would be similar to earlier
ones across China, Germany, Thailand, Turkey, Pakistan and the
Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Charles says he's a hands-on leader of his
trust fund for young entrepreneurs.
   The Prince's Youth Business Trust gives grants up to $1,700 and
loans up to five times that amount to young people who want to
start businesses.
   Speaking of his style as president, Charles said, ``I shower my
trust people with endless notes, letters and telephone calls
asking, `What about this and why?' `We ought to do this,' `Have you
thought about that?'
   ``I think I must give them endless headaches,'' he said, adding
that to elicit financial support from banks and business people, he
has ``badgered people endlessly.''
   The heir to the British throne told British Broadcasting Corp.
radio Tuesday he sympathized with the difficulties of setting out
in life without a college education.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than two years after a life-saving bone
marrow transplant, tenor Jose Carreras says he is looking forward
to singing opera again and raising money for leukemia research.
   At a news conference Tuesday at the Fred Hutchinson Cancer
Research Center, where he underwent surgery in November 1987,
Carreras said he ``considered myself really discharged the day I
was able to sing again.''
   That was in July, when his concert drew 150,000 wildly cheering
fans at a stadium in Barcelona, Spain, his birthplace and hometown.
Now, he is looking forward to his first post-surgery opera role in
``Medea,'' scheduled to open in July in Barcelona.
   He was in town for Thursday's benefit concert for the newly
established Jose Carreras International Foundation for the
Prevention of Leukemia.
   ``If in one sense this recital can give a little hope to even
one patient in this hospital who is in the condition that I was in,
this recital will have achieved its purpose,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businessman Harvey Mackay, whose first book,
``Swim With the Sharks Without Being Eaten Alive'' sold more than a
million copies, says he enjoys the water so much he's diving in
again.
   Mackay said Tuesday he has sold world publication rights for a
second book to William Morrow &amp; Co. for hardcover and to Fawcett
Books, a unit of Random House, for paperback.
   Mackay said the new book will be broader and more in-depth than
``Sharks,'' in which he outlined his philosophy on how to become
successful and the insights he gleaned from his experiences in
building Mackay Envelope Corp. into a business with 350 employees,
sales of about $35 million and modern plants in Minnesota and Iowa.
   A person is never too old to achieve success, said the
56-year-old Mackay, who will address the subject of aging in the
new book.
   ``I don't believe in age,'' he said. ``Find something you love
to do, and you'll never have to work a day in your life. You find
people like that at any age level. Age doesn't limit people one
tenth of one percent.''
</TEXT>
