<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-TheJapaneseRest     05-03 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-The Japanese Rest,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Country Closes Down for Lengthened Annual Holiday Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan has closed down for its annual weeklong
series of spring holidays, including one created by the government
this year just to encourage the industrious workforce to let its
reputation slide a bit.
   For many, the annual ``Golden Week'' started Friday, giving them
the rare opportunity to take up to nine days off in a row. For
others, time off began today, the first of three consecutive
official national holidays.
   April 29, which fell on Friday, has been a holiday for more than
60 years, marking the birthday of the late Emperor Hirohito. After
his death Jan. 7, its name was changed to Greenery Day.
   Constitution Day falls on May 3 and Children's Day on May 5.
This year, the government has made May 4 a national holiday also,
to encourage more people to take consecutive days off.
   ``It's different from foreign countries. Japanese generally
can't take several days of vacation at one time,'' said Reiko
Tomizawa of the Japan Travel Bureau, the country's largest travel
agency.
   ``People even used to work every other day during Golden Week
until the government made May 4 a holiday this year,'' Ms. Tomizawa
said. ``It's just the national character of the Japanese to work
hard without vacations.''
   But government officials believe the Japanese should devote more
time to leisure activities and spend more money on both them and
imports in order to reduce the nation's huge trade surplus.
   Earlier this year, the government instituted a shortened
five-day work week every other week for government employees. It is
enouraging private business to follow suit.
   A record 17.7 million Japanese, or 14.7 percent of the
population, are gong on trips of more than one night this week, and
an all-time high of 365,000 are taking advantage of the high value
of the yen to go overseas, according to a survey by the Japan
Travel Bureau.
   The most popular family destinations this year are Hawaii, Guam
and Hong Kong, the bureau said.
   Young, single ``office ladies'' are turning toward Canada and
Europe, the agency said. They usually save money by living at their
parents' home, and they have a reputation for being big holiday
spenders.
   Japanese are spending an average $2,107 on travel abroad, up 8.7
percent, and $394, up 8.9 percent, for domestic travel, according
to the agency's study.
   Many workers, however, see Golden Week as a time to lounge
around at home and avoid the jammed highways, hot springs, and
mountain resorts.
   ``It's too crowded and expensive to do anything,'' said Katsuya
Hirai, 33, who works in the sales department of a Japanese
automaker. ``And it's before our June bonus, so I don't have any
money right now.''
   ``I can afford to take the family for a day trip to a safari
park near Mount Fuji,'' he says. ``But my wife says she wants to
eat out every night.''
   Hotels across Southeast Asia report room shortages during the
week because of the Japanese influx, especially in popular
destinations such as Thailand, Hong Kong and even Singapore, until
recently suffering from a hotel glut.
   ``To make matters worse, some hotels in Southeast Asia are
becoming disenchanted with tour groups, the mode of travel
particularly favored by the Japanese,'' said the Nihon Keizai
Shimbun, Japan's main economic newspaper.
   ``They are starting to focus on individual guests, where the
profit margins are higher and the noise level is lower.''
</TEXT>
