<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Agenda     05-03 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Agenda,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush to Use Commencement Speeches to Spell out Foreign Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will spell out the conclusions
of his wide-ranging foreign policy review in the next few weeks in
a series of commencement addresses dealing with East-West
relations, the Soviet Union and NATO, the White House says.
   ``Basically it will point out the Bush view of the world and the
United States' role in it and our attitude toward other
countries,'' White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said
Tuesday.
   ``There will be some differences with existing policy although
the general thrust will not be too different,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``It's not clear to me there will ever be any written reports''
about the review, Fitzwater said. ``These speeches may in effect be
the most definitive enunciation of the results of that review.''
   Bush is scheduled to give five commencement speeches this month,
beginning with a May 12 address at Texas A&amp;M University. Fitzwater
said the topic of that speech will be foreign policy, although it
is not clear what the focus will be.
   A May 21 speech at Boston University will spell out Bush's view
of East-West relations and U.S. strategy for dealing with the
Soviet Union, the spokesman said.
   Then, Bush will use a May 24 speech at the U.S. Coast Guard
Academy in New London, Conn., to discuss the strength of NATO and
the future of the 16-nation Western Alliance.
   Two days later, Bush will fly to Rome on the first leg of a
four-nation trip and a full NATO summit May 29-30. In recent days,
NATO has been shaken by a dispute over modernization of short-range
nuclear weapons stationed in West Germany.
   Bush's speeches will follow on the heels of next week's trip to
Moscow by Secretary of State James A. Baker III for talks with
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze.
   Baker's trip is expected to produce a date for resumption of
negotiations to cut back long-range nuclear weapons and explore
possibilities for a summit sometime this year between Bush and
Gorbachev.
   The arms talks went into recess late last year and were expected
to resume in February, but were put off by Bush pending completion
of the foreign policy reviews.
   Fitzwater said the NATO summit and a seven-nation economic
summit in Paris in July will give further definition to Bush's
policies.
   With the first 100 days of Bush's administration completed,
Fitzwater said the next three months will concentrate heavily on
foreign policy objectives.
   Other commencement addresses by Bush this month will be on May
13 at Alcorn State University in Lorman, Miss., and at Mississippi
State University at Starkville on the same day.
</TEXT>
