<DOCNO> AP890503-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0308EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AviationSecurity     05-03 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aviation Security,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosives-Detection Bill Advances In House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill that would give airlines and airports
$270 million for devices to detect plastic explosives goes before a
House committee Thursday, after a subcommittee rejected Republican
efforts to make airlines pay half the cost.
   The legislation requires installation of the sophisticated units
in U.S. and foreign airports that are considered vulnerable to
terrorists. It does the same thing as a Transportation Department
order last month, which would have airlines pay the full cost of
the units.
   The bill, passed Tuesday by the House Public Works aviation
subcommittee, would take the $270 million from an aviation trust
fund without budgeting new money. The fund has accumulated more
than $6 billion in fees collected from airline passengers for
airport improvements.
   Republicans tried to amend the measure to require that U.S.
airlines pay half the cost, but the bill received no opposing votes
when it passed with full federal funding for the security devices.
   The Transportation Department last month ordered airlines to
install the sophisticated bomb-detection machines at high-risk
airports. Both the order and the legislation call for detection
systems such as thermal neutron devices that have been tested by
the Federal Aviation Administration.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said Tuesday he expects
the first machine to be installed in July at John F. Kennedy
International Airport in New York and the second at an airport in
Great Britain. He said several more should be in place before the
end of the year.
   Skinner was in Europe last week meeting with officials of other
governments about aviation security as a result of the Dec. 21
bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over Scotland that killed 270 people.
He said the administration feels the airlines should pay for
additional security, using revenue from security fees collected
with passengers' tickets.
   The legislation would provide up to 100 percent grants to U.S.
airlines and airports which would own, operate and maintain the
detection units expected to cost about $1 million each. The airline
grants also would cover installation in high-risk foreign airports.
   Subcommittee chairman Rep. James Oberstar, D-Minn., argued that
the government should pay for the devices that would examine
checked-in baggage because the government, not airlines, has been
the target of terrorists.
   Other governments will be paying for security units used by
their airlines, which would put them at a competitive advantage,
Oberstar said.
   Republicans argued that airlines have always paid for security
equipment at airports, and the subsidy could lead to other moves to
use federal money to help airlines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ChemicalWeapons     05-03 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chemical Weapons,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Customs Chief Blames Courts for Problems with Enforcement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American agents are ``plugged into the
underworld'' of illegal diversion of deadly chemical weapons
materials, but their successes are being undermined by the courts,
says the U.S. customs commissioner.
   ``The penalties we have are there,'' William von Raab told the
Senate Governmental Affairs Committee at a hearing Tuesday on the
illegal export of biological agents and other material used to make
chemical weapons. ``The problem is judges don't apply them.''
   The Customs Service, through informants and various sting
operations, has controlled to some degree the diversion of the
materials to terrorist nations, von Raab said.
   ``With the volume we're dealing with, I don't think we're losing
a lot,'' he said. ``We're pretty well plugged into the underworld.''
   However, the effort by the Customs Service, the State Department
and the Commerce Department has been thwarted by the judicial
system, which has failed to impose stiffer penalties, von Raab said.
   The commissioner described the case of Peter Walaschek, a West
German national arrested for purchasing three orders of
thiodiglycol, a precursor for mustard gas, from Alcolac
International Inc., of Baltimore, Md., for shipment to Greece and
Singapore. The shipments were re-exported to Iran.
   Customs agents, suspicious of Walaschek's third order, told
inspectors in Norfolk, Va., to seize the chemical and replace it
with water. The agents then tracked the shipment of water to
Singapore; Karachi, Pakistan; and then Bandar Abbas, Iran.
   Walaschek was arrested on July 27, 1988, in Maryland and pleaded
guilty to violating the Export Administration Act. He admitted that
he purchased the chemical at the request of Sayed Kharim Ali
Sobhani, an Iranian diplomat stationed at his country's embassy in
Bonn, West Germany.
   But under protests from the government, Walaschek was placed in
a halfway house. He later fled and is currently a fugitive in West
Germany.
   Von Raab said another part of the problem is that the criminals
give the impression of being average businessmen.
   ``They look normal, they've done normal things _ offering and
accepting merchandise _ but what they're dealing with is poison,''
the commissioner said.
   The chemical industry is the United States' largest
international trading industry with total shipments in 1988 at $238
billion, according to the Commerce Department. Current export
controls apply to 40 of an estimated 20,000 commercially traded
chemicals and chemical products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0325EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-StealthBomber     05-03 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stealth Bomber,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Gives More Details on B-2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Air Force general has offered a
surprising amount of detail about the new B-2 stealth bomber,
disclosing it will have great range, an ability to land almost
anywhere and a payload of 25 tons of bombs.
   The plane's capabilities will be such that had the B-2 been
available in 1986, when American bombers attacked Tripoli, Libya,
``just three to four B-2s could have done the job direct from
stateside bases,'' said Gen. Bernard P. Randolph, the head of the
Air Force Systems Command.
   More than 100 combat and support aircraft from the Air Force and
Navy were used for that bombing mission. The B-2 would require at
most two tankers to fuel it during the mission, Randolph said.
   Randolph, in making his revelations last weekend, said little
about the cost of the B-2 or of Defense Secretary Dick Cheney's
recent budget decision to postpone the start of production by a
full year.
   But he asserted to a meeting of aviation reporters in Phoenix,
Ariz., that the B-2 was nothing less than a ``quantum leap into the
21st century'' that was essential to America's future strength,
thanks to its ability to slip behind enemy lines without being
detected on radar.
   Randolph appeared before the reporters on Saturday. A text of
his remarks was released later at the Pentagon.
   Not only is the B-2 destined to become a key part of America's
nuclear arsenal, but it offers a capability to deliver conventional
weapons that is unmatched among manned bombers, Randolph said.
   The Libyan bombing raid ``could have been conducted with greater
tactical surprise and vastly less risk of life,'' he said.
   Among Randolph's disclosures:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _The B-2 will be capable of flying more than 6,000 nautical
miles _ or 6,900 statute miles _ without refueling. With one
mid-air refueling, it will be able to fly more than 10,000 nautical
miles or 11,500 statute miles.
   _The plane will have a maximum takeoff weight of more than
350,000 pounds and will be able to carry up to 50,000 pounds of
either nuclear or conventional bombs. Specifically, it will be able
to carry 16 large nuclear weapons, 20 smaller nuclear bombs, or up
to 80 conventional 500-pound bombs. The B-52, the mainstay
strategic bomber, carries 60,000 tons of bombs.
   _The plane is designed to operate with minimal support equipment
and can land on any runway that's just 40 feet wide, meaning ``it
can operate from any airfield that can handle a 727 commercial
airliner.''
   ``With one air refueling, operating from just four bases _ two
stateside and two overseas _ the B-2 could cover any point on the
world's land mass on a non-stop radius mission carrying a full
conventional payload,'' Randolph said.
   ``Those possibilities could deter a great deal of adventurism.''
   Randolph also announced the first flight of the B-2 would
probably occur in about two months, but only when the Air Force was
convinced the plane was ready.
   The B-2, built primarily by Northrop Corp., is a
futuristic-looking gray-and black ``flying wing'' designed to evade
enemy radar and deliver nuclear weapons. It resembles a huge,
tailless manta ray, with wide sweeping wings blending smoothly into
a rounded cockpit and engine housings on the top side.
   The stealth gets its name from the claim that it will be
extremely difficult to detect by enemy radar, due to the extensive
use of exotic composite materials; its lack of sharp surface
angles; and a cross-section that offers a very small profile to
radar.
   Before Cheney's decision to slow production, the Air Force had
estimated 132 of the planes would cost $68.1 billion. Even if money
spent on research and development is set aside, that amounts to
production costs of $305 million per plane.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0307EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     05-03 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWTOWN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elections for borough offices never draw
long lines at the voting booth, but this year's contests set a new
standard for apathy.
   Candidates outnumbered voters in Monday's election, when only 21
people voted for the 22 candidates. Nearly all the voters were
either running for office or were relatives of the candidates.
   Every two years, the borough, which administers the center of
the southwestern Connecticut town, stages elections that generate
little opposition or interest. No political affiliations are noted
on the ballot. The positions include board of tax review, zoning
commission, fire inspector, tax assessor and tax collector.
   Jean St. Jean, a candidate for burgess, a borough council, said
a persistent drizzle may have kept the throngs home this week.
   The winners?
   Everyone.
   Even Clerk Ethel Connor, who forgot to put her name on the
ballot, kept her post. She received 13 write-in votes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House budget document usually makes
for dry reading, but it's well-thumbed this year.
   Hidden among thousands of items are several gags. On page 243,
between spending for the Department of Corrections and salaries for
state employees, are 15 sports trivia questions. A word jumble
asking arcane questions is on another page.
   On the cover, a newspaper cartoon shows a threadbare pauper
examining his empty pockets _ a visual reference to the no-frills
spending plan the House Appropriations Committee approved Monday.
   ``There's not enough in there to take seriously. It's what's not
in there that's got everybody upset,'' said Appropriations Chairman
T.K. Wetherell. ``I thought everybody would read it this year for a
change.''
   The $22.7 billion spending plan also has buried in it an offer
of $10 and a free turkey dinner to the first member of the capital
press corps who finds it.
   The Miami Herald bureau chief, Mark Silva, was the winner but
declined the reward.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What's in a name? In this rapidly
developing community, there're omelette makings for some.
   Huevos (Egg) Circle and Jamon (Ham) Lane are some of the street
names in the same neighborhood of Mission Viejo, which has grown
from scratch to 75,000 people in 23 years.
   The Spanish heritage of the area has inspired some fanciful
names for places and streets. The original Rancho Mission Viejo was
established under a Spanish land grant.
   ``The story was told that when they decided to have a Spanish
theme for the community _ Barcelona walls, Franciscan bells,
Spanish-themed architecture _ they decided all streets would have
Spanish names,'' said Wendy Wetzel, director of corporate
communications for the Mission Viejo Co.
   But Ronald Harmon, professor of Spanish and Portuguese at
California State University, Fullerton, said some of the names are
silly.
   ``Unfortunately people don't often have a clear sense of what it
means to use another language, so they use it
impressionistically,'' Harmon said. ``It just sounds `Spanishy.'
The other thing is that people have a tendency to seek the exotic,
and foreign names are exotic.''
   The race to name streets included one called Rabida, (rabid).
Other names: Via Fabricante (Manufacturer Street), El Charco (The
Puddle, near Lake Mission Viejo), and Via Remolino (Whirlpool
Street).
</TEXT>
