<FIRST>r w PM-Jackson-Lucas     05-03 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jackson-Lucas,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Supports Lucas Appointment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil rights activist Jesse Jackson says
``questions remain'' over the appointment of William Lucas to head
the Justice Department's civil rights division, but he supports
Lucas nonetheless.
   Jackson commented after meeting Tuesday with Attorney General
Dick Thornburgh, who said later that he had made ``a pitch'' to
Jackson about Lucas, 61, whose nomination has been opposed by the
NAACP.
   Jackson revealed his attitude toward Lucas only in response to a
reporter's questions, and when asked directly whether he supported
him, Jackson said only, ``Yes.''
   ``I hope that he will honor the trust that the government is
putting in him,'' Jackson said. ``I have reason to believe he
will.''
   The nomination of Lucas, a black Democrat-turned-Republican who
lost a race for governor of Michigan in 1986, has been opposed by
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the
nation's oldest and largest civil rights group.
   Also opposing the nomination is Rep. William H. Gray, D-Pa., who
said he was surprised by Jackson's support.
   ``I don't know why Mr. Jackson said what he said,'' said Gray,
the chairman of the Democratic Caucus.
   Lucas is ``an outstanding human being ... but his public service
has been in law enforcement,'' said Gray.
   ``He is better suited for deputy drug czar or deputy FBI
director, and not as chief policy maker on civil rights enforcement
in the Justice Department in light of no litigatory experience or
policy experience, unless you're making the assumption that anybody
with black skin has the qualifications,'' said Gray, who is black.
``I don't make that assumption and I find it offensive when people
do make that assumption.''
   Lucas, a Detroit lawyer, has been an FBI agent, sheriff of Wayne
County, Mich., and the chief executive for that county. Thornburgh
spokesman Dave Runkel said the assistant attorney general position
``is a law enforcement job and needs someone with a law enforcement
background and management background.''
   Among those supporting Lucas are some members of the
Congressional Black Caucus and the Rev. Joseph Lowery, president of
the Southern Christian Leadership Conference.
   Rep. John Conyers, a black Democrat from Detroit, said a Senate
fight by civil rights groups to block the Lucas nomination ``would
be a useless one, maybe even counterproductive.'' He invited
members of the caucus to meet informally with Lucas on Tuesday
afternoon.
   The nominee spent more than an hour with seven members of the
23-member caucus.
   Jackson said one of the main reasons he visited Thornburgh was
to fight for the rights of sugar cane workers from Jamaica and the
British West Indies.
   ``Because the sugar cane growers have lobbied to exempt sugar
cane as a perishable product, they are less eligible to get their
green cards and are therefore denied access to citizenship in this
country,'' he said.
   Jackson also criticized public housing officials who, following
the leadership of Housing and Urban Development Secretary Jack
Kemp, are evicting innocent people when one family member is
involved with drugs.
   ``I talked to a mother today who has lived in an apartment for
24 years and her son was arrested _ not arrested, indicted, tried
and convicted, just arrested _ and her furniture is on the
street,'' he said.
   Thornburgh told Jackson to talk with Kemp about the situation.
   A HUD spokesman said Kemp ``has been quite cautious in deciding
where waivers should be granted on federal administrative rules
regarding evictions. Those waivers will only be granted in those
states where the due process rights of the tenants will clearly be
protected.''
</TEXT>
