<FIRST>r a PM-ZiptoZap Bjt   05-03 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zip to Zap, Bjt,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>20 Years After, Zapites Brace Again For A `Happening'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Folks in Zap still shudder when they
recall the day 20 years ago when 2,000 drunken college students
rioted on Main Street and set a bonfire, causing $3,000 in damage.
   Saturday, a new generation of students plan a sequel.
   But Denise Schlegel, organizer of Zip to Zap II, promises a more
sedate celebration, one she hopes can erase hard feelings that have
festered in the town of 300 people since 1969.
   ``I want to show them that people are different and things like
this can work out,'' said the 21-year-old junior at North Dakota
State University in Fargo. ``We are mending fences in a way.''
   The school newspaper, The Spectrum, organized the first Zip to
Zap for a spring fling. But chaos erupted that May day and the
National Guard was called in to disperse the rowdy students.
   Although many Zap townspeople are apprehensive about college
students again invading the quiet hamlet, Schlegel, the editor of
The Spectrum, believes Zip to Zap II not only will restore her
newspaper's image. It also will provide an economic boon to the
town about 90 miles northwest of Bismarck.
   ``It all started as a Spectrum picnic in Zap 20 years ago,'' she
said. ``We have gotten a bad rap from it, and I just want to show
that things can work out. People can get together in a gathering
and it doesn't have to be a disaster. ... I don't think the
drinking is the same as it was 20 years ago.''
   Schlegel harbors no fears that Zip to Zap II will get out of
control, calling today's college students more mature and less
radical than their 1960s' counterparts.
   ``I don't think we are going to be starting street fires,'' she
said.
   Schlegel expects up to 1,000 students from campuses across North
Dakota to descend on Zap for 11 hours of free rock 'n' roll plus
some volleyball games.
   Six bands have volunteered for the show, which starts at 1 p.m.
in a pasture near the town, she said.
   Zap is gearing up to handle 2,000 people, said Tammy Schmidt,
president of the Community Club, a civic organization with 20
active members.
   Schmidt, 29, barely remembers the May 10, 1969, event, when she
was living with her family in nearby Beulah, but said: ``Everybody
was scared, seeing it on television.''
   The Mercer County Sheriff's Department expects to have about 15
officers in Zap on Saturday and Highway Patrol officers also will
be around, Deputy Sheriff Dean Nodland said Tuesday. ``We really
don't foresee that ... it is going to get out of hand,'' he said.
   Townspeople in Zap are split on whether another batch of college
revelers should even be let into town, Schmidt said. Some want the
town barricaded. ``They harbor the bad memories,'' she said.
   She doesn't expect a repeat of the disturbance but remains
cautious.
   ``When people are intoxicated, moods swing. If we knew this was
an annual event, we would know what to prepare for. But with a
20-year gap in it, it leaves anything and everything up in the
air,'' Schmidt said.
   The town is hoping to cash in, however. At least seven portable
food stands will be set up, Schmidt said. And the Zap Community
Club had 500 souvenir T-shirts printed with the message:
   ``I Zipped to Zap and had a blast.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
