<FIRST>r w PM-ABA-Judges     05-03 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ABA-Judges,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABA Says no Deal with Thornburgh on Judicial Screening</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh misstated the
position of the American Bar Association when he said its judicial
screening panel has agreed to stop considering the political and
ideological views of candidates for the federal bench, say two
leaders of the organization.
   ABA President Robert Raven and Harold R. Tyler Jr., chairman of
the Standing Committee on Federal Judiciary, both disagreed Tuesday
with Thornburgh's description of what has been produced by
discussions with the attorney general about judicial screening.
   The issue is sensitive because Thornburgh's choice to be deputy
attorney general, Robert B. Fiske Jr., could face tough questioning
by conservative senators about the job he did running the ABA
screening committee.
   Also, there are some 50 vacancies on the federal bench.
   The two ABA officials said there is no agreement with the
Justice Department.
   Tyler said the panel has only ``expressed a willingness'' in
discussions with Thornburgh to delete a clause from the guidelines
that says political views and ideology are not considered ``except
to the extent that they may bear upon the other factors''
considered by the screening panel.
   ``I don't think we have reached any agreement on the exact
language'' of any change to be made, Tyler said.
   Earlier Tuesday, Thornburgh had told the House Judiciary
Committee that the ABA committee during this decade has begun
assessing the ``ideological or political views of prospective
nominees.''
   As a result of discussions, the attorney general said, the ABA
will ``restrict their examination and assessment only to those
areas where they have special expertise.''
   ``We are pleased that the American Bar Association standing
committee has seen fit to withdraw from an area not only
contentious but in my view improper for their consideration _ that
is to say the political and ideological views of the prospective
nominees,'' Thornburgh told the House panel.
   David Runkel, a special assistant to Thornburgh, said that he
understood the agreement was based on an ``exchange of letters''
last week following ``personal discussions between ABA leaders and
top aides to the attorney general.''
   He said the ABA has agreed to return to pre-1979 language that
said ``The committee does not attempt to investigate or report on
political or ideological matters with respect to the prospective
nominee.''
   Tyler said the only letter he is aware of was one he wrote April
4 to the attorney general summarizing their conversation that day.
   Fiske, Thornburgh's choice for his deputy, has not been formally
nominated by President Bush. But Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H.,
charged in an April 17 letter to the president that Fiske shared
the names of prospective nominees with liberal groups,``thus
enabling those groups to target conservative candidates even before
their nominations were made public.''
   At Tuesday's hearing, Thornburgh said the agreement with the ABA
resulted ``through the efforts largely of Robert Fiske.''
   His remark appeared calculated to mollify Humphrey and other
conservatives.
   Tyler said he had discussed the issue and others with Fiske but
``I didn't realize I was in any negotiation.''
   The ABA has been accused by liberals and conservatives of
considering political views when rating a nominee's qualifications
for the judiciary. The rating is delivered during Senate
confirmation hearings.
   Charges from conservatives that the process was being
politicized surfaced in 1987 after the ABA committee disclosed that
four of its 15 members dissented from a recommendation that Robert
Bork was qualified to sit on the Supreme Court.
   Members of the Senate Judiciary Committee in both political
parties have expressed dissatisfaction with the process. Some
senators have called for the ABA committee to reveal the sources of
its information about candidates and how each member voted on a
nominee.
   The Supreme Court is considering a legal claim that the Federal
Advisory Commission Act requires the ABA panel to meet in public.
   Such a requirement, the ABA says, would inhibit its ability to
gather information from professional peers of judicial candidates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
