<HEAD>News Reports Claim U.S. Facility Attacked By Radicals To Close</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Korea, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. cultural center in the
provincial city of Kwangju, attacked 26 times by radical students
since 1981, will be moved and temporarily closed, news reports said
today.
   Gerald McLoughlin said the center that he directs would close
May 10 to move to an as yet undetermined location, according to
Yonhap, the South Korean news agency.
   But officials at the U.S. Embassy denied that the center, 180
miles southwest of Seoul, would close even temporarily. A spokesman
said the question of a new location was still under study in
Washington.
   U.S. officials have been considering a move since early this
year after repeated attacks by radical students yelling anti-U.S.
slogans and hurling firebombs and rocks.
   Anti-U.S. sentiment is relatively high in Kwangju because of the
bloody military suppression of pro-democracy civil uprising there
in May 1980. About 200 people were killed and more than 1,000
others injured in the nine-day uprising.
   Many opposition and dissident figures claim the United States
shares responsibility for the bloodshed by acquiescing to a South
Korean government plan to ruthlessly quell the uprising.
   The United States denies the charges.
</TEXT>
