<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0430EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     05-03 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Advisory Panel Urges OK of Drug to Treat AIDS-Related Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Food and Drug Administration advisory
committee has recommended approval of a drug used to treat an
AIDS-related condition that can lead to blindness.
   Tuesday's approval of the drug ganciclovir was the second AIDS
drug the committee has recommended for approval in two days of
hearings. On Monday, the panel recommended approval of the
aerosolized version of pentamidine to ward off initial and
recurring bouts of pneumocystis carinii pneumonia, which kills 60
percent of AIDS patients.
   The committee's decision was based on new data that found
ganciclovir is effective in treating cytomegalovirus retinitis in
AIDS patients.
   FDA approval of ganciclovir is expected this summer, and
approval of aerosol pentamidine is likely within weeks, said an FDA
source who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   Advocates of programs to fight AIDS have been pushing the FDA to
move quickly on approving the drugs.
   Ganciclovir has been widely available to AIDS patients since
November when the FDA approved use of the drug for treatment of
patients who were in the immediate, sight-threatening stage of
cytomegalovirus retinitis.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Bush Surprises Press, Calls It a Day</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A familiar-sounding voice boomed out over
White House loudspeakers Tuesday evening announcing the end of the
business day.
   It was President Bush, personally announcing he was going home.
   It was the first time in anyone's memory that the president
himself had performed the daily chore.
   ``Ladies and gentlemen of the press, the president having gone
home for the day, there is a lid on,'' Bush said. A ``lid'' is the
term used to tell reporters that no more paperwork or presidential
actions are expected.
   Bush made the announcement while walking from the Oval Office to
his residence in the White House. Noticing a gathering of reporters
hanging around the press office, Bush asked why they were still
there.
   They said they had to wait for him to leave and for the White
House to announce a lid. Bush asked what a lid was, and a reporter
explained the term.
   Usually a lid is announced by a press aide using a telephone
that is hooked up to a White House announcement system. Bush asked
for the telephone and made the announcement himself at 6:40 p.m.
EDT.
   He departed for his quarters as the press cheered his
announcement.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Third World Inflation Jumped to 58.3 Percent in 1988</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices paid by consumers in Third World
countries jumped an average 58.3 percent last year, up from 35.7
percent in 1957, the International Monetary Fund reports.
   The average rise in the United States and 20 other industrial
countries was only 3.3 percent, a rise from 2.9 percent.
   The figures come from a monthly report distributed Tuesday.
   Inflation figures for the Third World were heavily influenced by
Latin America _ Brazil's 682 percent, Argentina's 343 percent and
Mexico's 114 percent. These are the Third World's three biggest
debtors as well.
   Mexico reported a slowdown from last year's 132 percent but
Brazil and Argentina were moving up. Argentina's annual rate was
over 387 percent in December, and Brazil's 1,170 percent in January.
   Nicaragua surpassed them all with 10,205 percent for 1988 and an
annual rate of just under 24,000 percent in December but the
country is too small to count for much in the overall average.
   There was also a rise of inflation in Asia, to 11.6 percent from
7.3 percent. China's rate was up beyond 20 percent, compared less
than 9 percent in 1987.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Consumer Activist Calls For Boycott of Exxon at Gas Pumps.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. ``should not be allowed to
forget'' the Alaskan oil spill, says consumer activist Ralph Nader
in calling for a consumer boycott of the oil company's products.
   Nader joined representatives from several environmental and
consumer groups in denouncing Exxon for its failure to be prepared
for and rapidly respond to the oil spill that has fouled hundreds
of square miles of pristine water and shoreline along Alaska's
southern coast.
   ``Exxon should not be allowed to forget this oil spill,'' said
Nader, suggesting Exxon and the entire petroleum industry must be
made aware of public outrage over the spill.
   ``Americans can take action now by voting with their steering
wheel and dollars against all Exxon products,'' Nader said at a
news conference called in connection with a protest against the oil
company in several cities across the nation.
   An Exxon spokesman, Bill Smith, said in a telephone interview
from New York that more than 10,000 Exxon credit cards have been
turned in since the Alaska spill, but he could not speculate on how
the spill has affected Exxon sales.
