<FIRST>r a PM-Nitze-MissileTalks     05-03 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nitze-Missile Talks,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nitze Criticizes Bush Policy On Short-Range Missiles</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-NATO-Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul H. Nitze, top arms control adviser in the
Reagan administration, says President Bush is missing a strategic
opportunity by refusing to open talks with the Soviets on
short-range nuclear missiles in Europe.
   In an interview in today's New York Times, the 82-year-old
veteran negotiator says talks on cutting back on missiles with a
range of less than 300 miles would actually be in the interest of
the West. They would provide an opportunity to eliminate a large
advantage held by the Soviet Union, he said.
   The Bush administration is pressing for development of a new
generation of short-range nuclear weapons while opposing the
U.S.-Soviet talks demanded by West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
   Nitze terms the administration's approach ``politically
impossible for much of Europe.''
   Nitze has served in a number of national security posts,
including Navy Secretary and Deputy Secretary of Defense. In the
early part of the Reagan administration, he was the chief
negotiator of the treaty to ban intermediate-range nuclear forces
in Europe.
</TEXT>
