<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0450EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Thomas     05-03 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Thomas,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescuer of Wildfowl Dies at 85</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arline Thomas, who became known as the ``bird
lady of Queens'' for rescuing and sheltering wild birds, has died
at age 85.
   Mrs. Thomas died of congestive heart failure Monday at
Huntington Hospital on Long Island.
   Mrs. Thomas treated 200 or more wild birds a year and until
recently was a member of the Audubon Society's volunteer
bird-saving corps. She held federal and state licenses to treat
wild birds. The licenses stipulate that the birds must be released
when they are well.
   She treated her first bird, a one-eyed nuthatch suffering from a
sprained wing, more than 30 years ago. Neighbors in the borough of
Queens soon began to bring her injured birds, and she learned to
care for them properly with help from the New York Zoological
Society's head birdkeeper.
   Between May and September, she would devote about 12 hours a day
to the birds. She had ducks in her bathtub, birds perched on the
edge of mixing bowls when she made cakes, and a bluejay that poked
cashew nuts into the ear of a pet rabbit.
   Mrs. Thomas wrote several books on the care of wild birds,
including ``Bird Ambulance,'' ``Mockingbird Trio,'' and ``Salty.''
   Survivors include a stepson.
</TEXT>
