<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--SewageSpill     05-03 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Sewage Spill,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beaches Shut Because of Huge Spill of Sewage Into Flood Channel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spill of 100,000 gallons of sewage into a
flood control channel triggered a precautionary closure of 3{ miles
of beaches as waste trapped behind sandbag dams was pumped back
into sewers.
   Results of water samples from the beaches were due today, said
Toby Staheli, spokeswoman for the Los Angeles County Department of
Health Services. ``We don't know what, if anything, got into the
ocean,'' she said.
   Beaches were closed Tuesday from the Venice pier south to
Dockweiler State Beach.
   The 100,000 gallons of sewage spilled when a power outage shut
down a pumping station in Inglewood on Monday night, said Don
Avila, a Sanitation Districts spokesman.
   Sewage flowed out of manholes for almost an hour until portable
generators put the plant back in operation, he said.
   The waste went into Centinela Creek, but a sandbag dam was
constructed in the channel to keep it from getting into Ballona
Creek, which flows into the ocean.
   Avila said about 1,000 gallons of waste may have gotten through
the sandbags but it was chlorinated as it passed through.
</TEXT>
