<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0541EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Thatcher     05-03 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thatcher,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Thatcher Reaches 10th Anniversary Of Election That Brought Her
To Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten years ago today an election swept Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher to power, and she continues to prevail
over a divided opposition despite a recent poll indicating a lot of
voters are fed up with her.
   There was no word today from 10 Downing St. of any special
events to mark the anniversary, which television, radio, newspapers
and magazines have marked with numerous programs and articles in
recent weeks.
   Mrs. Thatcher, 63, is the century's longest continuously serving
British prime minister and the headquarters of her Conservative
Party has printed a glossy booklet called ``The First 10 Years''
glowing with praise for her.
   She is now midway through her third term following Conservative
victories in the 1983 and 1987 general elections. Despite
indications of growing dislike among many voters of her
strong-willed personality and right-wing policies, she has said she
plans to try for a fourth term.
   A series of polls released this week indicate most Britons want
Mrs. Thatcher to step down soon and think her right-wing revolution
has gone too far.
   But while they said they don't like her, the likelihood is they
will go on voting for her because they respect the woman who has
always led what The Economist weekly calls a ``reluctant nation.''
   The Economist noted, for example, that virtually throughout Mrs.
Thatcher's tenure, Gallup soundings have never registered more than
24 percent support for a basic Thatcher doctrine: tax cuts rather
than increased state spending, particularly on welfare.
   The soundings published Sunday and Tuesday are part of a
nationwide assessment of ``Thatcherism'' prompted by the
anniversary of the Conservative Party's 1979 election triumph over
Prime Minister James Callaghan's Labor Party government.
   Mrs. Thatcher took office the following day, May 4. Europe's
first woman prime minister had been elected by a nation weary of
strikes and inflation and yearning for strong government to reverse
national decline.
   In the opinion polls, she scored high for qualities such as
determination and courage. Her most popular policies, the polls
showed, are curbing the trade unions and allowing public housing
tenants to buy their homes.
   Britons see their country as having gained respect abroad, while
becoming a more aggressive, violent and selfish society.
   A leader who set out to wipe out socialism from Britain, Mrs.
Thatcher also appears in most soundings to be presiding over a
nation that has not taken her message to its heart.
   A Market and Opinion Research International poll published
Tuesday in The Independent, a London daily, showed only 30 percent
support for the notion that ``private interests and a free market
economy should dominate.''
   According to a Harris poll in London's liberal Observer
newspaper, 58 percent think 10 years of Mrs. Thatcher is enough.
And 66 percent agreed with the statement, ``Mrs. Thatcher has gone
too far in her policies.''
   But just 7 percent of the 1,040 voters questioned by Harris
actually expected Mrs. Thatcher to resign within the next few years.
   The soundings also showed a generally subdued reckoning by
voters of the Thatcher revolution. For example, just 37 percent of
the 1,001 voters questioned by Gallup for the conservative Sunday
Telegraph said they thought that overall Britain is now a better
place to live in.
   And while 67 percent dislike Mrs. Thatcher personally, 63
percent respect her.
   The polls also showed most Britons think the country has become
more violent, citing soccer hooliganism and street crime.
   Mrs. Thatcher, who has won big majorities of around 42 percent
of the vote while the left-of-center is split, continues to be the
party leader most think would be the best prime minister. And when
it comes to casting a vote, she ends the first 10 years with 2 to 3
point lead over Labor in most soundings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
