<FIRST>r a PM-OwlAttack 1stLd-Writethru a0497 05-03 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Owl Attack, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0497,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boy Attacked by Owl May Lose Eye</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, ``The owl ...' to CORRECT to `through' sted `threw'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOWDEN, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A great horned owl swooped down and
scratched the face of a 6-year-old boy riding a bicycle, and
doctors fear he may lose his left eye.
   Tyler Tharp underwent several hours of surgery at University
Hospitals in Iowa City after Friday's attack, and doctors told his
family a decision will be made this week whether they can save the
eye.
   The youngster was listed in fair condition Tuesday.
   A family friend, Jean Oberholser, said Tyler was riding his bike
near his home in Lowden, an eastern Iowa town of 700 people, when
the owl struck.
   ``The owl hit him right in the face and a talon hit him directly
in the eye,'' Ms. Oberholser said. ``It made a T-shaped cut.
Originally, I don't think anyone thought they could save the eye,
but yesterday they said he could see light through it.''
   Craig Jackson of the Iowa Department of Natural Resources said
the attack probably was made by a female owl protecting her young.
   ``We can't verify it, but we assume there was a baby owl on the
ground when the youngster went by on the sidewalk,'' he said.
``Whenever young are around, animals become very protective. But
I've never heard of great horned owls attacking someone to this
extent.''
   Jackson said authorities destroyed both owl parents, not knowing
which one attacked and fearing the bird might attack again. He also
said officials were forced to destroy the offspring.
   Great horned owls, named for their large ear tufts, are
protected birds but are not considered endangered or threatened.
</TEXT>
