<HEAD>Charles Evers Loses Bid for Fifth Term as Mayor of Fayette, Miss.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAYETTE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Evers, the first black mayor of an
integrated Mississippi town since Reconstruction, lost his bid for
re-election to a fifth term.
   Former Mayor Kenny Middleton defeated Evers, 390-248, in
Tuesday's Democratic primary. Middleton will face independent
William E. Smith in June's general election.
   ``I feel fine. I'm relieved,'' said Evers, who did not actively
campaign. ``It was time for a change. ... I could feel the people
wanted a change, but I didn't want to quit.''
   Evers' brother, Medgar, was shot to death in an ambush in
Jackson during the 1960s while serving as field director for the
state NAACP.
