<FIRST>r a PM-SecondAbduction     05-03 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Second Abduction,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Expect Suspect Will Tip Hand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators trying to solve the second
reported baby abduction from the same family in three years have
released a cryptic bit of information about the likely, but so far
unknown, suspect.
   Police Sgt. Rick McCain said the FBI's National Center for
Analysis of Violent Crime came up with a psychological profile of
the person responsible.
   ``We've been led to believe that the perpetrator will suffer
severe anxiety as time passes,'' McCain said, ``and this will be
manifested in behavior the subject will be unable to control. It's
my feeling that it will make this person known to police.''
   McCain, the department's chief of detectives, refused to
elaborate on what kind of behavior might be expected or how
investigators might spot it.
   And he refused to say why police released that part of the
report.
   McCain said police still had hopes for the safe return of
6-week-old Heather Sims, whose parents, Robert and Paula Sims, said
she was abducted by a masked, armed intruder at their home Saturday
night.
   He said investigators have found no evidence disproving the
parents' story, that for the second time in three years a masked
gunman abducted their baby daughter.
   ``There's nothing to indicate that the Sims are anything but
victims at this time,'' McCain said.
   Their 13-day-old daughter, Loralei, disappeared under almost
identical circumstances in 1986.
   Loralei's body was found five days later, about 150 feet from
the couple's home in Brighton. No cause of death was determined and
no arrest was made in the case, although investigators at the time
said the parents were suspects.
   Dr. Janis Robinson, a pediatrician who examined Heather on April
22, said the baby had been in good health and there was nothing
unusual in the way Mrs. Sims had handled her.
   Detectives returned to the Simses' neighborhood Tuesday, asking
neighbors whether they had seen or heard anything that could help.
   ``We haven't found anyone who saw the alleged assailant, but
that doesn't mean there wasn't one,'' McCain said.
   The Simses have refused to talk to reporters.
</TEXT>
