<FIRST>r i PM-Marcos'Mother     05-03 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos' Mother,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Anniversary Of Death With No Burial In Sight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATAC, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials in the Marcos family's
hometown have a ``day of mourning'' for Thursday's first
anniversary of the death of Ferdinand Marcos' mother, whose body
still lies in an open casket.
   The Marcoses refuse to bury Josefa Edralin-Marcos, who died May
4, 1988, until President Corazon Aquino allows her deposed
predecessor to return from Hawaiian exile for the funeral.
   There's no indication the 95-year-old woman's body will be
buried anytime soon.
   Jesus Nalupta, mayor of this town of about 40,000 people that is
250 miles north of Manila, said today that the municipal council
declared the day of mourning because ``everybody is still
grieving.''
   But he said no special ceremonies were scheduled apart from
Roman Catholic Masses, which have been said nearly every day since
Mrs. Edralin-Marcos' body was brought last year from Manila, where
she died.
   Her body has been lying in an open casket in the Marcos
ancestral home, which has been turned into a museum.
   The wake has attracted an unusual assortment of Marcos
supporters, tourists, curiosity-seekers and a cult of religious
fanatics, who believe Marcos is ``the second son of God.''
   Mrs. Aquino has cited national security in refusing to allow
Marcos to return from Hawaii, where he has lived since he was
ousted in a popular uprising three years ago.
   Marcos has been hospitalized since January with heart and
bronchial ailments, and his followers say he is dying.
   Nalupta and many others here in Marcos' home province of Ilocos
Norte believe the former president should be allowed to return,
both to bury his mother and die in his homeland.
   ``We have given up all hopes that the Aquino government would
allow Marcos to come home,'' said Congressman Mariano Nalupta, a
brother of the mayor. ``We have given it to the will of God.''
   Frank Malabed, the Marcos family's mortician, said it has cost
the former president's family about $950 a month to continue the
wake, including charges for flowers, embalming supplies and changes
in clothing.
   Malabed said he inspects the body periodically and adds more
embalming fluid every two months. He said the lengthy, highly
publicized wake has been great for his business.
</TEXT>
