<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0631EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Fusion     05-03 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientist Use Poems, Visuals to Illustrate Cold Fusion Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX DOMINGUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Physicists are resorting to poems and visual
aids like a blade of grass to help illustrate the problems they
found in two chemists' claim of achieving nuclear fusion in a jar.
   ``Tens of millions of dollars are at stake, dear sister and
brother, because one scientist put a thermometer in one place
instead of the other,'' Walter Meyerhof of Stanford University
recited to reporters Tuesday at a meeting of the American Physical
Society.
   Meyerhof said the excess heat that the researchers attribute to
cold fusion was caused instead by incorrect temperature
measurements. He said the device the researchers used failed to
distribute temperature evenly.
   University of Utah chemist B. Stanley Pons and his collaborator,
Martin Fleischmann of Britain's University of Southampton, startled
the world March 23 by announcing they had achieved fusion at room
temperature.
   Most efforts to achieve fusion, the nuclear reaction that powers
the sun, have required staggeringly high temperatures. Cold fusion
could open the door to a clean, cheap and virtually unlimited
source of energy.
   Pons and Fleischmann said they did it by placing palladium and
platinum electrodes in a flask of deuterium oxide, or heavy water,
and applying electric current. Deuterium is a heavier isotope, or
cousin, of ordinary hydrogen.
   The researchers claimed the nuclei of the deuterium atoms fused,
releasing neutrons and producing four times more heat than invested.
   But in an informal show of hands, the scientists on a panel at
the American Physical Society meeting Tuesday voted 8-1 that they
were 95 percent confident the excess heat was not produced by
nuclear fusion.
   However, the panel also voted 6-3 against ruling out that
experiments in Utah and elsewhere had produced neutrons.
   ``The bottom line is we see nothing anomalous in any of their
experiments and have identified what we believe are serious errors
in the experiment,'' said Steven Koonin of the California Institute
of Technology.
   Koonin was part of a three-member Caltech team that tried to
duplicate the Utah experiments.
   Fred Skiff, a University of Maryland physicist, said that after
attempting to duplicate the results for two weeks he was certain
cold fusion had not taken place.
   ``It appears the work by Pons and Fleischmann is very sloppy,''
Skiff said. ``They should have presented their research in the
scientific community before going public with it,'' he said. ``The
public debate on this matter makes science look bad because of the
complicated process of verification.''
   One of the few physicists to hold out hope for cold fusion,
Brigham Young University's Steve Jones, said his experiments had
produced neutrons but at a level much lower than the University of
Utah experiment claimed. Cold fusion needs further study, but is
only a little understood effect, he said.
   He used a blade of grass to illustrate his point.
   ``I don't think it will grow into a tree,'' Jones said. ``I
think it will grow into a pleasant little flower in the garden of
physics.''
   Pons and Fleishmann have not responded in detail to this week's
criticism in Baltimore.
   But Pons did say: ``The absence of neutrons does not concern us
in the slightest. We couldn't be happier. We and other scientists
will soon tell them why this is so.''
   University of Utah officials also defended the research.
   ``It's difficult for me to believe people of Pons' and
Fleischmann's caliber could forget to put a thermometer in the
right place or something basic like stirring,'' said John Brophy,
the university's vice president for research. ``It doesn't shake my
confidence. It's never nice to be criticized. However, when you're
out in front, the wind can be cool sometimes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
