<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-03 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms in Texas, Chilly Morning In Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms moved across northern Texas today, dumping heavy
rain and hail, while Midwesterners awoke to another chilly morning.
   The most severe thunderstorms were near Ranger, Texas, where
funnel clouds were spotted Tuesday night. The town is about 70
miles southwest of Fort Worth.
   Baseball-sized hail fell near the town, the National Weather
Service said.
   Heavy wind blew over two semi-trailer trucks on Interstate 20
near Ranger, authorities said.
   Also in Texas, thunderstorm winds destroyed a barn in northern
Parker County, tore off a roof of a country club and overturned
several mobile homes in Comanche County. Winds were recorded up to
80 mph.
   Thunderstorms also were over southern Arkansas and central
Mississippi.
   Rain showers developed from Montana to central Colorado, and
showers fell over the lower Great Lakes region.
   Waco, Texas, had more than an inch of rain in the six hours
ending at 2 a.m. EDT, while Limestone, Maine, and Cleveland each
recorded nearly two-thirds of an inch in the same period.
   A high pressure system with a cold air mass was centered over
northern Missouri, creating chilly temperatures from the upper and
middle Mississippi Valley across the Great Lakes and the Ohio
Valley to the Appalachians.
   North Carolina's northern mountains had a frost warning today.
   The high temperature in the nation Tuesday was 102 in two
California communities _ Borrego Springs and Palm Springs.
   Today's forecast: showers and thunderstorms extending from the
lower Mississippi and lower Tennessee valleys across Oklahoma, the
central Plains, and western portions of the northern Plains to the
northern and central Rockies; showers from New England to western
Pennsylvania; snow showers in the higher elevations of western New
York and western Pennsylvania, where high temperatures were
expected in the 40s.
   Elsewhere, high temperatures were to be in the 50s from Michigan
to the northern and central Appalachians, and over Montana; in the
80s over Florida, Louisiana, much of Texas, New Mexico, central
Arizona and interior California; and in the 90s to near 100 over
southwest Texas and the desert Southwest. Much of the rest of the
nation was to have high temperatures in the 60s and 70s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 29
degrees in Marquette, Mich., to 81 degrees in Glendale, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 50 fair; Boston 52 partly cloudy; Buffalo 42
cloudy; Charleston, S.C., 57 fair; Cincinnati 36 fair; Cleveland 44
drizzle; Detroit 38 fair; Miami 75 fair; New York 50 fair;
Philadelphia 50 fair; Pittsburgh 42 cloudy; Portland, Maine, 47
fair; Washington 53 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 44 fair; Chicago 43 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 61 partly cloudy; Denver 48 rain; Des Moines 44
fair; Indianapolis 39 fair; Kansas City 45 foggy; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 47 partly cloudy; Nashville 52 cloudy; New Orleans 64 fair;
St. Louis 47 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 57 fair; Anchorage 50 cloudy; Las Vegas 73
partly cloudy; Los Angeles 61 fair; Phoenix 76 fair; Salt Lake City
53 cloudy; San Diego 60 cloudy; San Francisco 57 fair; Seattle 51
fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 45 cloudy; Toronto 41 cloudy.
