<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Jews     05-03 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Jews,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emigration Highest Since 1979, But Less Bound for Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union in April
soared to its highest level in 10 years, according to figures
released today by an agency that helps to resettle the emigrants.
   However, the share of those bound for Israel fell to a new low.
   Regina Boucault, spokeswoman of the Geneva-based
Intergovernmental Committee for Migration, said 4,129 Jews arrived
at the Vienna transit center from the Soviet Union in April,
compared with 3,893 in March.
   Only 87 of them, or 2.1 percent, said they wanted to go to
Israel. Most were heading for the United States, said Ms. Boucault.
   Last year the share of Soviet Jews bound for Israel was still
7.1 percent. In 1987, before the Palestinian uprising in the West
Bank and the Gaza strip it was as high as 24.4 percent.
   Since the beginning of 1989, 12,864 Jews have left the Soviet
Union, according to ICM figures.
   On Tuesday, the Washington-based National Conference on Soviet
Jewry reported an emigration total of 4,557 Jews for April. The ICM
figures only account for those Soviet Jews who pass through Vienna.
   The program for Jewish emigration from Soviet Union began in
1971 and reached a peak in 1979 when 51,328 were allowed to leave
the country. This dropped sharply when Soviet intervention in
Afghanistan chilled East-West relations.
</TEXT>
