<FIRST>r i PM-Netherlands 1stLd-Writethru   05-03 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Netherlands, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0486,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clash Over Anti-Pollution Plan Brings Down Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: ADDs one graf to UPDATE with representation in Dutch parliament.
^By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disagreement over a
multibillion-dollar plan to clean up the country's environment has
brought down the 7-year-old center-right government of Prime
Minister Ruud Lubbers.
   The Christian Democrat on Tuesday announced the resignation of
his Cabinet after a right-wing junior partner objected to his
proposal to end $325 million in income tax deductions for people
who drive their cars to work.
   Political observers predicted Lubbers would form a coalition
with the Dutch Labor Party, second only to the Christian Democrats
in the number of parliamentary seats it holds.
   Lubbers' action headed off a possible motion of no confidence
threatened by the junior coalition partner, the People's Party for
Freedom and Democracy.
   ``Environmental policy certainly needs to be paid for, but why
just by those who live at some distance from their jobs?'' said
Joris Voorhoeve, the right-wing party's leader in the 150-seat
Parliament.
   Lubbers' announcement came at the end of a tense 7{-hour
parliamentary debate on a $3.65 billion government plan to cut
pollution of the country's atmosphere to 30 percent of current
levels by the year 2010.
   ``If only we could motivate one in ten (car-driving commuters)
to change their habits ... that would have a very large effect on
the congestion, on mobility, on the environment,'' Lubbers said.
   The crisis also reflected years of irritation among Voorhoeve's
party at steadily losing decision-making power to the charismatic
Lubbers, who enjoys immense popularity in this nation of 14.6
million people.
   The 49-year-old prime minister said he planned to meet with
Queen Beatrix today ``to offer the resignation of all the
ministers'' in the Cabinet.
   In Dutch constitutional practice, the government will continue
in office with caretaker status until early elections later this
year. After the elections, it can take several months until a new
government is formed.
   Parliamentary elections had been scheduled for May 1990.
   The Christian Democrats have been in virtually every postwar
Dutch government and are likely to be the centerpiece of the next
one.
   Never in postwar Dutch history has a political party garnered
sufficient votes to govern alone.
   The 8-year-old Lubbers government has aimed to cut the $13
billion budget deficit and 11 percent unemployment rate.
   In recent months, the People's Party has accused Lubbers' party
of backing off from a pledge to cut corporate and private taxes and
slash social security, education and health care outlays.
   But the issue that prompted the government's resignation was a
Lubbers proposal to end the tax break for car-driving commuters in
a bid to reduce car exhaust fumes and highway congestion by forcing
motorists to take mass transit. Voorhoeve also objected to a
proposed $270 million increase in the tax on diesel fuel that would
mainly hit the trucking industry, one of the mainstays of the Dutch
economy.
   Under the anti-pollution plan, farmers also would have to pay
toward cleaning up deposits of manure produced by their livestock,
deposits that contribute to acid rain.
   The plan would set levies for polluting industries and contain
proposals for cleaning up hundreds of toxic waste dumps.
   Voorhoeve's move to topple the government had the support of the
52-seat Labor Party opposition, and the 54 Christian Democrats
would not have been able to hold off a no-confidence vote.
   The People's Party has 27 seats in Parliament, while 12 seats
are held by three opposition parties and five seats by three
right-wing parties that are generally supportive of the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0721EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Cambodia     05-03 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Sets Conditions to Return to Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the Vietnamese troop pullout from
Cambodia is independently confirmed and the constitution rewritten
to his satisfaction, Prince Norodom Sihanouk says he will return
home as head of state.
   Sihanouk, leader of the guerrilla coalition resisting the
Vietnamese-backed government, said today that he expects to decide
before November if his conditions have been met.
   He made the comments at a news conference on the second day of
peace talks in Jakarta.
   An international commission, to be named at a conference in
Paris on July 24-25, must first make sure the Vietnamese withdrawal
is genuine, Sihanouk said. Hanoi has promised to pull out its
remaining troops by Sept. 30.
   Sihanouk's other demands include a four-party interim government
in Phnom Penh until elections can be held, and constitutional
guarantees for a multiparty political system.
   The proposed interim administration would include the present
Cambodian government of Premier Hun Sen, Sihanouk's non-communist
followers, anti-communists from former Premier Son Sann's Khmer
People's National Liberation Front and the Communist Khmer Rouge.
   Hun Sen has been trying to persuade Sihanouk to abandon the
Khmer Rouge and return home as head of the the government he headed
until being ousted in 1970.
   The Khmer Rouge, which came to power in 1975 and was forced out
by the invading Vietnamese in 1978, is not represented at the
talks. Sihanouk said no support could be expected from them
following the Jakarta talks.
   ``The Khmer Rouge will reject everything because they are
interested in the continuation of the war,'' he said.
   The fanatical Khmer Rouge is accused of killing hundreds of
thousands of people during its bloody reign. Hun Sen, Sihanouk and
their allies insist that Pol Pot and other leaders of the original
``genocidal clique'' be barred from any future government.
   The Khmer Rouge, the largest Cambodian guerrilla group, today
rejected any conciliatory moves by the Vietnamese-installed
government, saying they should be thrown ``into the dustbin.''
   The Khmer Rouge radio was commenting on the constitutional
amendments the pro-Vietnamese government adopted Sunday.
   In concessions to Sihanouk, Hun Sen had changed the country's
name from People's Republic of Kampuchea to the State of Cambodia,
as well as changed its flag and anthem and promised several changes
to the constitution.
   These are merely part of efforts to legitimize the regime, the
Khmer Rouge broadcast said. A text of Tuesday's broadcast was
obtained today in Bangkok.
   The radio complained that the government had changed its outer
shell but ``the true nature remains a Vietnamese puppet, socialist
regime.''
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
said Tuesday that close ties with a future Cambodian government
would not be possible if it were heavily influenced by the Khmer
Rouge.
   Sihanouk said the Sino-Soviet summit in Beijing in mid-May
should be beneficial to his cause.
   He said Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev ``may put some
moral pressure on Hun Sen'' and the Chinese leadership might apply
pressure on the Khmer Rouge to seek a settlement in the 10-year-old
conflict.
   China is the primary military backer of the Khmer Rouge.
</TEXT>
