<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0811EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Pope     05-03 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Visits Depressed Mining Region Of Zambia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KITWE, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II traveled today to the
depressed Copperbelt mining region of central Zambia, one of
Africa's poorest and most indebted nations.
   The pope conducted a two-hour, open-air Mass at an abandoned
airport at Kitwe, the second-largest city in this southern African
nation of 7.5 million people, three-fourths of whom are Christian.
   In the near distance, behind the Papal podium, smoke stacks at a
copper smelting plant billowed black smoke into clear tropical
skies.
   Church choirs sang hymns to the throb of African tribal drums as
the pontiff, in an open ``popemobile'' rode through a crowd of
100,000 pilgrims.
   A hymn, written for the Mass in the local Bemba dialect,
described the pope as ``our hero.'' With arms outstretched, John
Paul blessed groups of women chanting and ululating, a traditional
means of expressing joy.
   John Paul, his face reddened by the tropical sun, paid tribute
to white priests who set up the first Roman Catholic missions in
Zambia nearly 100 years ago. Today, there are 1.7 million Catholics
in Zambia.
   Tens of thousands of pilgrims, mainly from northern districts of
this nation, waved yellow-and-white Vatican flags and wore
sari-like cloths emblazoned with John Paul's portrait.
   Bishop Dennis de Jong of the Copperbelt diocese of Ndola that
covers Kitwe said in a brief welcoming statement that the pope is
visiting the mining region at a time of economic hardships.
   The fall in world copper prices left Zambia with ``an enormous
national debt,'' severe unemployment and social problems, he said.
   Copper prices slumped in the 1970s. Current foreign debt of $5
billion drains about two-fifths of all export income, 90 percent of
which is derived from sales of copper.
   On his arrival in Lusaka, Zambia on Tuesday, John Paul lashed
out at white-ruled South Africa's system of apartheid or racial
separation, describing it as an unacceptable system.
   Zambian President Kenneth Kaunda, in his welcoming speech, also
assailed apartheid and said the pope's visit would strengthen
Zambia's resolve to work for peace in southern Africa ``in a spirit
of dialogue and reconciliation and not confrontation.''
   Kaunda, 65, is chairman of the African Frontline States, a
grouping of six black countries spearheading efforts to end
apartheid.
   Leaders of the African National Congress, the main
guerrilla-backed movement fighting South Africa's government, have
said they would like to meet the pope while he is in Lusaka, the
ANC's external headquarters.
   Vatican officials said no talks were planned, but they did not
rule out the prospect of an informal meeting.
   The pope is on the third leg of a four-nation tour of African
and Indian Ocean states. He leaves Zambia on Thursday for
neighboring Malawi.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
