<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-PLO 1stLd-Writethru a0504 05-03 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0504,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat's Representative Remains In Coma After Operation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with guerrilla killed. Pickup 2nd,
``A spokesman...'' Inserts 3 grafs after 10th pvs, ``That was ...'' to
UPDATE with Israel accused. Pickup 11th pvs, ``Arafat, a...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat's
representative to Lebanon remained in a coma today but was reported
in stable condition a day after being shot in the head by a masked
gunman.
   Another guerrilla from Arafat's mainline Fatah faction was
killed today as he drove his motorcycle down a main street in
Sidon. Bassam Hourani, 30, ``died instantly from several shot
wounds in the head and chest,'' said a police spokesman. The gunman
escaped.
   A spokesman at Hammoud Hospital said Arafat's representative,
48-year-old Issam Salem, survived a five-hour operation to remove a
bullet that pierced the left side of his forehead in an
assassination attempt Tuesday.
   ``The operation was a success. Mr. Salem is in stable condition
but still in coma. However, we won't know if we can take him off
the critical list for at least 48 hours,'' the spokesman said. He
declined to be named.
   Salem was the second high-ranking PLO official to become the
target of an assassination attempt in Sidon within four days.
   Police said a lone assailant, wearing a plastic mask and armed
with a 9mm pistol, fired two bullets into Salem's head and shoulder
at a gift store in this port city's Fakhreddin Street.
   The gunman escaped through narrow alleyways leading to the
Palestinian refugee camp of Ein El-Hilweh on Sidon's southern
flank, according to police.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization security department and
the Nasserite leftist Moslem militia that governs Sidon said they
launched a joint hunt for the gunman. But spokesmen for both groups
said no arrests were made.
   There was no claim of responsibility for the attempt against
Salem or the rocket-propelled grenade attack Saturday on the house
of Zeid Wehbi, the PLO spokesman in Sidon.
   Arafat, on an official visit in France, called the attack on
Salem ``a message for us to put up our hands and stop helping our
Lebanese brothers.''
   That was interpreted by Christian-controlled radio stations in
Beirut as an accusation against Syria, whose forces have been
locked in heavy artillery duels with Christian units of the
Lebanese army in the past seven weeks.
   Wehbi, however, blamed Israel's secret service.
   He told reporters the attack was designed to ``deal a blow to
Lebanese-Palestinian coexistence in the Sidon region.''
   Wehbi charged Israel is launching ``a wave of assassination
attempts against our brethren.''
   Arafat, a staunch foe of Syrian President Hafez Assad, had
declared support for the Christians in the latest round of
Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war that has claimed almost 300 lives.
   But Arafat's estimated 5,000 guerrillas who have returned to the
Sidon region after his evacuation from Lebanon during Israel's 1982
invasion have taken no active part in the fighting.
   Sidon, Lebanon's third largest city 25 miles south of Beirut, is
the PLO's main power base in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
