<HEAD>Woman Charges Opry Star With Assault</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts 2nd graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALLATIN, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman has charged Grand Ole Opry star
Bill Monroe with assault and battery, alleging the 77-year-old
entertainer hit her with a Bible, knocked her down and kicked her.
   Wanda Huff, of Birmingham, Ala., filed a criminal complaint in
Sumner County General Sessions Court on Monday.
   Monroe, known as the ``father of bluegrass music,'' was released
on his own recognizance pending a preliminary hearing next
Wednesday.
   Ms. Huff alleged that Monroe struck her when she went to his
farm to recover property that belonged to her, according to a court
complaint.
   ``While she (Ms. Huff) was there, defendant Monroe became angry,
hit her in the face with a Bible, knocked her down, kicked her in
the face,'' the complaint said.
   Tony Conway, an executive at Music Row's Buddy Lee Attractions,
which handles bookings for Monroe, said the singer told him that
Ms. Huff started destroying property at his house.
   ``He asked her to leave several times and she refused to
leave,'' Conway said. ``Mr. Monroe called the police, the police
came to the house, took statements from both parties, and I guess
she filed charges against him.
   ``He did state that he's totally shocked and that he's never
been arrested for anything in his life.''
   Sumner County Chief Deputy J.D. Vandercook said that Monroe
called officers to his home.
   ``Any citizen of Sumner County or of the United States has the
right to obtain a warrant,'' Vandercook said. ``Her testimony will
have to be weighed against his in General Sessions Court.''
   Reached at her home, Ms. Huff said she has known Monroe ``a
pretty good while. ... He's a wonderful musician and a wonderful
songwriter, but he's got a mean streak down his back.''
   No one answered a telephone call to Monroe's office this morning.
   Monroe won a Grammy award this year for ``Southern Flavor,''
under the first-time bluegrass music category. He is a member of
the Country Music Hall of Fame and has played at the Opry for 50
years.
