<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Stabbing 4thLd-Writethru a0527 05-03 0820</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Stabbing, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0527,0838</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab Fatally Stabs Two Israelis, Wounds Three Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with former member of Moslem fundamentalist
group arrested in stabbing, police stop protest by Jews, arrest Kahane.
No pickup. ^By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian shouting ``God is great'' stabbed
to death two elderly Israelis waiting at a bus stop in downtown
Jerusalem today, police said. Three other Israelis were seriously
injured in the attack.
   Dozens of angry passers-by chased the short, stocky assailant
about 30 yards and caught him after a brief struggle. Police pinned
the Arab to the ground in a nearby flower shop to protect him from
the crowd.
   Police said the man, a 25-year-old resident of the West Bank
town of Ramallah, acted alone. Israel radio said the attacker was a
former member of a Moslem fundamentalist group, and police said he
had been questioned about unspecified ``terrorist activities'' in
the past.
   The attack came one day after PLO leader Yasser Arafat disavowed
the 25-year-old PLO charter, which calls for the destruction of
Israel. His announcement in Paris prompted protests from radical
Palestinian factions.
   The stabbings further escalated Arab-Jewish tensions in
Jerusalem, already at a breaking point after 17 months of
Palestinian rebellion against Israeli rule in the occupied lands.
Nearly 460 Palestinians and 20 Israelis have been killed since the
uprising began in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The stabbings occurred around 11 a.m. across from Jerusalem's
main post office on Jaffa Road, the main shopping street in Jewish
west Jerusalem.
   Police reinforcements, including mounted horse patrols, rushed
to the scene to control groups of angry Israelis who shouted
``Death to the terrorists!'' and ``Death to the Arabs!''
   About three hours after the stabbing, police fired tear gas to
disperse dozens of followers of Rabbi Meir Kahane's anti-Arab Kach
Party who shouted ``revenge, revenge.'' The group was en route to
the Western Wall, Judaism's holiest site, to stage a protest when
it was halted by police.
   Kahane, who is from Brooklyn, N.Y., and who founded the Jewish
Defense League in the United States, was arrested along with six of
his followers. They were charged with disturbing public order.
   Police Minister Chaim Bar-Lev urged restraint. ``I hope it won't
prompt extremists from our side to react because that could bring
about a vicious cycle,'' Bar-Lev said on Israel radio.
   Romi Shimon, who was sitting in a Jaffa Road restaurant, said
the assailant was shouting ``God is Great'' when he attacked five
Israelis at the bus stop, four of them elderly. ``He was going
crazy and started stabbing people. We caught him at the end of the
street,'' Shimon told Israel radio.
   Sima Ozer, an employee in the Newman Flower Shop across from the
post office on Jaffa Road, said the short, stocky Arab was carrying
a blood-covered eight-inch knife as he was being chased.
   ``Then a policeman came and stopped the crowd from lynching
him,'' she said. ``Police threw him on the floor of the flower shop
... while people outside were shouting `kill him, kill him, death
to the Arabs.'''
   At one point during the chase, she said she heard a gun shot. A
reporter saw blood on the floor of the flower shop.
   Minutes later, the crowd chased a Palestinian teen-ager wearing
a white kaffiyeh headdress. Two policemen whisked him away to
safety.
   Vardi Kalman, 60, was taken to a nearby souvenir shop where he
later died of his wounds. Hundreds of onlookers crowded the shop
entrance, and the body, wrapped in a white sheet, was carried to an
ambulance.
   Nissim Levy, 91, died of wounds at Hadassah Hospital which was
also treating a woman in her 90s. Bikur Holim Hospital reported
treating two men, one 64 and the other a 25-year-old Jewish
seminary student, for stab wounds in the stomach and chest.
   Police Commissioner David Krauss said the assailant appeared to
have no accomplices.
   Police spokesman Uzi Sandori said the assailant had spent the
night praying at Jerusalem's Al Aqsa mosque to mark Leilat al Kadr,
the night the Moslem holy book Koran was received by the Prophet
Mohammed. He said the man had a record of being detained and
questioned about anti-Israeli acts in the past.
   Police did not say if the attacker operated under orders from a
group or initiated the attack on his own.
   The army sealed the assailant's hometown, Ramallah, setting up
roadblocks on main roads, Arab reporters said. Troops detained
dozens of Palestinian youths after ordering them off buses and
taxis, they said.
   Arafat's announcement in Paris on Tuesday prompted immediate
protests from radical Palestinians, including the Marxist Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine of George Habash. Slogans
painted on walls in the West Bank town of Nablus said, ``Down with
the betrayer Arafat.'' Last year, the United States opened talks
with the PLO after Arafat recognized Israel's right to exist.
</TEXT>
