<FIRST>r a PM-AbusedBoy     05-03 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abused Boy,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police, Neighbors Say Boy Who Died After Beating Was Abused Daily</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has been charged with beating to
death a 3{-year-old boy who police say lived ``a life of torture''
from almost daily physical abuse.
   A relative and two neighbors witnessed some of the abuse but
none contacted authorities, The Boston Globe reported in today's
editions.
   Neighbors and police said Randolph Scott, 38, beat the boy,
Hanif Sutton, with his fists, a belt or sneakers and forced the
child to stand in the bathroom for long periods in uncomfortable
positions.
   Scott was being held without bail in East Cambridge Jail today
on charges of first-degree murder, five counts of assault and
battery and one count of deriving support from a prostitute.
   Police said the abuse culminated in a beating Saturday. On
Monday, Hanif died at Children's Hospital in Boston of trauma to
the head. When he was admitted to the hospital on Saturday, he was
suffering swelling and bleeding of the brain, a ruptured spleen and
bruises, said John McEvoy, a Middlesex County assistant district
attorney.
   ``The baby was leading a life of torture,'' said Police Capt.
John Cullen.
   Cullen said Scott is a heroin addict whose habit was supported
by the boy's mother, Rosalyn Rochester, through prostitution. ``She
kept nothing for herself and nothing for the baby,'' Cullen said.
   A social worker from the state Department of Social Services
regularly visited the apartment where the boy lived. A spokeswoman,
Lorraine Carli, said the agency was concerned about neglect but was
unaware of any abuse of the boy. ``This is very frightening to us.
It is an unexpected, unpredictable explosion of violence,'' she
said.
   John Rivera, a neighbor living downstairs from Ms. Rochester and
her son, told the Globe, ``It goes back for months. He beat the kid
every day. I could hear the kid screaming and fighting.
   ``My old lady said tey were just wrestling, but when you wrestle
with a kid there is laughing and giggling. I never heard laughing.
I feel bad I never called someone ... but (Scott) was into dope and
I didn't want to get into trouble,'' Rivera said.
   Another neighbor, Brenda Martin, said Hanif was often beaten for
urinating in his pants, and an unnamed relative of Scott's said she
saw burns on Hanif's back, the Globe reported.
   The Social Services' case was opened after an anonymous report
of medical neglect Jan. 26, three days after Scott was released
from the Billerica House of Correction where he had been held for
assault and robbery, the Globe said.
</TEXT>
