<FIRST>r a PM-AuctionSeason     05-03 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auction Season,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Prices Bid for Contemporary Artworks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Works by 27 contemporary artists fetched record
prices as the annual spring art-buying frenzy got under way at
Sotheby's auction house.
   Reflecting a trend in the art world, about a fourth of the
buyers Tuesday were Japanese, said Lucy Mitchell Innes, a Sotheby's
spokeswoman.
   Among the records was $11.5 million for a Jackson Pollock drip
painting that the buyer felt was a bargain.
   ``I was extremely pleased to get it at what many in the trade
feel is a very advantageous price,'' said Jeffrey Deitch, who
bought ``Number 8, 1950,'' for an anonymous collector. ``Sometimes
you just get lucky.''
   The previous record for a Pollock painting was $5.72 million
last year for his ``Frieze.''
   Tuesday's sale, with total receipts of $78.6 million, was a
record for a contemporary art auction.
   Tuesday's auction kicked off 12 days of selling at Sotheby's and
Christie's, two of the world's biggest auction houses. More than
4,400 artworks are expected to be sold for a total of $572 million.
   ``Triptych May-June,'' done by Francis Bacon in 1973, inspired
by the suicide of a close friend of the artist, sold for $6.2
million. The record for Bacon was $1.76 million in 1987 for ``Study
for Portrait II.''
   Five sculptures with tasty themes by Claes Oldenburg also sold:
``Ice Cream Sandwich,'' $407,000; ``Plate of Meat,'' $396,000;
``Bacon and Egg,'' $495,000; ``Cheesecake from Javatime,'' $52,250;
and ``Green Beans,'' $264,000.
   Andy Warhol's ``Red Jackie,'' which portrays a ruby-lipped
Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis as first lady in 1963, sold for
$750,000, more than twice the presale estimate.
   All prices include a 10 percent house commission.
   Next Tuesday, Sotheby's sale of impressionist and modern
paintings and sculpture will feature Gauguin's ``Mata Mua,'' circa
1892, completed during the artist's first trip to Tahiti. Estimated
at $20 million to $25 million, it is being sold by Jaime
Ortiz-Patino, heir to a Bolivian tin fortune, and Baron Hans
Heinrich Thyssen-Bornemisza, a member of the advisory board of
Sotheby's Holdings.
   The same day, ``Yo Picasso,'' a 1901 self-portrait done in Paris
during the artist's blue period, is expected to command $15 million
to $20 million. It is being sold by Wendell Cherry, president and
chief executive officer of Humana Inc., the hospital management
corporation based in Louisville, Ky.
   Another Warhol portrait, ``Red Marilyn,'' a 1964 depiction of
Marilyn Monroe, will be offered Wednesday at Christie's. The
estimate for the silkscreen work is $1.5 million to $2 million.
</TEXT>
