<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 1047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Hinckley-Lawyer 1stLd-Writethru a0471 05-03 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hinckley-Lawyer, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0471,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Assassination Expert Says He Won't Exploit Hinckley</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 8 grafs new to lead with Hinckley wanting to leave country;
picks up 7th graf pvs, Hinckley received.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential assailant John W. Hinckley Jr.
wants to leave the country with his fiancee, says assassination
expert Mark Lane, whom Hinckley has asked to represent him.
   Lane said Hinckley, 33, wants to start a new life abroad with
formal mental patient Leslie deVeau, who was found innocent by
reason of insanity in the 1982 shotgun slaying of her 10-year-old
daughter.
   ``Together they would like to go to some other country and
promise they'll never return,'' Lane said in an interview Tuesday
night. ``He wants to go abroad and try to live a normal life.''
   He said Hinckley, who was found innocent by reason of insanity
in the attempted assassination of President Reagan, did not specify
what country he wants to live in.
   Lane also said in the interview that he would not exploit
Hinckley if he decides to become his attorney, despite what a
hospital attorney argued.
   ``I've never written a book about any client of mine,'' said
Lane, author of books about the assassinations of President Kennedy
and civil rights leader Dr. Martin Luther King. Lane, who later
represented King assailant James Earl Ray, met with Hinckley for
two hours Tuesday.
   ``He's asked me to represent him, and I agreed that I would read
all of the files in his case at St. Elizabeths and tell him if it
would be appropriate for me,'' said Lane.
   Lane said Hinckley feels his proposal to leave the hospital
makes more sense than the hospital's policy of issuing weekend
passes to select patients and requiring them to stay in the area.
   Hinckley received permission from U.S. District Judge June L.
Green on April 20 to start negotiations to hire Lane. Previously,
Lane said, the mental hospital had barred him from meeting with
Hinckley.
   ``The attorney for St. Elizabeths told me the reason I was
seeking out his case and wanted to represent him was so I could
write a book about him and exploit him,'' he said. Lane emphasized
that Hinckley made the initial contact.
   In addition to his quest to leave the country, Hinckley has two
primary requests, Lane said _ to be returned from maximum security
to medium security and to be allowed to speak with the media.
   In 1987, prosecutors turned up evidence Hinckley was
corresponding with serial killer Ted Bundy, who was executed last
year. A cache of letters about actress Jodie Foster was uncovered
last summer, Lane said.
   ``Each time, St. Elizabeths administration was embarrassed when
he was taken to court,'' said Lane. ``They retaliated by placing
him back in maximum security.''
   Lane acknowledged that Hinckley told him ``it was actually
stupid of him to write to Bundy.'' In the case of the Foster
letters, Lane said Hinckley told him a ``guy'' kept writing him
asking if he'd like pictures of Foster, and Hinckley finally
requested the pictures in an effort to stop the letters.
   Prosecutors contend that Hinckley shot President Reagan and
three other men here on March 30, 1981, to impress Miss Foster.
   Asked if he was leaning toward representing Hinckley, Lane said,
``I think he needs assistance, and I think that his rights are
being violated.'' Lane said he would make a decision within two
weeks.
   Lane is the author of ``Rush to Judgment: A Citizen's Dissent,''
the best-selling book about the Warren Commission Report into
President Kennedy's assassination, and coauthor, with Dick Gregory,
of ``Code Name Zorro,'' a chronicle of King's assassination.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
