<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 1050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-WrightProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0457 05-03 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethics Committee Begins Interviews of Wright's Fellow Investors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 3 grafs new with depositions beginning, Myers comment; edits
to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee today began tying
up loose ends in its 11-month probe of Speaker Jim Wright by
hearing from the first of a group of Texas investors in a gas well
that yielded huge profits for Wright.
   San Antonio financier Morris Jaffe was the first to go before
the panel, entering the hearing room in the Capitol basement with
his Washington lawyer, Stanley Brand. Jaffe and four others ``stood
up'' the committee a week ago when two members traveled to San
Antonio to interview them.
   ``I hope they will cooperate, for the sake of getting this task
completed,'' said Rep. John T. Myers, R-Ind., the panel's senior
Republican. Myers said the work of inquiring into the gas well
venture was tying up committee staff who otherwise could be
preparing for a disciplinary hearing for Wright, expected to come
late this month.
   The committee is seeking to clear up circumstances under which
Wright and his business partner, George Mallick, were brought into
the well venture in Sabine Lake near the Texas-Louisiana line, and
parlayed an initial cash outlay of $9,120 into a $340,000 profit in
less than five months.
   In a 23-page defense the investors issued Monday by Brand they
argued that the well was a legitimate business venture and not, as
ethics committee counsel Richard Phelan argued, a potential funnel
for gifts to Wright.
   The investors say they still plan to invest more into sinking
another well at the site in hopes of freeing millions of dollars
worth of gas and petroleum.
   Also subpoenaed were Jaffe's son Doug, president of the family's
companies; Marlyn Cherry, the Jaffes' bookkeeper; Doug Prestridge,
a geologist; and Dave Myers, who supplied the drilling equipment
for the well.
   In a related matter, Wright on Tuesday defended his use of the
Congressional Record to praise a video program his wife helped
develop, but a member of the House ethics committee said the panel
might have to look at the incident.
   ``I don't think there's anything improper about it,'' Wright
told reporters. ``I think it's a tempest in a teapot.''
   But Myers said the situation ``certainly does raise a question''
and could be discussed by the ethics committee. ``It's something
for the whole committee to decide,'' he said.
   In 1985, Wright used his position as a congressman to insert
into the official Capitol publication a column effusively praising
a family motivational video series produced by the Pacific
Institute. The column did not mention that his wife, Betty, was
then drawing a $36,000 salary from the company.
   House rules prohibit a lawmaker from benefiting financially
because of his official position, and guidelines advise that House
members not become too closely associated with any particular
business or make commercial endorsements.
   Also on Tuesday, Wright criticized the ethics committee's
process, saying he has been denied a chance to address the issues
that formed the basis for the 69 counts of House rules violations
he now faces.
   ``I thought I'd answered everything they had in mind,'' Wright
said, referring to his testimony to the committee last September.
But the ultimate charges were based on information that was
developed since then, he said.
   At the same time, Wright and his advisers continued to map a
plan for making the speaker's case both to the ethics committee, at
an anticipated disciplinary hearing late this month, and to the
public.
   Sources said Wright complained vigorously at a strategy session
Monday that he was being unfairly pilloried by the press and by the
ethics committee and voiced frustration that the story of his
public service career, from World War II on, was being obscured.
   Advisers also discussed how to handle the announcement of an
emerging defense team led by his current lawyer, William Oldaker,
and bolstered by the presence of Democratic patriarch Clark
Clifford and perhaps other attorneys with strong courtroom defense
experience.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
