<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-MurderTrial     05-03 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Murder Trial,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Man Dragged To Death, Witness Testifies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white businessman tied a
black farm laborer to the back of his truck and dragged him more
than half a mile on dirt and tar roads until he died, a witness
testified at a murder trial.
   The witness, Michael C. van Rensburg, told the Supreme Court
that his employer, John A. Perreira, 53, tied laborer Molefe Tholi
Nzima by the neck to the tow bar of his truck. Van Rensburg said
his employer then drove the truck through water, down a dirt road
and along a paved road until he swung onto his own property, where
the victim's head slammed into a cement block.
   Van Rensburg testified in Witbank, east of Johannesburg, on
Tuesday.
   He said that on Nov. 18, 1987, he and Perreira were looking for
someone who had been stealing chickens from Perreira's farm in
Ogies, near Witbank, and had received permission from a white
neighbor to question his laborers.
   Perreira threatened a woman at Nzima's house with a gun, then
tied Nzima's arms, body and legs with nylon rope, winding the rope
four times around the man's neck before attaching him to the tow
bar, van Rensburg said.
   After Nzima's head hit the block, Perreira poured water on the
victim to revive him. But Nzima muttered something and died, van
Rensburg said.
   Nzima's bloodied body was taken to a police station. Van
Rensburg said Perreira told him to say Nzima had been stealing
sheep and cattle for about five years and that he died when he fell
off the truck. Van Rensburg said he told the police that story, but
the next day he returned to tell the truth.
   Perreira denies the charge and the trial continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
