<HEAD>Talk Show Hosts Unite: Mort Was Attacked</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmitting to fix cycle designator.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abrasive talk show host Morton Downey Jr. has at
least one believer in his disputed account of a violent encounter
with skinheads in a San Francisco airport.
   ``I believe him,'' Phil Donahue said during recording of his
show Tuesday with Downey as a guest. The program was to be
broadcast today.
   Police and airport officials have said there was no evidence
such an attack took place and suggested the incident was staged.
   Downey told Donahue how he was attacked by skinheads who cut his
hair and drew swastikas on his face. He lifted a toupee to show the
bald spot.
   He acknowledged there are rumors that his show may be canceled
because of the publicity surrounding the incident. Downey's
producers and distributor have not publicly supported him.
   ``Sure I'm in professional jeopardy,'' Downey said. ``And if I'm
lying I'm in mental jeopardy and need a rubber room.''
   Donahue said he did not want Downey off the air.
   ``We'd have to find someone else,'' Donahue said. ``He not only
keeps us honest, he keeps us more aggressive.''
