<FIRST>r a PM-ArtArrests     05-03 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Art Arrests,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Arrested in Zurich Art Theft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Belgians have been arrested and charged
with possession of $4 million worth of Renaissance paintings stolen
at gunpoint from a Swiss art gallery last month.
   The nine paintings were among 21 taken in an April 12 armed
robbery at the Koetser Gallery in Zurich, U.S. Attorney Benito
Romano said Tuesday.
   The three people taken into custody were identified as Rene De
Grove, 54, Thierry Houze, 29, and Martine Wins, 26, officials said.
   De Grove and Houze were identified in court documents as two of
the robbers and Ms. Wins was identified as Houze's companion.
   All three were arrested Monday at De Grove's apartment by
undercover FBI agents.
   They were charged with possession of internationally transported
stolen goods, according to a criminal complaint filed at federal
court.
   ``De Grove voluntarily gave a statement in which, in substance,
he admitted that he was one of the three who robbed the Koetser
Gallery and that he had brought three of the stolen paintings into
the United States on or about April 29,'' said the complaint.
   The art gallery was robbed April 12. Three armed robbers who
bound and gagged a gallery employee got away with 21 works by
artists such as Jan Meartens, the Younger; Jan Steen; Willem Van
Aelst and Dirck Hals.
   If convicted, all three defendants face maximum penalties of 10
years in prison and $250,000 in fines.
</TEXT>
