<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador     05-03 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Embassy Warehouse Bombed In El Salvador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assailants threw two bombs at a
U.S. Embassy warehouse, causing damage but no casualties, police
said today.
   Police officers on the scene said the attack Tuesday night was
presumably the work of leftist guerrillas battling the U.S.-backed
government. But the rebels, in a communique broadcast on their
clandestine radio, denied that.
   The rebels called the bombing ``a blatant maneuver by the army
and Arena to complicate the visit of a delegation of the Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front to the United States.'' Arena is
the rightist party whose leader, Alfredo Cristiani, is to assume
the presidency June 1.
   The Farabundo front is the rebel army. Three representatives of
the front are in New York for talks with United Nations officials.
   The rebels repeated their pledge to refrain from attacking U.S.
personnel and U.S. economic and diplomatic institutions in El
Salvador.
   The bombs damaged a wall and the roof of the warehouse. There
was no immediate estimate of the cost of repairing the damages.
U.S. Embassy officials were not immediately available to comment on
the attack.
</TEXT>
