<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   05-03 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0701</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   April 27
   Tucson (Ariz.) Citizen on abortion:
   The activists are so positive about abortion. They hide behind
their chosen ``pro'' words, protected against doubts. Pro-choice.
Pro-life.
   Caught between two extremes that have split the nation in a
moral civil war are the majority of thinking Americans, fed up with
simplistic shock rhetoric and self-serving doublespeak. Their
pro-word is protest. ...
   Pro-abortion groups warn of ``back-alley deaths'' by abortion
butchers if abortion is outlawed. They beg sympathy for the poor
unwed mother or rape victim for whom an abortion is the difference
between life and death of hope and opportunity.
   At the other extreme are the anti-abortion marchers who shock
with pictures of well-advanced fetuses. They describe women who
have abortions as murderers, and compare 1.6 million abortions each
year to history's most appalling genocide.
   Both sides tell sophisticated lies.
   If the Supreme Court allowed the states to decide ..., there
would be no need for back alley deaths. ...
   The Missouri law being reviewed by the Supreme Court doesn't
outlaw abortion. It restricts state support. Most abortions are
done in private clinics.
   And most women who obtain abortions are not rape victims, nor
are they poor. The implication that some see abortion as a
convenient birth control of last resort is morally repugnant, and
belies the stereotype favored by pro-abortion propaganda.
   But equally unjust is the ``abortion on demand'' cliche that
justifies state interference to halt alleged ``casual
carelessness'' with human life and let government make our moral
decisions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 1
   Los Angeles Times on President Bush's environmental appointees:
   (President) Bush has made one outstanding appointment in William
K. Reilly as chief of the Environmental Protection Agency.
   But his selections for other critical nature-resource jobs raise
serious questions about the administration's pledge to safeguard
the nation's parks, wilderness and coastline. ...
   James Cason has been nominated as assistant secretary of
agriculture in charge of the U.S. Forest Service and Cy Jamison has
been selected to be director of the Bureau of Land Management. ...
   Cason is a former Oregon real estate developer who constantly
ran afoul of the nation's environmental organizations as deputy
assistant secretary of the interior. Jamison ... for the past eight
years he has been an aide to Rep. Ron Marlenee (R-Mont).
   Bush's determination to build a strong environmental record will
be severly undermined _ or doomed _ unless he also has managers at
Interior and the Forest Service who are willing to put conservation
and protection of the nation's dwindling natural estate ahead of
the business-as-usual practice of commercial exploitation.
   The new appointees should be given a chance to demonstrate such
a commitment, but so far, the record is not encouraging.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 28
   Skagit Valley Herald, Mount Vernon, Wash., on the Bush-Quayle
first 100 days:
   Assessments of the first 100 days of the Bush-Quayle
administration, which have poured from Washington like a river ...,
have been nothing if not predictable.
   Read what President Bush or Vice President Quayle has to say
about the first 100 days: Just fine; gaining momentum; under
control.
   Read what conservatives say: competent if not spectacular.
   Read what liberals say: lack of focus, unimpressive.
   Funny, that's exactly what they were saying last year before the
election.
   The fact is, 100 days is too soon for anyone _ the president
included _ to make any meaningful assessment of a new
administration. In that short amount of time the president can do
little more than react to situations while he tries to put his team
together.
   Members of that new team, in the meantime, are still trying to
remember the way to the nearest restroom.
   The measure of a presidency is how successful it is at
accomplishing the goals it sets for itself, and how appropriate
those goals turn out to be. The voters will be making the final
assessment on that when they go to the polls in 1992.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
