<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   05-03 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: in 1992.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   April 27
   The News and Courier, Charleston, S.C., on dismantling the
Pentagon:
   Little by little, piece by piece, the Reagan Revolution, insofar
as it affected the nation's armed forces, is being dismantled.
Money, more precisely a shortage of money, is at the bottom of it.
   With not enough money in a trillion-dollar-plus budget to go
around, not enough to sate the insatiable demands of politically
attractive social programs, not enough to begin to reduce the
crushing burden of accumulated debt, the Army, the Navy and the Air
Force become attractive targets for those with eyes focused less on
the stars than on the next election. ...
   Now, there is nothing inherently wrong in reasoned reductions in
the nation's armed strength to match reductions in perceived threat
_ indeed, were Congress and the administration to support
enormously expensive armed forces in excess of those actually
required to deter war, they would be no less guilty of malfeasance
than if the forces they funded were by design inadequate to the
task. ...
   We hope that President Bush and Secretary (Dick) Cheney, both
new in the job, have not gotten the horse before the cart. The last
thing we need is a return to the dreadful 1960s and '70s when our
armed forces were stretched to the breaking point and, some would
say, beyond.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 28
   The News-Leader, Springfield, Mo., on Mikhail Gorbachev:
   See Mikhail Gorbachev smile. Now see him bite.
   The Soviet president has purged a third of the ruling Communist
Central Committee.
   Officially, the departures were described as ``resignations.''
   Uhhhhhh-huh. Imagine 110 entrenched Communists deciding to
retire gracefully from powerful public office at precisely the same
moment.
   In fact, Gorbachev has accomplished what all Soviet leaders must
do. The alternative is to lose power to someone else. It's not
democratic, but it's effective. ...
   Americans should be neither totally naive nor completely cynical.
   The winds of revolution blow hard in the Soviet Union. When they
are warm, they are welcome. When they are cold, nations suffering
under communism feel the iron fist of power.
   Now it looks like an outstretched hand. But a hand can still be
a fist.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 1
   Tampa (Fla.) Tribune on the USS Iowa:
   Many Americans' hearts fill with awe and pride at the sight of a
battleship. Others would respond similarly to the sight of a troop
of horse cavalry, but they can't.
   While the Navy still has battleships, such as the Iowa in whose
No. 2 gun turret an explosion April 19 killed 47 crew members, the
Army's horse cavalry is long gone, replaced by tanks. ...
   The explosion in its No. 2 turret is not a major reason for
mothballing the Iowa and its three sisters again, and for the last
time.
   The best reason has existed for decades, and it's a shame that
it took the deaths of 47 brave men to remind us that the
battleship, like the horse cavalry, has long since had its day.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 27
   Argus Leader, Sioux Falls, S.D., on the USS Iowa:
   The USS Iowa, first launched in 1942, has served the United
States from a period that spans World War II to a 1988 tour near
the Persian Gulf.
   Former Navy Secretary Frank Knox once called it the greatest
ship ever launched by the United States.
   But weapons become obsolete.
   The time to retire the USS Iowa and the three other (World War
II-era) battleships may have arrived.
</TEXT>
