<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   05-03 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: have arrived.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   April 29
   The Journal, New Ulm, Minn., on the USS Iowa:
   The Navy has acted properly in convening a board of inquiry into
the explosion aboard the USS Iowa that claimed the lives of 47
seamen. ...
   While we may never learn the cause of the disaster, the Navy has
acted wisely, we believe, in imposing a moratorium on the firing of
all its 16-inch guns.
   It is now up to the Defense Department to go one step more and
conduct a thorough review of the need to retain these old ships
like the Iowa in service.
   What we have here is World War I technology aboard a World War
II ship attempting to defend a nation headed into the 21st century.
   The USS Iowa and its sister ships are nearing the half-century
mark. The technology of those 16-inch guns requires sailors to hand
carry 110-pound silk bags of gunpowder to load the guns.
   We do not question the unmatched capacity for sustained
firepower that these ships can deliver, but the question should be
asked if maybe they were better suited for helping contain
brushfire wars in various parts of the globe and be replaced for
general combat.
   For the billions of dollars we spend on defense, we think it's
time we think about retiring aging battleships that present a risk
of life for our own servicemen.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 30
   The Journal, Providence, R.I., on East-West short-range missile
talks:
   As he slid deeper into political trouble this past week, West
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl sought relief by looking eastward,
not West. ...
   Kohl's new disarmament proposals, notably his urgent insistence
on short-range missile reduction talks with Moscow, will surely
throw the NATO allies into some confusion when they meet (in late
May).
   Both the United States and Britain are opposed to such early
discussions _ especially since the fine details of Mikhail
Gorbachev's suggestions are not yet fully understood, and the Bush
administration is preparing its own version of arms-control
proposals.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 26
   The Daily Journal, Elizabeth, N.J., on same-day voter
registration:
   The New Jersey Rainbow Coalition is calling for same-day voter
registation in the state. In other states, this system has spurred
greater voter participation and no increase in election fraud.
   The Rainbow Coalition makes some other good points. For example,
why can't citizens register to vote at government agencies, as they
pay for water bills or renew a drivers license?
   Why must voters register before a 29-day cutoff? Why are
registered voters purged from the voting rolls if they haven't cast
a ballot over a four-year period?
   The United States ranks among the lowest in voter turnout among
the Western democracies, but our powers-that-be aren't too worried
about that. Why should they be? If the demographics of the voting
public ever changed, perhaps they'd become powers-that-were.
   We should all be concerned that such a large chunk of society _
made up largely of the underprivileged and undereducated _ doesn't
vote because of the red tape and bureaucratic hassles.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
</DOC>
