<FIRST>r a PM-BabyFood-Pins     05-03 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baby Food-Pins,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third Incident of Food Tampering Reported in Illinois</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The third incident of food tampering in
less than a week has surfaced in central Illinois, as pinlike
objects were found in vending machine candy, authorities said today.
   A shoe-store employee at Hickory Point Mall in Forsyth, just
north of Decatur, bit into a piece of candy and cut his mouth on a
sharp object Tuesday, said Sgt. Jerry Dawson of the Macon County
sheriff's police.
   Kevin Gentry, 26, spit the candy into a sink, Dawson said. After
waiting on customers he looked back into the sink and found metal
that could have been ``a broken-off straight pin or needle,''
Dawson said.
   A co-worker later found another pinlike object in a piece of the
candy-coated peanuts, Dawson said.
   Seven machines in the mall that serve up handfuls of the candy
were locked up pending investigation, Dawson said.
   Meanwhile, investigators say they believe that pins reportedly
found in Heinz baby food jars in Jacksonville and Springfield are
isolated incidents.
   The company's baby food was removed from store shelves in
Jacksonville Tuesday after a complaint Monday night. Springfield
grocers returned Heinz baby products to their shelves Tuesday after
an incident of food tampering was reported there last week.
   Nobody was hurt in either baby food case.
   Police in Springfield, about 35 miles east of Jacksonville, said
Monday that authorities had no objections to restocking because
there was no evidence the tampering occurred at the point of
production.
   Spokeswoman Beth Adams of Heinz U.S.A. in Pittsburgh, a division
of H.J. Heinz Co., said the criminal investigation in Springfield
is continuing, as tampering is a federal crime.
   There is a ``99-to-one'' chance that the Jacksonville complaint
will be found to be isolated and a ``copy-cat'' of tampering cases
in Great Britain, she said.
   Ms. Adams said Heinz U.S.A. has no connection to the Heinz
company affected by tampering in Britain, where some 300 cases of
contamination were reported, including food found with glass
shards, razor blades and caustic soda.
</TEXT>
