<FIRST>u i PM-Quayle 3rdLd-Writethru a0548 05-03 0882</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0548,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President, Thais Discuss Economic Issues, Cambodia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to correct spelling of Bangkok; subs 11th graf,
Quayle also, to correct word to conferred sted confirmed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle, visiting his
third Southeast Asian country in as many days, discussed economic
issues and the future of Cambodia in get-acquainted meetings with
Thai officials today.
   Quayle was greeted with a 19-gun salute when he arrived here for
a 1{-day stay that will include a tour Thursday of a border camp
for nearly 60,000 Cambodian refugees about 200 miles from Bangkok.
   The fate of Cambodia has been a dominant theme during the vice
president's 12-day tour of Australia, Indonesia, Singapore and
Thailand. In Jakarta, Indonesia, he met with Prince Norodom
Sihanouk, the Cambodian resistence leader whom the United States
wants to head a transition goverment after Vietnam withdraws its
occupation troops this fall.
   Quayle said at a news conference today that the United States
will not consider closer diplomatic ties with Vietnam until that
country ``removes itself from Cambodia.''
   Part of Quayle's responsibility on his trip is to gather ideas
from other Asian nations on Cambodia, and report back to President
Bush, whose administration is reassessing its policy towards Phnom
Penh. Among the options are providing military aid to the
non-communist factions seeking to take over in Cambodia.
   Quayle explained the basic U.S. position on Cambodia during a
50-minute meeting with Thai Prime Minister Chatichai Choonhavan and
also stressed the importance the United States places on protection
of copyrights _ perhaps the only major friction in otherwise strong
relations between the two countries.
   Earlier this year, the United States, Thailand's major export
market, denied the country $165 million in duty-free exports. The
action was taken after Washington complained the Thais had failed
to honor intellectual property rights, for instance copying
patented drugs.
   The United States is weighing whether to further blunt Thai
exports by imposing additional trade restrictions.
   Thai government spokesman Suvit Yoadmanee quoted Chatichai as
telling Quayle the United States should not take drastic action on
the issue because overall relations, including anti-narcotics
cooperation, were good. He noted that most recent negotiations had
gone well.
   Chatichai, according to Suvit, said the United States should
regard Thailand as a ``springboard'' for trade with Indochina and
Burma and noted there was room for increases in trade and joint
ventures between Thailand and the United States.
   Quayle also conferred with Foreign Minister Siddhi Savetsila and
had an audience with King Bhumibol Adulyadej. The vice president
and his wife, Marilyn, were to be guests at a banquet tonight.
   While Quayle met with the prime minister, a half-dozen
university students attempted to hand to the vice president an open
letter protesting any implementation of further restrictions,
claiming it would amount to ``overt intervention of Thailand's
internal affairs.''
   Thai security kept the students from entering Government House,
where Quayle and Chatichai were meeting, and the students
circulated the letter among reporters and others.
   Deputy Prime Minister Pong Sarasin said he was ``more relaxed
than 30 days ago after having received reports about the latest
status of negotiations on trade-related issues.''
   Quayle arrived here from Singapore. He leaves Thursday for
Alaska where he will monitor clean-up efforts from the March 24
Exxon Valdez oil spill in Prince William Sound.
   In Singapore, Quayle met with Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew during
a visit designed to strengthen ties between the United States and
the island republic.
   Quayle said Tuesday's meeting with Lee was fruitful and the two
discussed ``every single issue I can imagine.''
   He said he was impressed by Singapore's ``economic miracle ...
and booming economy.''
   Quayle also saw Goh Chok Tong, Singapore's defense minister and
deputy prime minister.
   At that session, Quayle raised the subject of the Singapore
government's restrictions on the circulation of the U.S.-owned
Asian Wall Street Journal and Far Eastern Economic Review,
according to Goh's private secretary, Tan Jee Say.
   ``I did bring this up,'' Quayle said afterward. ``We have a
difference of opinion on this .... We still hope that they will
change,'' but he added it was up to the Singapore government.
   Goh reiterated his government's position that foreign newspapers
are circulated in Singapore ``not as a right, but as a privilege
granted by the government on terms set by the government,''
according to Tan.
   The government allows papers to circulate in Singapore so long
as they do not engage in domestic politics, Goh said.
   In 1987, the Singapore government severely restricted the
circulation of both publications, a move that prompted the Far
Eastern Economic Review to shut down all distribution here.
   Editors from both papers have denied allegations by the
Singapore government that they meddled in local government.
   Restrictions on the press as well as human rights concerns have
strained U.S.-Singapore relations at times over the past years.
Last year, Singapore expelled an American diplomat, claiming that
he was interfering in domestic politics in his contacts with the
opposition.
   Washington denied that charge. It also has criticized Singapore
in the past for detaining political opponents.
   While in Singapore the vice president also played golf, his
second stint on the greens of his Asia-Pacific trip. The round was
cut short after five holes because of rain.
</TEXT>
