<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 1233EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-JeffersonLecture     05-03 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jefferson Lecture,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Novelist Says Science, by Ignoring Language, Is `Incoherent'</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release 8 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Novelist Walker Percy said Wednesday that
modern science is ``radically incoherent'' because it has failed to
bridge the gap between mind and matter by recognizing the
importance of human language.
   Delivering the 18th annual Jefferson Lecture of the National
Endowment for the Humanities, Percy urged creating a new ``science
of man'' that focuses on the words and meanings of language, the
only place, he said, where mind and matter intersect.
   ``We do not find it odd that there is only one science of
chemistry and neurology but, at last count, more than 600 different
schools of psychotherapy, and growing,'' Percy said in text of his
speech.
   ``We accept the explanation that, after all, the mind is vastly
more complicated than a molecule of sodium chloride or even a nerve
cell,'' he said.
   ``That may be true, but it doesn't explain why the physical
sciences are converging whereas the psychic `sciences' are
diverging; that is, getting nuttier,'' he said.
   Percy, an award-winning novelist from New Orleans and a former
physician, delivered his lecture, titled ``The Fateful Rift: The
San Andreas Fault in the Modern Mind,'' before 1,000 invited guests.
   The Jefferson Lecture, given by an eminent scholar every year
since 1972, is the highest federal honor for outstanding
achievement in the humanities. It carries a stipend of $10,000.
   Percy said science ignores or fails to deal with the relation
between the human mind and the physical world. Contemporary
psychology, he says, deals with visible, measurable entities such
as neurons and synapses and mental phenomena such as ``self'' or
``ego'' without linking them.
   However, he said, ``an increasing number of people are beginning
to know that a different sort of reality lies at the heart of all
uniquely human activity _ speaking, listening, understanding,
thinking, looking at art.''
   Percy said this reality, ``man's unique behavior of language and
symbol-mongering,'' eventually must be confronted by science as a
natural phenomenon that explains humanity.
   Art, poetry and novels ``ought to be taken very seriously
indeed, since these are the cognitive, scientific ... statements
that we have about what it is to be human,'' Percy said.
   ``The humanities, in a word, are not the minstrels of the age
whose only role is to promise `R &amp; R' to tired technicians and
consumers after work,'' he said.
   ``Rather are the humanities the elder brother of the sciences,
who sees how the new scientist got his tail in a crack when he
takes on the human subject as object and who even shows him the
shape of a new science.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 1234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TaxFreedomDay     05-03 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Freedom Day,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Come Friday, You'll Be Working for Yourself</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thursday is ``Tax Freedom Day.'' Once you put
in your eight hours, you'll be working for yourself the rest of the
year.
   The Tax Foundation calculates the average American will have to
work 124 days this year _ the same as in 1987 and 1988 _ just to
pay federal, state and local taxes. Thursday is the 124th day of
the year.
   Tax Freedom Day has never fallen later in the year. This year's
date is also the same as in 1981, before President Reagan and
Congress agreed on a 23-percent across-the-board cut in individual
income tax rates.
   Economists for the foundation, a nonpartisan Washington research
group, say the value of that tax cut has been offset by more than a
dozen subsequent federal tax increases and by higher state and
local taxes caused partially by cuts in federal programs.
   The foundation's calculations are based on the assumption that
all taxes, including those collected by businesses, ultimately are
paid by individuals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
