<FIRST>u i PM-Paraguay 1stLd-Writethru   05-03 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paraguay, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0448,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rodriguez Announces Pay Raises After Election Victory</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with pay raises announced, latest
results. Pickup 5th pvs, `Some losers...' Deletes pvs grafs 8-10 to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Andres Rodriguez today ordered
pay raises of 30 percent to 70 percent for public employees and the
military after his overwhelming victory in presidential and
congressional elections.
   The salaries of brigadier generals will jump 70 percent, from
$448 to $761 a month. Captains' salaries will go from $248 to $421,
and sergeants will earn $209, up from $123.
   Rodriguez, who toppled dictator Alfredo Stroessner in a coup
Feb. 3, also announced 30 percent pay raises for public employees
and 49 percent increases for workers in clinics and hospitals.
   On Tuesday, Rodriguez announced the retirement of up to three
dozen army generals, some of them Stroessner loyalists, as part of
a shakeup to allow younger officers to move up in rank.
   ``Within a few days, or within the month of May, I'll give you
the list of those who have left (retired) and those who have been
promoted to general,'' Rodriguez told reporters as he left the
National Palace.
   The Central Electoral Board said today that of 898,829 votes
counted so far, Rodriguez received 667,434, or slightly more than
74 percent.
   His governing Colorado Party won control of Congress in the vote.
   ``I am pleased and happy that I have the affection of the
people, and they showed their confidence in me,'' Rodriguez said
when asked about the results.
   Some losers fumed about voting irregularities, but Paraguayans
seemed satisfied with the triumph of Rodriguez, a longtime
Stroessner aide who has respected civil liberties and promised
democratic reforms since taking power.
   ``You couldn't expect any other result because the people are
very grateful to him for putting his life in danger to bring us
freedom,'' said Susana Jara, 50, a fruit vendor in the public
market.
   ``Half of the vote for Rodriguez was a `thank you' for
overthrowing Stroessner,'' said Aldo Zuccolillo, editor of the
newspaper ABC Color that reopened last March after being shut down
five years ago by the former regime.
   Fernando Vera, presidential candidate of the Revolutionary
Febrerista Party, noted the election's many ``irregularities,'' but
said Rodriguez obviously won ``by a landslide.''
   Rodriguez has pledged to support reforms of the Constitution,
electoral law and the penal code. He also promised not to seek
re-election in 1993.
   The balloting was to choose a successor to finish the five-year
terms of Stroessner, who now lives in Brazil, and the Congress that
Rodriguez dissolved after the coup.
   The partial, official tally gave the governing Colorado Party
67.2 percent of the vote for the 36-member Senate and the 72-member
Chamber of Deputies. Unofficial tallies gave the Colorados, in
power since 1947, similar winning margins.
   The runner-up in the presidential balloting, Domingo Laino of
the Authentic Radical Liberal Party, has complained of ``shameful
irregularities'' in the voting. On Tuesday, he met with other party
leaders to decide whether to issue a protest.
   Flaws cited by international election observers and party
officials included lack of space for voting in private, lack of
indelible ink to prevent multiple voting, and apparently illegal,
last-minute registrations by the Colorados.
   ``The conduct of the elections was far from perfect,'' the
Washington-based National Democratic Institute for International
Affairs said in a statement.
   The group, an arm of the Democratic Party, noted the short time
to prepare and the country's history of authoritarian rule.
Widespread vote fraud occurred during the eight elections won by
Stroessner in his nearly 35 years of rule.
   The inauguration of Rodriguez and the Congress was set for May
15.
</TEXT>
