<FIRST>u a PM-HarrierCrash     05-03 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Harrier Crash,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harrier Jet Crashes at Parris Island, Pilot Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARRIS ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military jet crashed today during a
training flight, and the pilot died from injuries suffered when he
ejected moments before the plane went down, Marines Corps officials
said.
   The single-seat AV-8 Harrier crashed about 9 a.m. near a
training airfield at the Marine Corps Recruiting Depot near
Beaufort, Marine spokesman 1st Lt. Arnold John Kozloski said.
   The pilot died later at the U.S. Naval Hospital in Beaufort,
authorities said.
   The pilot, whose name was withheld pending notification of
relatives, was assigned to the 2nd Marine Aviation Wing at Cherry
Point Marine Air Station in North Carolina, Kozloski said.
   The pilot was one of 25,600 Marines and sailors participating in
the ``Solid Shield '89'' training exercise, which began today along
the East Coast and is scheduled to run until May 20.
   The Harrier jet, capable of vertical take-offs and landings, had
taken off from Page Field at Parris Island, Kozloski said.
   No weapons or explosives were aboard the jet, which crashed 100
feet from the end of the runway and sparked a fire, Kozloski said.
   No injuries were reported on the ground and the fire was brought
under control, Kozloski said.
   Three pilots have died in 14 Harrier jet crashes since May 1988,
said 1st Lt. Tamara Skipton at Cherry Point, where all the U.S.
military's Harrier jets are based.
   The jet's predecessor, the AV-8C, was introduced by McDonald
Aircraft Co. in 1969 and used by the British during the Falkland
Islands war.
</TEXT>
