<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Parasite     05-03 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Parasite,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parasitic Fly Threatens Africa, Middle East, Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A parasitic worm that causes millions of dollars'
damage to livestock in the Americas has been found in North Africa
and threatens that entire continent, the Middle East and southern
Europe, a U.N. agency said Wednesday.
   Edouard Saouma, director-general of the Food and Agriculture
Organization, notified 37 countries the American screwworm ``could
have disastrous consequences to livestock, wildlife and perhaps
even human populations.''
   The agency said the screwworm is one of the most drastic insect
pests in the Western Hemisphere, costing farmers hundreds of
millions of dollars a year.
   The screwworm is the larva of a blowfly which infests wounds and
apertures like nostrils, breeding there and debilitating
warm-blooded animals. They can die without treatment.
   U.N. experts said they do not know how the parasite reached
North Africa.
</TEXT>
