<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 1350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ChildEvicted     05-03 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Evicted,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Age Law Does Not Apply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW PORT RICHEY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An adult community has won the
right to evict a toddler in a test of a federal law aimed at
preventing age discrimination in housing.
   Pasco Circuit Judge Lawrence Keough gave Vincent Malloy 30 days
to remove his son Johnny, who turns 2 this week, from Arborwood at
Summertree, a 289-unit community for adults 55 and older.
   After a three-hour non-jury trial, Keough decided Tuesday that
the subdivision fits exceptions to the newly amended Fair Housing
Act, which took effect March 12, and upheld the association's age
restriction as legal.
   The law includes exemptions for retirement communities if 80
percent of the households have at least one person age 55 or older
and if facilities and services are provided for them.
   Arborwood attorney Michael Brudny said the subdivision meets
both requirements.
   Malloy represented himself, saying he could have afforded a
lawyer but chose not to do so because others similarly affected
might not be able to afford one.
   ``To decide on their part, you're deciding against all the
people that Congress tried to protect with this law. And you're
also deciding against all the people 55 and up who like children,''
Malloy told the judge in his closing agrument.
   Malloy said he will honor the order and expects to move to
another home five miles away he has arranged to buy.
   He originally bought the $90,000 Arborwood home for his
80-year-old father, who died in December 1985 before the house was
finished. Malloy said he and his son moved to Arborwood last June
after he divorced the boy's mother. He said he lived there two
weeks before receiving notice from the homeowners group to move.
   Earlier this year, Keough rejected a bid by the association to
evict the child and said the subdivision's original restriction
against minors _ residents younger than 18 _ would become illegal
when the fair housing law took effect. The Arborwood association
amended its bylaws to become a 55-and-older community.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
