<HEAD>Former Chancellor Still Paid Despite Embezzlement Conviction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former chancellor of the
University of California, Santa Barbara, continues to receive his
$6,800-a-month salary, 10 months after being convicted of
embezzling $250,000 in campus funds.
   A campus discipline review process has yet to decide the future
of Robert Huttenback, who was suspended indefinitely in September
as a tenured history professor.
   Many professors and students have expressed outrage that the
university continues to pay Huttenback.
   ``This year there are 2,400 freshmen who are unable to take
required freshman English courses because the university is too
short of money to provide those courses,'' said John Reiff, who
teaches freshman composition. ``So it's terribly puzzling and
distressing to pay a convicted felon for not teaching.''
   ``It's disgraceful that we continue to pay a man who has been
convicted of stealing from us,'' said student body President Javier
LaFianza.
   John Myers, chairman of the five-member Committee of Privilege
and Tenure, said the panel has not made a recommendation on
Huttenback because ``this is a very complicated matter that has to
be done with a great deal of thought.''
   Huttenback resigned as chancellor in July 1986 but continued to
teach history. He was later convicted of embezzlement and income
tax evasion in connection with embezzling school funds to make
repairs at his home.
   He was fined $60,000, placed on five years' probation and
ordered to perform 1,000 hours of community service. He is
appealing his sentence.
</TEXT>
