<FIRST>r i AM-SovietBooks     05-03 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Books,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet: Importing Publications Just a `Commercial Issue'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Importing books and other publications to the
Soviet Union is ``purely a commercial'' proposition, unhindered by
political considerations, a high-ranking Soviet official said
Wednesday.
   Dmitry Mamleev, deputy head of the Soviet state committee for
publishing and the book trade, also said exchanges between
Americans and Soviets in the publishing world are booming thanks to
glasnost.
   ``There is no problem with political issues now,'' Mamleev said
at a news conference during a 35-nation forum on the flow of
information between East and West. ``This is purely a commercial
issue now.''
   Mamleev, who introduced himself as a journalist, said 12 joint
ventures have been created recently for distributing books. He
cited only Soviet-Polish and Soviet-Bulgarian examples of
cooperation, however.
   He denied that censorship existed in the Soviet Union, saying
the only ban was on publication of state secrets.
   Due to glasnost, the new Soviet policy of openness, all
publishing houses were ``independent,'' he said.
   Despite a paper shortage, he said, 2{ billion books and 84,000
new titles were being published every year.
   Speaking of exchanges with Americans, Mamleev said, ``two years
ago we started at a level below zero _ today I don't know how many
of my publishers are in the States, there are so many.''
   As part of the limited importation of foreign magazines and
newspapers begun last fall, he said 1,000 copies of Time magazine
recently went on sale.
   The newspaper USA Today is set to follow and his committee is
negotiating an exchange of the science magazine Omni for its Soviet
counterpart, Science in the U.S.S.R.
   Until recently, Soviet customs inspectors searched the bags of
arriving tourists to confiscate Western publications.
   On Tuesday, U.S. delegation member Judith Ingram criticized the
Soviet Union's decision to allow the public to attend the Moscow
International Book Fair in September for only two days of its seven
day-run.
   Ms. Ingram expressed U.S. concern that ``this period will not be
long enough to accommodate the many Soviet citizens who depend on
this biennial event to acquint themselves with world literature.''
   She also cited the case of Vladimir Ryabakon, a Russian Orthodox
Christian, whose religious literature was confiscated upon his
return to the Soviet Union in December, despite official Soviet
media articles announcing the lifting of all limitations on
importing such material.
   She said U.S. delegates hoped that the positive changes toward
freedom of expression seen in Poland, Hungary and ``to some
extent'' in the Soviet Union would also reach other East bloc
countries where they were needed, such as Bulgaria and Romania.
   The month-long conference, known as the Information Forum, ends
next week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
