<FIRST>u w PM-NATO-Missiles 3rdLd-Writethru a0569 05-03 0907</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NATO-Missiles, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0569,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Rules Out Talks With Soviets Over Short-Range Nuclear Missiles</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with Bush statement, picks up with 3rd graf
pvs, I tried. Removes last 6 grafs pvs to shorten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today ruled out negotiations
with the Soviet Union on short-range nuclear missiles, saying such
talks ``would be a mistake.''
   He said the weapons must be kept in West Germany and made more
powerful in order to deter Soviet attack.
   Bush outlined his position to Prime Minister Gro Harlem
Brundtland in an hour-long White House meeting. She stressed a need
to find ``commmon ground'' with West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl,
who wants the missiles scaled back and eventually eliminated.
   Bush's spokesman, Marlin Fitzwater, suggested the disagreement
was not likely to be resolved before Bush, Kohl and the leaders of
the 14 other North Atlantic Treaty Organization countries attend a
summit meeting in Brussels May 29-30.
   ``We will continue to discuss it but we are very firm in our
position,'' Fitzwater said.
   The centerpiece of the summit is celebration of the 40th
anniversary of the Western alliance. Fitzwater said ``we will have
a healthy debate'' if a solution remains elusive. But, he said, ``I
don't think it will damage the basic strength of NATO.''
   Quoting Bush, the spokesman said the president had told the
Norwegian leader that the short-range Lance missiles were
``essential'' to NATO's strategy of deterring an attack by the
Warsaw Pact and that ``such systems must be kept up to date.''
   Moreover, Fitzwater said, Bush told Mrs. Brundtland that
``entering into arms control negotiations on short-range nuclear
forces with the Soviet Union would be a mistake.''
   The statement appeared to rule out negotiations to eliminate the
Lances under any circumstances. Fitzwater said there could be no
consideration of such talks at least until after the Warsaw Pact
reduced its conventional forces in Europe.
   Mrs. Brundtland, taking an optimistic view, had predicted after
seeing Bush that the NATO allies would find a ``common ground''
between conflicting U.S. and West German positions on the
short-range nuclear missiles.
   ``I tried to listen very seriously to the concerns and the
positions of the American administration,'' the Norwegian leader
said.
   While Norway shares the U.S. view that the Warsaw Pact's edge in
conventional weapons should be trimmed, Mrs. Brundtland made it
clear her government is closer to the West German stand on the
missiles.
   ``I think he knows that,'' she said of Bush, whose hopes for a
successful first summit meeting with the NATO allies, scheduled for
Brusssels May 29-30, are clouded by differences with West German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
   Bush wants to more than triple the range of U.S.-built Lance
missiles in West Germany. Kohl, who is up for re-election next year
before a disarmament-inclined electorate, wants the program delayed
and negotiations held between the United States and the Soviet
Union to scale back short-range nuclear rockets.
   ``I think we will see the NATO summit will find common ground by
continuing discussions in the weeks before that meeting,'' Mrs.
Brundtland said.
   If not, the Norwegian leader said, the 16 allied leaders could
accomplish the task in Brussels. ``There is always something left
for political leaders to do,'' she said.
   Mrs. Brundtland said the elements of a compromise should include
a ``linkage'' between non-nuclear and nulcear weapons. ``We have to
be very clear in our requirements to the Soviets on reducing
conventional arms,'' she said.
   The prime minister said the Bush administration felt it had been
taken by surprise by the West German demand for speedy negotiations
over the Lance missiles. ``But these change are a fact and I think
we need to find common ground,'' Mrs. Brundtland said.
   U.S. officials said on Tuesday the Bush administration was
considering a compromise in which the United States would develop a
non-nuclear missile jointly with the West Germans.
   This would require a reversal of a decision by Bonn in February
to stop research and development on the FK90 missile, which was
classified as a tactical weapon with a range below 300 miles.
   A U.S. official said the missile could target Warsaw Pact
airfields and other military installations now targeted by the
Lances.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
development of the non-nuclear missile was under consideration at
NATO headquarters in Brussels and at the Pentagon. ``It would give
us greater flexibility,'' he said.
   Another option under discussion within the alliance is a
declaration at the Brussels summit meeting May 29-30 proposing to
scale back the Lance missiles _ but only after their range is more
than tripled and provided the Soviets reduce their short-range
rockets, as well.
   Mrs. Brundtland said at a news conference Tuesday that ``what we
need now is to look for the common ground, to look for what will be
a sensible and coherent way of addressing the issues both of arms
control and disarmament.''
   The prime minister said her government's position is that ``all
kinds of weapons'' should be on the table in arms control and
disarmament talks.
   Norway has lined up with West Germany in seeking a delay in
extending the range of the Lances to about 250 miles.
   Mrs. Brundtland said Norway also would like to see NATO's agenda
expanded to deal with environmental and energy problems. ``We will
all be hurt by climate and atmosphere changes wherever we live on
the globe,'' she said.
</TEXT>
