<FIRST>r i AM-Quayle-Reporter'sNotebook     05-03 0768</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle-Reporter's Notebook,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Trip: A Sporting Chance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sometimes Vice President Dan Quayle's
trip to Australia and Southeast Asia seemed more like Wide World of
Sports than a diplomatic mission.
   Once, he kept Indonesia's minister of tourism waiting for nearly
two hours at the Jakarta airport because he and his wife, Marilyn,
wanted to squeeze in some last-minute tennis at a Port Douglas
resort in northeast Australia.
   Quayle's favorite sport is golf, which stood him in good stead
in golf-crazy Asia. After he played five holes in Singapore, Prime
Minister Lee Kuan Yew quizzed him on his golf backround.
   Quayle, a well-above-average golfer, said he first handled a
club when he was 10. By the time he was 20, he allowed, he knew
he'd never make pro.
   The Quayles also donned wetsuits and strapped oxygen tanks on
their backs to try scuba diving in the brilliant waters of
Australia's coral-rich Great Barrier Reef. They were so hooked on
the sport, they opted for a second dive.
   In Melbourne, Quayle jogged around the city's botanical gardens,
stopping to chat with the locals.
   And in an Indiana tradition, he started his 12-day trip with a 3
a.m. pickup basketball game at Hickam Air Force base in Honolulu.
Score: Visitors 23, Home 16.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Quayle is vice president now, but the former Indiana senator
hasn't forgotten his Hoosier roots.
   Asked by an Australian reporter where the word ``Hoosier''
originated, Quayle responded: ``That's important. ... Let me answer
that ... I'll give you a little advertising here.''
   Launching into a description of the state - ``five-and-a-half
million people, we don't produce a lot of wheat'' _ Quayle gave one
of the many versions of where the word came from. He said the
Hoosiers were a family who worked on a railroad in Ohio in the
1800s.
   ``Anytime that they really wanted to get the job done, he (the
boss), would always say, `Give me my Hoosier gang,' which meant the
people from Indiana.''
   ``They were hard-working, effective, brilliant people like you
are seeing right here,'' Quayle said as the crowd roared.
   So, interjected the questioner, ``It's got nothing to do with
`Who's you mother?'''
   By coincidence, one of the movies available on the cable channel
where Quayle's staff stayed in Jakarta, Indonesia, was
``Hoosiers,'' spelled ``Hossiers'' on the schedule.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   While Quayle met officials in government buildings, his wife
often went her own way, visiting historic cultural sights.
   ``If you want to go out and see the country, go with Marilyn,''
Quayle told reporters at the start of his 27,000-mile trip. He was
right.
   Mrs. Quayle, traveling abroad with her husband for the first
time since he became vice president, toured a sultan's palace in
Jogjakarta, Indonesia; learned about aboriginal art at Australia's
national gallery in Canberra; gazed at the emerald Buddha inside a
gilded temple at the Grand Palace in Bangkok, and climbed to the
top of the 9th century Buddhist temple at Borobudur in central Java.
   There, she stuck her arm though a stone cage to touch the hand
of a carved Buddha inside.
   ``It's for success in life,'' she proclaimed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Quayle, 42, prides himself on his stamina, but he acknowledged
he felt the effects of his ``if it's Wednesday, it must be
Bangkok'' trip at times.
   On his second day in Australia, the vice president was asked
what surprised him most about the place.
   ``I suppose the most surprising thing, and I've only been here
less that 24 hours, was how tired I was last night,'' he responded.
   Later, Quayle said he'd taken sleeping pills the first couple of
nights of the trip to cope with jet lag.
   Counting four brief stops in cities in U.S. territory before he
reached Australia, Quayle was visiting 13 places in 12 days, flying
27,000 miles.
   His itinerary: Washington, Chicago, Los Angeles, Honolulu, Pago
Pago, Canberra, Melbourne, Sydney, Port Douglas, Jakarta,
Singapore, Bangkok, Site B refugee camp Alaska, Washington.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Quayles seemed to survive their trip without any noticeable
cultural faux pas. Not that there weren't chances.
   For example, the visitors' guide to Thailand, prepared by the
U.S. Embassy and handed out to Quayle's entourage, advised the
following:
   ``Don't stand over a seated Thai when talking to him.''
   ``Don't touch a Thai on the head.''
   ``Don't point or shake your finger at someone. When sitting, do
not allow your toes to point directly at another person.''
   ``Do stand up when the king's anthem is played at the movie or
other public gatherings.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
