<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-PLO     05-03 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-PLO,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Security Man Killed, Arafat's Envoy Remains Critical</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An assassin killed a Palestinian security
man Wednesday, the day after Yasser Arafat's personal
representative was critically wounded in Sidon, which has become
PLO's main power base in Lebanon.
   Police said Bassam Hourani, 30, was shot to death on his
motorcycle near the Sidon vegetable market. Hourani was a second
lieutenant in Fatah, the guerrilla faction led by Arafat, the
chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   ``The assailant, firing an automatic rifle, riddled Hourani with
several bullets in the head and chest,'' said a police spokesman,
who cannot be identified under standing rules. ``Death was
instantaneous. The assailant escaped.''
   Arafat's representative, Issam Salem, 48, was shot down in a
gift shop Tuesday by a man who wore a plastic mask. The assailant
escaped.
   Police said they had no explanation for the attacks on
Palestinians that began with the grenade fired at the home of Zeid
Wehbi on Saturday. Two passers-by were wounded.
   No group claimed responsibility for any of the three attacks,
but Wehbi blamed Israel for the attempt on Salem.
   Dr. Ghassan Hammoud, one of three surgeons who operated on
Salem, said he was making ``remarkable progress'' afer the removal
of the bullet, which pierced the left side of his forehead.
   ``He's in a coma, but not a deep coma,'' Hammoud said. ``The
improvement in his condition was unexpected, considering his
condition when he was brought in. Yesterday, his right side was
completely paralyzed, but today there's only a little paralysis
left on the right arm.''
   Salem's wife, Jihad, said: ``When he hears my voice, Issam opens
his eyes as if in recognition.''
   Her brother, Ali Hassan Salameh, was killed 10 years ago in a
Beirut car bomb explosion blamed on Israeli agents. Salameh, known
as Abul Hassan, led the the PLO security organization Force 17.
   The PLO security department, and the leftist Lebanese Nasserite
militia that governs this ancient port city 25 miles south of
Beirut, said they were conducting a joint search for Salem's
attacker.
   A source in the PLO said privately that several people had been
apprehended, but he would not give details.
   Wehbe said the attack on Salem was intended to ``deal a blow to
Lebanese-Palestinian coexistence in the Sidon region'' and ``such
operations are carried out only by the Israeli Mossad'' secret
service.
   Another PLO official said, on condition of anonymity: ``They're
all being plotted in the same kitchen. It may be Mossad or not.''
   Arafat, on an official visit to France, called the attempt to
kill Salem ``a message for us to put up our hands and stop helping
our Lebanese brothers.''
   Christian-controlled radio stations in Beirut interpreted the
remark as an accusation against Syria, whose soldiers are fighting
Christian units of the Lebanese army. Arafat, a foe of Syrian
President Hafez Assad, has declared support for the Christians.
   Syria has about 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon under a 1976
peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League. Lebanon's sectarian
civil war began in 1975.
</TEXT>
