<FIRST>r i AM-Quayle     05-03 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Meets With Thais, Plans Visit to Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle held
get-acquainted meetings Wednesday with Thai officials and will get
a first-hand look at the plight of Cambodian refugees Thursday when
he winds up a 12-day foreign trip.
   Quayle flies to the embattled Thai-Cambodian border, where he
will visit Site B, a sprawling camp inhabited by nearly 60,000
refugees under the control of guerrillas fighting the
Vietnam-backed Phnom Penh government in Cambodia.
   The vice president, accompanied by his wife, is on the last leg
of a 12-day tour of Australia, Indonesia, Singapore and Thailand.
   Cambodia's fate has been a dominant theme during the trip.
   Site B is the major camp controlled by forces loyal to Prince
Norodom Sihanouk, the leader of a three-party resistance coalition
currently negotiating with the Phnom Penh government to end a
decade-long guerrilla war which began after Vietnam's invasion of
Cambodia in late 1978.
   In Jakarta, Indonesia, Quayle met with Sihanouk, whom the United
States wants to head a transition government after Vietnam
withdraws its troops this fall. Quayle told a news conference
Wednesday that the United States will not consider closer
diplomatic ties with Vietnam until that country ``removes itself
from Cambodia.''
   After his arrival in Thailand, his third Southeast Asian country
in as many days, Quayle explained the basic U.S. position on
Cambodia during a 50-minute meeting with Thai Prime Minister
Chatichai Choonhavan and also stressed the importance the United
States places on protection of copyrights _ perhaps the only major
friction in otherwise strong relations between the two countries.
   Earlier this year, the United States, Thailand's major export
market, denied the country $165 million in duty free exports. The
action was taken after Washington complained the Thais had failed
to honor intellectual property rights.
   Unlicensed reproductions of American video movies, music
cassettes, designer clothes and computer software are made and
openly sold in Thailand. American pharmaceutical products are
similarly manufactured and distributed
   Thai officials say laws exist to protect intellectual property
but enforcement is still difficult. The United States, however, is
considering further and stiffer retaliatory measures.
   Thai government spokesman Suvit Yoadmanee quoted Chatichai as
telling Quayle that good bilateral relations should not be marred
by the United States taking drastic action on the issue. He noted
that the most recent negotiations had proceeded well.
   While Quayle met with the prime minister, half a dozen
university students attempted to hand Quayle an open letter
protesting further American economic retaliation, claiming this
would amount to ``overt intervention of Thailand's internal
affairs.''
   Thai security kept the students from entering Government House,
where Quayle and Chatichai were meeting, and the students
circulated the letter among reporters and others.
   Quayle also met with Foreign Minister Siddhi Savetsila, and had
an audience with King Bhumibol Adulyadej and members of his family.
The vice president and his wife, Marilyn, were then hosted at a
dinner banquet.
   Quayle leaves Thailand Thursday for Alaska where he will monitor
clean-up efforts from the March 24 Exxon Valdez oil spill in Prince
William Sound.
</TEXT>
