<HEAD>Exxon Captain Will Waive Extradition, Prosecutor Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Hazelwood, who...' to UPDATE with clerk in Anchorage
saying Hazelwood is scheduled to appear in court today. It would be after
5:30 p.m. EDT, and a lead is unlikely this cycle.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fired captain of the tanker that
spilled more than 10 million gallons of oil in Alaska plans to
waive extradition and surrender soon, an Alaskan prosecutor said
today.
   Attorneys for Joseph Hazelwood, 42, assured Alaskan officials
the ex-captain would surrender today or Thursday, said prosecutor
Dean Guaneli of the state attorney general's office.
   His surrender would negate an extradition hearing scheduled for
Friday in Suffolk County, said Suffolk Assistant District Attorney
Philip Castellano Jr.
   Hazelwood, who returned to his home area on Long Island after
the nation's worst oil spill occurred on March 24, was freed by a
Suffolk judge on $25,000 bail. He arrived this morning in Anchorage
and was scheduled to appear in state District Court later today, a
court clerk said.
   An arrest warrant was issued by Alaskan authorities last month
after Hazelwood was charged with three misdemeanors in connection
with the tanker accident. He is accused of operating a ship while
intoxicated, reckless endangerment, and negligent discharge of oil.
   Hazelwood allegedly turned over control of the Exxon Valdez to
an unqualified third mate before the tanker ran into a reef in
Prince William Sound off Alaska.
