<FIRST>r w AM-US-Korea     05-03 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Korea,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korean Minister Says U.S. Pressure Could Spark Instability</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soon Cho, South Korea's deputy prime minister
and top economic planning officer, said Wednesday that increased
U.S. pressure on his country to open its markets and revalue its
currency could spark even more instability in his violence-plagued
nation.
   ``The most pressing business for the government of Korea is to
restore order and establish the democratic system,'' said Soon, in
Washington for meetings with congressional leaders and top Bush
administration officials.
   Soon spoke with reporters as the most recent wave of student
unrest claimed the lives of six riot police in Pusan, a city about
200 miles southeast of Seoul. The victims were set afire during one
of the many violent protests that have prompted President Roh
Tae-woo to threaten the imposition of emergency measures.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said in a
statement that the administration deplored ``the senseless violence
that has led to this tragic and needless loss of life'' and urged
all parties in South Korea to refrain from further violence.
   On trade matters, the administration has charged South Korea
with erecting significant trade barriers to U.S. products, part of
a process that could result in retaliation against nations refusing
to open their doors to American goods.
   The United States has also been pressuring South Korea to allow
its currency to rise in value in relation to the dollar as a way of
making its goods more expensive on American markets and making U.S.
goods cheaper on South Korean markets.
   The South Korean official is slated to meet Thursday with
Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady. Those topics were sure to be
discussed.
   Pointing out that his nation has been afflicted with near-daily
demonstrations on the part of students, farmers and workers, Soon
said the United States ``is pressing Korea very hard to further
open its markets, appreciate its currency and so on.''
   Arguing that South Korea has already made great strides in
attempting to open its markets, Soon said U.S. retaliation would be
interpreted by the South Korean public as ``too harsh in spite of
the great effort that the Korean government is making.
   ``I'm sure that it would be adding to instability from which
(the) Korean government is already suffering,'' Soon said.
   The radical student and dissident protestors are demanding the
overthrow of Roh's government, but haven't had broad public support
because of their extremism and violent tactics. They have been
able, however, to form alliances with striking workers.
   Soon argued that the South Korean government ``considers the
present level (of the won, the South Korean currency) to be a
fairly appropriate one'' and sees no reason to revalue it at
present.
   He disupted the contention, made in an initial Treasury
Department report last October, that his nation has manipulated its
currency to gain an unfair competitve advantage in world markets,
and he accused the U.S. government of showing ``a lack of
understanding on this matter.''
   He also faulted the United States for making ``one-way demands''
on trade matters, saying ``that is not beneficial to the
maintainance of good relations.''
   Soon stressed, however, that his nation was more than willing to
continue the dialogue to prevent inciting a trade war between the
two countries and to maintain a cooperative relationship.
</TEXT>
