<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 1617EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Trade     05-03 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Press Hills to Target Japan for Market-Opening Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators urged the nation's top trade
negotiator on Wednesday to resist pressure to omit Japan from a
target list being developed by the Bush administration in an effort
to open key world markets to American exports.
   ``We would be amazed if Japan, with its whole panoply of trade
barriers, were not on the list,'' Sen. John C. Danforth, R-Mo.,
said at a Senate Finance Committee trade hearing.
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills told the senators that the
administration would ``use the negotiating tools contained in the
1988 act vigorously but constructively to open markets, combat
unfair trade practices and persuade our trading partners to honor
agreements.''
   ``In administering these provisions, we will act as a surgeon
using a scalpel to remove these trade barriers and promote a
healthier trading system,'' she said. ``We will not use these tools
to butcher the rules of the system we are trying to strengthen.''
   At issue is a report from Hills, due by the end of the month,
that must target specific countries for market-opening action and
possible retaliation under the so-called Super 301 section of the
1988 trade law. There reportedly is divided opinion within the
administration over whether to include Japan.
   Under the Super 301 provision, the U.S. trade representative
targets key countries for market-opening pressure. If they fail to
lower their barriers to American exports within 15 to 19 months,
the trade representative takes retaliatory steps, such as tariffs
and quotas, to compensate the United States. The president does
have discretion to abort such steps in some cases.
   The provision is called Super 301 because it represents an
extension of section 301 of the Trade Act, which has long been the
basic legal authority under which the president is authorized to
retaliate against foreign countries for alleged unfair trade
practices. Hills is due to unveil her list May 30.
   ``I strongly support the idea and urge you to include Japan in
the Super 301 category,'' Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., told
Hills. He said that ``their market is not open to us in any way
that it should be.''
   Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., noted that a long-running dispute
between the United States and Japan over semiconductors remains
unresolved.
   ``If that isn't grounds for listing under Super 301 what is?''
Heinz said.
   Under questioning from Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., Hills said
that ``great concern has been expressed by some'' officials of
America's trading partners as the date for the list approaches and
there has been a reaction ``among some others (of) more
belligerence perhaps.''
   ``There is general anxiety,'' she said.
   Asked by Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., about reports that foreign
lobbying has been heavy at her office as other countries strive to
stay off the list, Hills merely said, ``We've had a good number of
visitors.''
   She agreed with the view of Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
D-N.Y., that merely lowering barriers overseas is far from the
answer to the nation's trade problems.
   ``We could open all the markets we have enumerated and it would
not correct our trade deficit, and I think we make a mistake not to
tell the American people that,'' she said. ``To tell the American
people that if you open all these markets that will take care of
the trade deficit _ that is not true.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
