<FIRST>r i AM-Thatcher     05-03 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thatcher,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Tigress' Thatcher Cuddles Grandson, Defends Record of 10 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher on Wednesday
marked the 10th anniversary of her election cuddling her grandson
and likening her combative style to a tigress under attack.
   Interviewed by the domestic Press Association agency, the prime
minister rejected the charge her style is confrontational, saying:
``Most women defend themselves. It is the female of the species.''
   ``It is the tigress and the lioness in you which tends to defend
when attacked. That may give the feeling that one is constantly in
some kind of battle.''
   Britain's longest continuously serving prime minister this
century also dismissed the latest opinion polls, saying: ``If you
just set out to be liked, you would be prepared to compromise on
anything at any time and you would achieve nothing.''
   Opponents looked back glumly to May 3, 1979, when, after a
winter of strikes had left the dead unburied and garbage piled in
the streets, Britons voted out the socialist Labor Party government
of James Callaghan.
   Mrs. Thatcher, leader of the Conservative Party, took office the
next day, May 4, becoming Europe's first woman prime minister. She
since has won two more terms, pursuing a right-wing revolution that
has emasculated labor unions and increased prosperity.
   But critics charge ``Thatcherism'' has made the poor poorer,
encouraged greed and divided the nation.
   ``She has preached the gospel of conflict and division,'' said
Roy Hattersley, deputy leader of the Labor Party. ``(She) has
chosen to govern with an arrogance and autocracy which amounts to
an assault on our democratic rights.''
   In her interview, the 63-year-old Mrs. Thatcher said: ``Everyone
knows now that Britain counts for something in the world at large.
That is the result of many other achievements.''
   Earlier, she posed on the steps of her 10 Downing St. residence
cradling her grandson, Michael. Her son, Mark, and his American
wife, Diane, brought the baby from their home in Dallas.
   ``Isn't he beautiful? Isn't he good?'' Mrs. Thatcher cooed as
she showed off the sleeping baby, dressed in a blue and white
sailor suit.
   Then she ate lunch at the Savoy Hotel, where rank-and-file
Conservative Party legislators presented her with a silver bowl
engraved with the emblems of England, Scotland, Wales and Northern
Ireland.
   Also engraved was a tiny penguin, a reminder of the 1982 war
against Argentina in which Britain wrested back the disputed
Falkland Islands in the South Atlantic.
   The anniversary has triggered a mass of media analyses of
Thatcherism, opinion polls about the Thatcher decade, souvenirs and
Thatcher books.
   These range from weighty biographies to a paperback jokebook.
Sample: ``Margaret Thatcher boasts that she is a self-made woman.
That certainly relieves the Almighty of a dreadful responsibility.''
   On Thursday, Mrs. Thatcher's 21 Cabinet colleagues, all male and
including only three survivors of her first Cabinet, will host a
dinner in her honor at 10 Downing Street.
   To beat all records for length of service, she would have to
overtake Lord Liverpool's 1812-27 tenure. ``I think you might say,
well within reach,'' a Thatcher aide said sardonically Wednesday.
   Whether they like it or not, many Britons agree.
   A Harris poll in London's liberal Observer newspaper showed 58
percent of those questioned want Mrs. Thatcher to step down within
a couple of years, but only 7 percent believe she actually will.
   A Gallup poll showed 67 percent of respondents dislike Mrs.
Thatcher personally, about the same as the 63 percent who said they
respect her.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
