<FIRST>r a AM-FloodingRescue     05-03 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flooding Rescue,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elderly Man Rescued From Submerged Car; `Nicest Cop,' He Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELMONT, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was trapped for 20 minutes when his
car was submerged on a flooded street during heavy rain, but he was
rescued by an off-duty police officer who dove in and swam to the
car.
   ``He's the nicest cop I ever met,'' said Willie Cooper, 71, of
Elmont, at a hospital where he was treated for exposure.
   ``It's all part of my job,'' said Nassau County Police Officer
Edward Powell.
   Cooper's car stalled Tuesday in water accumulating under a
parkway overpass during a heavy rain storm.
   ``I knew it was raining like the dickens but I didn't know the
water was that deep,'' Cooper said later Tuesday.
   He said he had stopped his car at the edge of the water but a
motorist behind him pushed him into the center of the rising pool,
where his engine stalled.
   The motorist who pushed him and several other cars turned around
and left.
   Cooper couldn't open his car doors because of the water, which
was up to the top of the steering wheel and rising quickly.
   And with the engine off he couldn't open his electric windows.
   ``I just sat there and waited,'' said Cooper.
   Powell, 28, was on his way home from the overnight shift when he
saw two cars under water.
   Still wearing his uniform, the 6-foot-2 officer jumped into the
approximately six feet of water and swam about 50 feet to the cars.
   There was no one in the first car he checked, but he spotted
Cooper in his car, tugged the driver's door open, grabbed Cooper
and carried him to safety.
   Cooper had spent about 20 minutes in the water.
   ``I'm not going to take any more baths like that one,'' he said.
</TEXT>
