<FIRST>r w AM-SouthernBorder     05-03 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Southern Border,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Immigration Officials Say Mexico Helping Slow Illegal Aliens</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Amnesty, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration authorities credited the Mexican
government Wednesday with helping stem a flood of Central American
refugees illegally trying to cross the U.S. border into Texas.
   James L. Buck, deputy immigration commissioner, said Mexican
authorities have arrested some 13,000 Central Americans trying to
enter Mexico from the south in the past six months, up from 12,000
in the previous year.
   The latest arrests occurred after Mexico tightened security
along its own southern border and began random highway checks of
motorists driving north through the country toward Texas, Buck said.
   Mexico's stepped-up enforcement, combined with tighter border
security imposed in February by U.S. authorities in south Texas,
has significantly reduced the flow of illegal aliens, Buck said.
   An Immigration and Naturalization Service task force set up Feb.
21 to stem a flow of illegal aliens seeking political asylum has
reported a sharp drop in border arrests since then, Buck said.
   The task force arrested 54 people on Tuesday, down from the 200
to 300 daily in February, Buck said.
   The task force now gets only a handful of asylum applications
each day, Buck said. In February it was receiving as many as 200 a
day. Following a court battle, INS won the right to detain people
seeking asylum while their applications were pending.
   Most of the applicants for asylum were rejected because U.S.
officials ruled they could not demonstrate a well-founded fear of
persecution at home. INS officials say most are fleeing poverty and
seeking better opportunities in this country and are therefore not
political refugees.
   As many as 2,500 were detained at the INS facility in Port
Isabel, Texas, where 1,500 people are currently being held. About
1,700 have been deported.
   The complement of 400 Border Patrol, INS, State Department and
immigration personnel who were sent to the Harlingen, Texas, area
is costing the government $4 million to $5 million a month, Buck
said.
   If current trends continue, ``probably by the end of the summer,
we will begin to see this entire task force sized down
significantly,'' Buck said.
</TEXT>
