<FIRST>r p AM-EversDefeated     05-03 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Evers Defeated,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Longtime Mississippi Civil Rights Figure Loses Mayoral Re-Election
Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Longtime political and civil rights figure
Charles Evers lost his bid for a fifth term as mayor of Fayette in
the Democratic primary, but Evers says he won't miss being the
center of attention.
   ``I'm happy to be out of the race and out of the limelight,''
the 66-year-old Evers said after losing Tuesday 390-248 to attorney
and longtime foe Kennie Middleton.
   ``It was time for a change,'' added Evers, who says he'll now
concentrate on helping youth in Fayette and Jefferson County,
located in southwest Mississippi and among the most impoverished
areas of the nation's poorest state.
   Middleton, 39, a Fayette native, faces independent candidate
William E. Smith in the June 6 general election.
   The always outspoken and often controversial Evers lost to
Middleton eight years ago and trailed in the balloting against
Middleton four years ago. In 1985, however, he won back the town's
top spot for another four-year term through legal challenges that
eventually were settled by the Mississippi Supreme Court. Evers
first was elected mayor in 1969.
   ``In 1985 he ran a very negative campaign and a campaign of lies
that there were going to be quick solutions to the problems in
Fayette,'' Middleton said.
   Middleton said Evers had done little over the years tobring
about positive change in Fayette, a town of just over 2,000 located
about 25 miles northeast of the historic Mississippi River city of
Natchez.
   Nearly 20 percent of Fayette residents, about 90 percent of whom
are black, were without jobs in March, the last month for which
figures are available. Mississippi had a March unemployment rate of
8.6 percent and the national rate was 5.2 percent.
   ``I think that for all of his visibility and name recognition,
there's one basic element missing,'' Middleton said. ``Those things
do not make him a good administrator, a good mayor. He has
celebrity status, but that does not necessarily equate with the
ability to run a city.''
   Evers says while he was a candidate, he didn't bother to
campaign because he ``could feel the people wanted a change.''
   ``But I didn't want to quit. I wanted the people to select
change.''
   Evers lost a 1978 U.S. Senate bid and ran unsuccessfully for
governor in 1971. He was defeated in a March 14 special election
for the state's central district highway commissioner post.
   Evers is the brother of Medgar Evers, who was field director of
the state National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People when he was gunned down by a sniper in 1963.
   He raised the ire of some civil rights leaders when, on June 22,
1988, he gave a humanitarian award named for his brother to Angolan
rebel leader Jonas Savimbi.
   ``I'm tired. Twenty years is enough,'' Evers said. ``I'm tired
of being out front. Let someone else be out front.''
   As for the future, Evers says he will continue living in Fayette
and will be supportive of the new adminstration.
   ``I will continue to travel, to promote, to have fun and live,''
he said. ``I will keep busy.''
</TEXT>
