<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Kidnapping     05-03 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Kidnapping,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diplomat Says Rebels Kidnapped French Priest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern Sudanese rebels have kidnapped a
Roman Catholic priest from France and are holding him in the
war-torn south or neighboring Uganda, a French diplomat said
Wednesday.
   French Embassy spokesman Jean-Luc Eyguiser identified the priest
only as the Rev. le Vacher and said he was kidnapped from Torit, a
southern Sudanese town that fell Feb. 26 to rebels of the Sudan
People's Liberation Army.
   Eyguiser refused to say when it is thought the priest was
abducted.
   In Paris, a spokesman for the White Fathers confirmed that a
Rev. Jean-Marie le Vacher, 62, has been assigned to Torit since May
1987. But the Rev. Louis Nouaille said the order has not heard of
any kidnapping.
   He said he last heard of le Vacher on March 17, when a colleague
returning from Torit told him the priest was in good health.
   ``Had there been any question of a kidnapping at the time, we
would have known,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   Nouaille did not dismiss the possibility le Vacher was kidnapped
later.
   He said the priest, born in the Mediterranean town of Giens,
``insisted on staying on in Torit despite the fighting.''
   Rebels in southern Sudan took up arms against the government in
1983, demanding autonomy and more economic development from the
Khartoum government, which is dominated by the majority Moslems.
Most southerners are a minority of Christians and animists.
   Rebels have kidnapped more than 20 foreign missionaries and
development workers over the years.
   In 1983, Sudanese commandos twice stormed rebel camps to free
foreign hostages, some held under death threats against demands for
money.
   Kidnappings since then appear to be publicity ploys, though
rebels claim they abduct victims for their own protection. Those
held are freed after varying lengths of time.
   This week, rebel leader John Garang announced a one-month
cease-fire to allow the government to work on a peace plan, and to
facilitate a massive U.N. relief effort to save 100,000 southerners
threatened by war-induced famine.
</TEXT>
