<FIRST>r a AM-BabyDeath     05-03 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby Death,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyers For Accused Father Urge Family To Tell All About Plug-Pulling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury heard testimony Wednesday from
relatives of a man accused of murdering his 16-month-old son,
comatose since last summer, by unhooking his hospital life-support
system.
   The wife, mother and brother of Rudy Linares, 23, of suburban
Cicero, testified behind closed doors before the panel, which can
decide if Linares should be indicted in the death of his son,
Samuel, who was buried Monday.
   Linares held hands with his wife, Tamara, as they and other
relatives entered the Cook County Criminal Court building.
   ``They're in deep grieving over this,'' said Kevin Smith, an
assistant public defender representing Linares.
   ``This has been a nine-month ordeal for them and it's been
exacerbated by the fact that their grieving has been done in
public. Rudy and Tammy can't just go off by themselves and
grieve,'' Smith said.
   The boy suffered brain damage after choking on a balloon or
small piece of aluminum foil last summer, officials have said.
   Authorities said Linares held Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's
Medical Center workers at bay with a gun early on April 26 and
unhooked the ventilator that kept Samuel alive for eight months.
According to police, Linares tearfully held Samuel until he died,
saying later he did it ``because I loved my son.''
   Linares, charged with first-degree murder, was not subpoenaed to
appear before the grand jury. He waited in his attorneys' office
while Mrs. Linares, his brother, Robert, and his mother, Marie
Linares, went to testify, his lawyers said.
   The family members all left the building later Wednesday without
talking to reporters.
   ``We encourage Rudy's wife, mother and brother to fully
cooperate in the sure belief that the grand jury will refuse to
indict,'' Smith said.
   If the grand jury chooses not to return an indictment, the case
would likely go to a Criminal Court judge, whose options would
include dropping the existing charge.
   Tamara Linares, accompanied by her lawyer, Daniel Coyne, was in
the grand jury room for about 25 minutes.
   Coyne said later that she did not invoke a 5th Amendment right
to avoid testifying, but he would not disclose what she said. ``I'm
convinced she's not a target'' of the investigation, he added.
   The couple have two other children, a boy and a girl under age 5.
</TEXT>
