<SECOND>AM-Brites,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW CANAAN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   College-bound students worn out by the
college application process have let off a little steam by burning
college catalogs and rejection letters.
   ``I'm going to savor this,'' said Mary Pescatello, 18, who was
about to throw her rejection letters from Princeton University and
Dartmouth College into the blaze. ``We've been under a lot of
pressure and I'm going to have fun doing this.''
   Pescatello was joined by about 100 other seniors and parents who
participated in the Tuesday evening bonfire dubbed ``Senior Burn
Out.''
   ``It's over. Burn. Burn,'' the students yelled.
   One of the parents received the largest roar of approval when
she threw in a textbook on how to take the Scholastic Aptitude
Tests, known as SATs.
   ``The kids have so much to worry about now,'' said David Hunt, a
member of the parents group that organized the bonfire. ``This is a
way to help them get some of that pressure off their minds.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUNSWICK, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With hundreds of McDonald's Big Macs
stored in its bomb bay, a P-3 Orion submarine hunter will lift off
May 11 on a mission to the Portuguese Azores, perhaps one of the
few places left on earth where there are no Golden Arches.
   The airborne food run was the brainchild of Azores Troop 1 of
the worldwide Direct Service Council of the Boy Scouts, which
decided that peddling a bit of fast food would be a good way to
raise money for a jamboree in West Germany.
   The flight from Brunswick Naval Air Station to the island 3,000
miles into the Atlantic will be a routine Navy logistics flight. It
would take place with or without the 2,000 Big Macs, which have
been ordered in advance from a local McDonald's restaurant.
   The military said the burgers will go into an unpressurized bomb
bay, where they will stay frozen during the flight. The other Big
Mac ingredients will be packed in special containers and stored in
the plane's cabin.
   Once the burgers are on the ground, they will be cooked by 21
scouts, who point out that some of the folks on the island will
probably buy them up fast after going up to three years with no
McDonald's food.
</TEXT>
