<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-NaziTrial     05-03 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Nazi Trial,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>Majdanek Guard Sentenced to Four Years in Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIELEFELD, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former guard at the Nazi
Majdanek concentration camp was sentenced Wednesday to four years
imprisonment for his role in the gas chamber deaths of 60 inmates.
   Karl-Friedrich Hoecker, 77, a former lieutenant in the SS, the
Nazis' special police, served as an aide to the Majdanek camp
commander in 1943 and 1944.
   The court found Hoecker guilty of complicity in the murder of 60
inmates. The court ruled that Hoecker was responsible for ordering
the Zyklon B poison gas used in Majdanek's gas chambers.
   More than 250,000 people, mostly Jews, were killed by the Nazis
at Majdanek, in Poland.
   In 1965, Hoecker was convicted by a Frankfurt court of
complicity in the deaths of at least 3,000 inmates, mostly Jews, at
the Auschwitz death camp during World War II. He served five years
of a seven-year sentence imposed by the Frankfurt court.
</TEXT>
