<FIRST>u w AM-US-Panama     05-03 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Panama,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says Electoral Fraud Being Planned in Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private human rights group said Wednesday
that conditions for next Sunday's elections in Panama ``fall far
short'' of minimum standards for a fair process, while the U.S.
government continued its campaign of daily attacks as well.
   The State Department accused Panamanian authorities of adopting
an ``increasingly threatening tone'' as the election approaches.
   A report issued by the International Human Rights Law group,
based in Washington, said the Panamanian government has taken a
number of steps to prevent an honest election, including the
forcing of prominent opposition leaders into exile.
   It also said that Panama's Electoral Tribunal is dominated by
pro-government representatives whose response to opposition
complaints has failed ``to inspire confidence in its impartiality.''
   The report said that the Panamanian government has demonstrated
both before and during the election campaign a willingness to
disregard the individual rights of its citizens.
   It noted that other human rights groups have alleged cases of
prolonged detention without charge, of torture and even of murder
of goverment critics.
   ``All of the evidence gathered by the Law Group in its study of
this election points unequivocally to the conclusion that the
conditions for the election fall far short of the minimum standards
required for a free and fair electoral exercise,'' the report said.
   At the State Department, spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said the
Panama Defense Forces and the government news media are undertaking
a ``campaign of intimidation'' aimed at reducing voter turnout and
discouraging popular protest once the victory of the government's
candidate, Carlos Duque, is announced.
   She noted that the government has warned that any media
reporting results other than those released by the government will
be punished by warnings, fines and possibly closure.
</TEXT>
