<FIRST>r a AM-MonroeCharged     05-03 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Monroe Charged,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Claims Bluegrass Star Hit Her With Bible</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALLATIN, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman says she was trying to end a
romantic relationship with 77-year-old bluegrass music star Bill
Monroe when he beat her with a Bible.
   Wanda Huff, 51, of Birmingham, Ala., said she was trying to get
Monroe to swear on the Bible that he was not seeing other women
when he grabbed the book and hit her with it at this farm near here.
   Huff, who was not seriously hurt in the incident Monday, filed
assault charges the same day against the Grand Ole Opry star. A
preliminary hearing is scheduled May 10.
   Monroe was arrested Tuesday and freed on $500 bond. He did not
return a telephone message left Wednesday by The Associated Press
at his Nashville office.
   Huff, who said she is the divorced mother of two, described
herself as Monroe's girlfriend for 3{ years.
   ``I was leaving him, and I wanted my things back,'' she said in
a copyright story Wednesday in the Nashville Banner.
   ``That's when he just started tearing things up,'' she said. ``I
told him to stop, and I asked him if we couldn't just end this
thing on a very peaceful note.''
   ``Things kept on, and finally I said, `Bill, if you haven't been
running around with these women, here's the Bible ...'
   ``I said, `Swear on it to me that you have not been running
around, because that way you'll tell me for real.'
   ``He said, `I'm not going to do it.' That's when he took the
Bible and _ swack _ right in the mouth. It was a big ol' Bible.''
   Huff, a dog trainer, said she pushed him away.
   ``Bill takes nitroglycerin for his heart, and all I need is for
the old man to drop dead on me and I'd be in trouble.''
   She said he also slapped her head, broke her glasses, and kicked
her.
   Huff said Monroe's farm manager, Archie Mills, came in the house
and helped her escape.
   Tony Conway of Buddy Lee Attractions, a Nashville booking agency
for Monroe, quoted the performer as saying Huff came to his house,
started destroying property and caused a major disturbance.
   ``He asked her to leave several times and she refused to
leave,'' Conway said. ``Mr. Monroe called the police, the police
came to the house, took statements from both parties, and I guess
she filed charges against him.
   ``He did state that he's totally shocked and that he's never
been arrested for anything in his life.''
   Conway said he did not ask the performer whether he struck the
woman.
   Monroe, a singer and mandolin player, has played with his band,
the Bluegrass Boys, on the Opry since 1939. ``Blue Moon of
Kentucky'' is Monroe's best-known song. In February, he won the
first Grammy award presented for bluegrass music.
</TEXT>
