<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Deaf     05-03 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Deaf,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Inaugurates Telephone Service for Deaf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush took a call in the Oval Office
on Wednesday from a student at the Arizona School for the Deaf and
Blind, inaugurating a service that allows speech- and
hearing-impaired people to talk to government officials and
agencies.
   By using a toll-free access number, Suzanne Smith, 17, who is
deaf, contacted a General Services Administration relay station,
using a Telecommunications Device for the Deaf, from her school in
Tucson.
   She typed a message to the center asking to reach the president,
and Bush, in the presence of photographers and reporters, took her
call.
   After some initial telephone interference that caused the
president to ask her to repeat herself, the call went ahead without
problems.
   ``Did you ever think about going to college, and, if so,
where?'' Bush asked Suzanne.
   ``I want to go to college,'' she replied. ``I would like to go
to Gallaudet University,'' a college for the deaf in Washington,
D.C.
   The young woman then asked Bush how the six puppies were doing.
   ``They're just fine,'' he said. ``The first one leaves tomorrow.
I'm not going to be too sorry to see them go. They're getting
pretty aggressive. We'll be glad to get back to one dog, if you
know what I mean.''
   First lady Barbara Bush will deliver one of the puppies of
Millie, the Springer spaniel, to her son, George W. Bush, when she
travels Thursday to Dallas.
</TEXT>
