<FIRST>r w AM-CourageAwards     05-03 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Courage Awards,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Honored For Courage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Courage Foundation, honoring four people
who served the public good, issued awards Tuesday to men who fought
against crime and inflation, a woman who demanded progress in the
classroom and a man who promoted public health.
   ``The idea is to recognize courage in our senior appointed and
elected officials,'' John Dyson, chairman of the New York-based
foundation said at a ceremony before granting crystal lions and a
$5,000 check to the recipients: U.S. Surgeon General C. Everett
Koop, former chairman of the Federal Reserve Board Paul Volcker,
former U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani, and teacher Gloria Pipkin.
   The Courage Foundation describes itself as a non-partisan,
non-political organization that draws its support from people of
all political persuasions.
   Kopp's award was for ``promoting the welfare of society in
general, not one group over another; and for his vigorous efforts
to educate the public about AIDS and cigarette smoking in the face
of harsh criticism.''
   Koop told the audience of about 30 he was ``a little
embarrassed.''
   Volcker's citation, according to a prepared statement, was for
``tightening the money supply during the early 1980s when it was
considered an unorthodox approach for combating the country's high
inflation rate.''
   Giuliani, who resigned as the former U.S. Attorney for the
Southern District of New York to run for New York City mayor, was
selected ``for his prosecution of organized crime kingpins, as well
as efforts to weed out corruption in the financial community.''
   He said described himself as ``very humbled'' and said he would
donate his $5,000 award check to a drug rehabilitation program.
   Ms. Pipkin, a Panama City, Fla., school teacher, was honored
``for spearheading a battle against school officials who banned the
classroom use of such books as `The Red Badge of Courage,'
`Hamlet,' and `Fahrenheit 451' because they contained material some
officials considered inappropriate.''
   Ms. Pipkin said in an interview that her suit against the school
board is still pending. She said her reading list was opposed by
Christian fundamentalists in the area and ``it got caught up in
missionary zeal.''
</TEXT>
