<FIRST>r w AM-People-Bennett-Baby     05-03 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Bennett-Baby,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>A New Baby in the Bennett Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug czar William J. Bennett and his wife,
Mary Elayne, became parents of a second son Wednesday, and mother
and son are doing fine at an undisclosed Washington area hospital,
a spokesman said.
   Bennett received a call from his wife that she was going into
labor shortly after he attended a breakfast meeting at the White
House, said spokesman Don Hamilton.
   A speech of the director of national drug control police before
several hundred members of the Washington Metropolitan Area
Interreligious Coalition was delayed by two hours until after Mrs.
Bennett delivered the 8-pound, 5-ounce baby.
   As Bennett began the talk at Washington Hebrew Congregation, he
told the gathering that his wife had insisted he give the speech.
   ``I walked out of the delivery room at 11:45, and I said, `I
think I'll just cancel.' And she said, `Who are you speaking to?'
And I told her, and she said, `We can't afford to give up all the
blessings.'''
   Bennett got hearty applause from the audience when Rabbi Joseph
P. Weinberg of the congregation gave Bennett a stuffed white bear
with blue features, adorned with several blue balloons.
   The Bennetts have another son, 5-year-old John.
   Asked the name of the new baby, Bennett told reporters, ``His
mother is working on that.''
</TEXT>
