<FIRST>r w AM-TreasuryRefunding     05-03 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Treasury Refunding,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Department Announces New Borrowing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department announced Wednesday
that it plans to borrow $28.75 billion next week to replenish the
government's coffers in one of four giant debt auctions it holds
during the year.
   Treasury officials said the auctions would include the sale of
three-year and 10-year notes and 30-year bonds to refinance $17.3
billion in maturing government debt and raise $11.5 billion in new
cash.
   The total debt being sold was in line with market expectations
and was very similar to the last debt sale held in February.
   At a briefing for reporters, William Bremner, Treasury deputy
assistant secretary for finance, said that the department expected
the government's debt, which currently stands at $2.76 trillion,
would hit the congressional limit of $2.8 billion sometime this
summer.
   ``We will hit the debt ceiling some time this summer and when it
occurs, it is our hope that Congress will raise the debt ceiling in
a timely fashion,'' Bremner said.
   In the past, extended debate over raising the limit on how much
the government can borrow has often become embroiled in questions
about spending and taxes and has thrown government operations into
a turmoil with threatened shutdowns because of a lack of cash.
   However, administration officials said they hope the recent
budget accord reached with Congress will avoid that situation this
year.
   According to Wednesday's announcement, the auctions for next
week will include:
   _ $9.75 billion in three-year notes in minimum denominations of
$5,000 to be auctioned on Tuesday.
   _ $9.5 billion in 10-year notes in minimum denominations of
$1,000 to be auctioned on Wednesday.
   _ $9.5 billion in 30-year bonds in minimum denominations of
$1,000 to be auctioned on Thursday.
</TEXT>
