<FIRST>r w AM-Pepper-Disabled     05-03 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepper-Disabled,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Proposes Nursing Home Quality Standards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Uniform national standards on such things as
cleanliness and food quality at boarding homes for the elderly
would override state regulations and be enforced by surprise
inspections under legislation introduced Wednesday by Rep. Claude
Pepper.
   ``We need to act immediately to end the abuse of our elderly and
disabled,'' Pepper, D-Fla., said in a statement. ``This bill seeks
to eradicate what is truly a tragedy of epic proportions.''
   He said many of the homes visited by congressional inspectors
``weren't fit for roaches, let alone the frail elderly and disabled
people who were forced to live there.''
   A spokesman for the Select Committee on Aging's subcommittee on
health said Pepper, who has been under hospital care since April 6,
signed the legislation last week during a visit to his office and
it was formally filed with the House clerk Wednesday.
   In a subcommittee report released earlier, investigators
determined there are more 1 million elderly and disabled residents
living in more than 68,000 board and care homes.
   Pepper said subcommittee investigators conducted unannounced
inspections of board and care homes in 10 states and ``found
evidence of fraud, waste and abuse in every state.''
   Federal and state governments spend an estimated $7 billion a
year to support elderly and disabled people in the homes, mostly
through the federal Supplemental Security Income program.
