<DOCNO> AP890503-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 1804EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-03 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Severe Weather Threat In The South Central U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmits to fix coding.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms with locally heavy rain developed Wednesday over
parts of Texas and Louisiana, and rain was widely scattered over
other sections of the nation.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed along a warm front over much
of eastern Texas and western Louisiana in the afternoon. Near
Houston, a thunderstorm winds gusted to 60 mph at Hobby Airport,
the National Weather Service said.
   Waco, Texas, got 1.01 inches of rain in the six hours before 1
p.m. CDT.
   An upper level weather disturbance moving southeastward into the
central Plains produced showers over parts of eastern Wyoming,
western South Dakota and Nebraska.
   Low pressure and a trailing cold front spread showers over
western Oregon and northwestern California.
   Elsewhere, a cold front over southern Canada spread clouds over
much of the Northeast, with showers over northern Maine, with
clouds also over parts of the upper Ohio Valley and lower Great
Lakes.
   Afternoon readings were only in the 40s over parts of the
Northeast, the central high Plains and the northern Rockies.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 39
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 95 at Gila Bend,
Ariz. Wednesday's low for the Lower 48 was 28 at Alamosa, Colo.,
and Marquette, Mich.
   For Thursday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from
northeastern Texas and the central Gulf Coast states to the Ohio
Valley and the middle Mississippi Valley. A cold front was expected
to spread scattered showers over the upper Mississippi Valley and
the northern Plains. Rain was forecast over the northern Rockies.
   Highs in the 50s were predicted over northern Maine and much of
Montana; mostly in the 60s 70 from New England to the Ohio Valley
and the Great Lakes region, and from the upper Mississippi Valley
to the central Rockies; above 80 across much of California,
Arizona, New Mexico and southern Nevada, and from Texas to Florida;
and in the 90s or above 100 in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
