<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Tennis     05-03 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Tennis,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Takes Time Out to Play Tennis with Bjorn Borg and Swedes.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush took a break from a tightly
scheduled potpourri of meetings Wednesday for an afternoon tennis
game with pro Bjorn Borg and two other Swedes.
   Bush and Borg teamed up against Swedish Ambassador Wilhelm
Wachtmeister and Ove Benstson, a former Davis Cup champion, in a
doubles match on the White House court.
   The president, dressed in white shorts and shirt with a yellow
vest and a white windbreaker that he shed after about 10 minutes of
warming up, energetically raced across the court and bounded back
and forth to the net.
   He apologized for his bad shots and hit his share of good ones.
   One shot into the net produced a particular grimace from the
president and an expletive between clenched teeth. ``Sorry,'' he
said quickly.
   When a reporter complimented the president on his game, Bush
replied, ``Answer to this game is to get a good partner.''
   But Bush's serve failed him in the first set. He double faulted
to lose the game point. With that, the small group of reporters and
camera crews on hand to observe were escorted back to the White
House press quarters. The score at that point was 2-1, in favor of
the president's team.
</TEXT>
