<FIRST>u a AM-TeachingAssistants 1stLd-Writethru a0728 05-03 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teaching Assistants, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0728,0849</SECOND>
<HEAD>Graduate Student Assistants Demanding Union Recognition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `About 90 percent ..., to CORRECT that 90 percent
of graduate students, sted all, took part in walkout; SUBS 20th graf, `The
association ..., to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With final exams just two weeks away, a
union of 3,200 graduate assistants walked out of University of
California-Berkeley classrooms Wednesday and onto picket lines to
press a demand for recognition as employees.
   ``Hey, hey! Ho, ho! Union busting's got to go!'' sign-carrying
teaching and research assistants chanted as they demonstrated at
every major entrance to the campus.
   Their union based here, the Association for Graduate Student
Employees, is affiliated with the United Auto Workers, and is the
vanguard of a burgeoning movement challenging the traditional view
of graduate students as scholars living off stipends. The students
say they are underpaid, overworked and often forced to go without
health and other benefits.
   ``This is not a question of mainly getting more money for me;
it's a matter of justice,'' said James Martel, a 24-year-old
teaching assistant in the political science department.
   ``We're not a bunch of Berkeley radicals demanding a change in
foreign policy; we just want to exercise a basic American right to
join a union and have our concerns represented at a bargaining
table,'' added Martel, who joined about 200 pickets as classes were
to begin.
   Union representatives claimed hundreds of classes were canceled
on the first day of the two-day strike. The university did not
check the number of canceled classes, but a Berkeley spokesman
called the protest largely symbolic.
   About 90 percent ot the 3,200 graduate assistants took part in
the walkout, the association claimed. There are about 9,000
graduate students at Berkeley.
   A victory by the Berkeley students could legitimize similar
demands eat many more campuses, said David Lambert, a member of the
association's executive board.
   ``The movement nationally on this issue is picking up steam,''
Lambert said. ``We're not making demands in a vacuum.''
   In the last 10 years, at least five major universities in
Florida, Wisconsin, Michigan, Oregon and New Jersey have recognized
graduate student assistants as employees.
   Teaching assistants at the University of Wisconsin in Madison
won collective bargaining from the Legislature in 1985. Their
union, affiliated with the American Federation of Teachers, is
negotiating their second contract.
   At the University of Michigan in Ann Arbor, the university and
its newly organized teaching assistants reached a collective
bargaining agreement earlier this year giving assistants a 14
percent pay raise over the next two years.
   At the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, the coordinating
committe of the teaching assistants' union voted last week to
affiliate with the UAW.
   The Berkeley union has been seeking recognition since 1983. Last
week, the state Public Employment Relations Board, ruling 2-1 in
favor of a university appeal, said a 1979 law forbids graduate
students from being treated as employees because their work duties
are part of scholarly training.
   The association plans to appeal to court.
   At the start of Berkeley's school day, Sproul Plaza, where
one-fifth of students generally enter, was unusually quiet.
Protesters handed out yellow armbands to supporters.
   ``The teaching assistants are the university when it comes to
learning here,'' said undergraduate Cammy Starks, 21, who said her
morning classes had been canceled and wore an armband. ``Everything
I've learned, I've learned from the assistants, not professors who
hardly ever get to know you.''
   Anthropology Professor Gerald Berreman, who joined pickets, said
graduate students handle 90 percent of the paper grading. ``I'm
here to show them how important they are to faculty,'' he said.
   On Tuesday, 71 professors in 10 departments sent a letter to
Chancellor Ira Michael Heyman endorsing the walkout and the
association's call for teaching assistants to cancel or reschedule
classes. Berkeley has 1,350 tenured professors.
   The association said that at least 500 Wednesday and Thursday
classes were canceled or rescheduled.
   According to a selective survey by the association of 307
classes through Wednesday afternoon, 66 percent were canceled, 25
percent were less than half-full, and 9 percent were at capacity.
   University spokesman Tom Debley said the results were not
necessarily representative of the campus, which has 23,000
undergraduates. He said it's not unusual for some students to skip
classes in the final weeks before finals to gain time to prepare
papers.
   Debley said the cost of pay raises and for providing health and
other benefits could have a substantial impact on university
budgets.
   According to a study by the association, teaching assistants
handle 58 percent of classroom work involving undergraduate
students and research assistants do about half the laboratory work.
   The university contends the work cannot be considered employment
because it is so intertwined with educational experience, Debley
said. Students receive annual stipends from the university or
research institutions averaging about $10,000 annually.
   ``It is more of a learning experience than an employment
experience,'' Debley said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
