<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay-Children     05-03 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay-Children,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Argentine Couple Accused Of Stealing Children Extradited</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paraguay on Wednesday extradited an
Argentine couple accused of stealing two children whose mother
disappeared during Argentina's ``dirty war'' against subversion in
the 1970s.
   Samuel Miara, a former Argentine federal policeman, his wife
Alicia and the 12-year-old twins, Gonzalo and Matias, were placed
aboard an Argentine commercial jetliner on a regular flight to
Buenos Aires.
   The Miaras say the twins are theirs.
   ``The children feel very badly and obviously I'm not doing too
well either,'' Miara told reporters shortly before police arrived
at their Asuncion home to take them to the airport.
   Another couple, former Argentine Army Maj. Norberto Bianco and
his wife Susana, are awaiting final legal proceedings in a similar
case involving two children.
   Both couples fled to Paraguay, then under the rule of
authoritarian president Gen. Alfredo Stroessner, in April 1986
after human rights groups accused them of stealing children of
pregnant women who disappeared during a military crackdown on
leftist subversion.
   Both couples refused to return to Argentina, claiming they were
victims of political persecution and would not receive a fair trial.
   Argentine requests for the extradition of the couples were tied
up in the courts for two years and strained relations between the
two nations. Argentine Ambassador Raul Quijano was recalled for
three months in 1987 after the Paraguayan attorney general
recommended against extradition.
   Stroessner and his 34-year regime were ousted in a military coup
on Feb. 3. Gen. Andres Rodriguez, elected president in Monday's
national elections, and the Supreme Court approved extradition of
the Miaras on March 6.
   Adalberto Rossetti, who claims to be the real father of the
Miara boys, has said that his wife, Liliana, 21 at the time, was
four months pregnant when she was arrested by security forces for
allegedly subversive activity as a student at the University of La
Plata. She never was seen again.
   Rossetti, an attorney in Buenos Aires, said he has never seen
the boys.
</TEXT>
