<FIRST>u w AM-NorthTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0609 05-03 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0609,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says North Jury Must Work 9-to-5 but Won't Push Harder for
Verdict</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with deliberations ended for day, subbing lead and inserting
1 graf after 6th graf, He said; adds 3 grafs at end with news media suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the Oliver North trial said
Wednesday he has imposed a 9-to-5 workday on the jury but won't
push harder for a verdict in the deliberations, which continued
inconclusively for the 11th day.
   ``I see no reason why I should intervene with the jury at all,''
U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell told lawyers for North and
the government _ both of whom had raised questions about the
lengthy deliberations.
   ``There is nothing the court can do to say that people must
deliberate,'' he said. ``I have no reason to think they aren't
deliberating; they are human beings and they are going to set their
own pace.''
   Gesell pointed out that ``not long ago a jury in this courthouse
took two months to reach a decision'' _ apparently referring to the
trial of nine members of a Black Hebrew sect convicted on
racketeering charges in 1986 by a jury that deliberated 200 hours
over 36 days.
   The nine women and three men on the North jury generally have
worked on the case five or six hours each weekday and a half-day on
Saturday.
   ``I felt that time was being wasted,'' Gesell said. ``They are
not starting as early as they could have and they have been leaving
at 4:15. I felt I should hold them in there until five.''
   He said he told U.S. marshals, who transport the jurors from the
hotel where they are sequestered, ``to get them in by nine and take
them home by five.''
   And so, at 5:03 p.m., the van pulled away from the courthouse
and the jury had completed another seven hours of work _ a total of
about 60 hours since it got the case on April 20. A court official
said deliberations stopped at 4:45.
   Prosecutor John Keker had suggested that Gesell might summon
jurors to the courtroom each day to learn what hours they wanted to
work the following day and to advise them they could deliberate
longer.
   The judge said the new hours would take care of that and an
eight-hour day was reasonable. The jurors, he said, worked shorter
days earlier because several suffered from colds and one had
problems with high blood pressure.
   North lawyer Brendan Sullivan asked why the jurors, who had been
using Gesell's courtroom, had returned to a smaller deliberation
room where they had complained of being crowded.
   Gesell said he needed the courtroom for other business and the
crowding problem had been solved by removing excess chairs.
   ``I think we'll just have to wait it out together until we hear
something concrete from them,'' he told the lawyers.
   Keker replied that ``we are running out of books (to read) in
our office.''
   Said Gesell: ``I understand there is a movie you could look at''
_ an apparent reference to the two-part television drama on ``The
Rise and Fall of Oliver North'' that finished Tuesday night.
   Charges against North include lying to Congress and the attorney
general and obstructing investigations into the Iran-Contra affair,
particularly his White House efforts to help the Nicaraguan rebels
at a time when official U.S. aid was banned. Other charges accuse
North of illegally profiting from the enterprise.
   Meanwhile, the Justice Department urged Gesell to deny a news
media request for a document that was given to the jury but not to
the press. The department said the news organizations should pursue
the matter through the Defense Department _ ``the executive branch
agency responsible for classifying the information at issue.''
   Said the Justice Department: ``This court cannot serve as a
substitute for such a process.''
   The organizations pressing for the document _ a summary of
intelligence ``intercepts'' made while a shipment of missiles was
being sent to Iran in 1985 _ are The Associated Press; Cable News
Network Inc.; Capital Cities-ABC Inc.; CBS Inc.; Dow Jones &amp; Co.
Inc.; National Broadcasting Co. Inc.; National Public Radio; The
New York Times Co.; the Times Mirror Co., and The Washington Post.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
