<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 1855EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FishWars     05-03 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fish Wars,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Says US-Japan Reach Tentative Agreement On Driftnet Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Japan have reached a
tentative agreement over driftnet fishing in the northern Pacific
Ocean, Rep. Jolene Unsoeld said Wednesday.
   Unsoeld, D-Wash., outlined details of what she said is an
agreement that might end the dispute over use of the huge nets. She
was critical of the pact.
   An estimated 700 fishing boats from Taiwan, South Korea and
Japan use driftnets, which can stretch 35 miles in length and cover
more than 30,000 square miles of ocean on any given day.
   American fishermen claim that vessels from Taiwan, South Korea
and Japan use driftnets to illegally snare millions of tons of
salmon under the guise of squid fishing. Fishing groups have said
the illegal fishing has already impacted salmon runs in Alaska,
Washington state and Oregon.
   Unsoeld, D-Wash., released what she said are details of the
pact, based on talks with unnamed officials from the State
Department and the U.S. fishing industry.
   She said the pact calls for:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _ 2 observers stationed aboard Japanese driftnet vessels to
monitor their catch. There are an estimated 400 vessels in the
Japanese driftnet fleet.
   _ An increase from four to five in the number of Japanese patrol
vessels in the North Pacific and an increase in patrol days for the
vessels from the current 250 per year to 600 per year. U.S.
enforcement officers will be stationed aboard the patrol vessels.
   _ Stiffer Japanese penalties for ships caught illegally driftnet
fishing.
   _ Marking of all driftnets so the owners of those cast adrift
can be identified.
   _ A ban on the high-seas transfer of fish between Japanese
trawlers and freighters, which carry the fish back to port.
   Unsoeld said the Japanese refused to agree to a U.S. State
Department request for a pilot program to place transponders on a
dozen or so Japanese vessels. Using satellites, the U.S. could have
monitored the movements of the ships.
   The U.S. is considering a transponder test using American
vessels, Unsoeld said.
   Other congressional sources, who asked not to be identified,
confirmed most of the details supplied by Unsoeld, but added that
the agreement was for only one year and the Japanese have
essentially told the State Department ``take it or leave it.''
   The sources also said the Japanese have indicated they plan to
move the legal driftnet zone slightly northward, though exactly how
far remains unclear.
   The existing driftnet zone was designed to keep fishing vessels
far south of the migration routes of North American salmon.
   Ed Wolfe, the State Department's ambassador for ocean and
fisheries, was out of his office and unavailable for comment
Wednesday. Earlier this week, Wolfe told a House subcommittee that
an agreement with the Japanese was close.
   Congressional sources said the agreement has actually been
signed by Japanese officials and initialed by U.S. negotiators.
   ``I am extremely apprehensive that this agreement will not be
adequate,'' said Unsoeld. ``I am also not sure that this will meet
the requirements of the 1987 Driftnet Act.''
   Under that act, if Japan and other countries with driftnet
fleets have not entered into monitoring and enforcement agreements
with the United States by June 29, the president could impose trade
sanctions.
   Unsoeld said she was upset that the Japanese had refused to
agree to a transponder test program.
   ``We may have negotiated away our ability to put any teeth in
our action,'' she said. ``It's absolutely goofy. If they aren't
violating any existing agreements, why are they objecting to us
placing transponders on their ships?''
   Unsoeld also said she felt the number of observers called for in
the agreement falls short of what was needed to provide
``sufficient'' data on the impact of driftnet fishing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
