<FIRST>r w AM-TradeSanctions     05-03 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade Sanctions,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Products Could Face Stiff Duties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills on
Wednesday released a target list of Japanese products which could
face 100 percent duties, doubling their price in this country,
under trade retaliation being considered by the Bush administration.
   The list of potential target products for the higher tariffs
ranges from color televisions to tape recorders and photocopying
machines.
   The broad variety of goods, including some of the most popular
Japanese electronic devices sold in this country, served to
emphasize the seriousness with which the Bush administration is
viewing this latest trade dispute with Japan.
   Mrs. Hills announced on Friday that the government was
considering sanctions against Japan because of a finding by the
administration that the country has not opened its
telecommunications market to American companies.
   Mrs. Hills said at the time that the retaliation could be
avoided if the Japanese make meaningful concessions.
   A final list of products which could be subject to the higher
tariffs will be drawn up after a hearing scheduled for May 24. That
list will be selected from the broader one released on Wednesday.
   In making the telecommunications decision, Mrs. Hills found that
Japan had limited U.S. access to its market for car telephones and
business radios.
   The Motorola Co., the principal American maker of these
products, has contended that it has been denied access to the
Japanese market. It maintains that with fair access it could
achieve sales in Japan of about $400 million a year.
   The Japanese have argued that there is a shortage of radio
frequencies for such services.
</TEXT>
