<FIRST>r a AM-ChelseaSchools     05-03 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chelsea Schools,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chelsea-Boston University Contract Signed, Delivered to Lawmakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHELSEA, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boston University's controversial plan to
run Chelsea's ailing schools went to state lawmakers Wednesday,
with supporters confident the promised renaissance will dispel
doubts about putting a public concern in private hands.
   ``This is the happiest day of my 45 years in Chelsea,'' said
Mayor John Brennan, who sent the Legislature a home rule petition
that would install Boston University as manager of its school
system.
   The proposal has the backing of Democrat Richard Voke, chairman
of the powerful House Ways and Means Committee, and is expected to
pass. Others were less enthusiastic.
   School Committee Chairwoman Elizabeth McBride was against the
proposal, citing concerns that the university would not consult
with parents, teachers and administrators.
   Supporters say the plan is Chelsea's last chance to escape the
plague of poverty: shabby buildings, low test scores and a high
school dropout rate of 17 percent.
   Opponents, including teachers and Hispanic groups, say the
proposal also would turn Chelsea into a experimental education
laboratory for university students.
   Hispanics oppose the contract, signed by representatives of
Boston University and Chelsea's schools, saying university
officials have ignored requests for more information about
bilingual programs.
   Boston University President John Silber said he would heed
concerns raised.
   ``We are not going to privatize the schools,'' Silber said. ``We
are going to manage the public schools and they are going to remain
public.''
   The Massachusetts Federation of Teachers criticized the signing
of the contract before lawmakers act as ``indicative of the private
and arrogant manner in which the entire process ... has been
conducted.''
   Chelsea, a city of about 25,000 with a sizable immigrant
population, has seen its tax base shrink and faces cuts of about
$2.8 million in next year's school budget due to a statewide budget
crunch.
   Silber said he would lobby for funds from private donors, the
federal government and the state, advertising the reforms of
Chelsea as a possible road to reviving the area a few miles from
Boston.
   ``Chelsea is a city waiting for a renaissance to happen,''
Silber said. ``If we can improve those schools, people will move
back into Chelsea.''
</TEXT>
