<SECOND>AM-Recreation,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Recreation Bill Despite GOP Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Interior Committee on Wednesday
approved legislation to protect open land and build recreational
facilities, but Republicans on the committee walked out in protest
before the committee took its vote.
   The bill, known as the American Heritage Trust Act, would make
the existing land and water conservation fund and historic
preservation fund permanent trusts that would generate $1 billion a
year for land acquisition and construction of recreational
facilities like golf courses, ball fields, pools and marinas.
   Republicans on the committee objected to more government buying
of land.
   ``This nation's heritage is private ownership of land, not
public owners and control,'' said Rep. Larry Craig, R-Idaho.
   But Rep. Morris Udall, D-Ariz., chairman of the committee, said
the bill is necessary because too many communities in the United
States are being overdeveloped with insufficient recreational
facilities.
   Craig said the Republicans walked out when it became apparent
that amendments they offered would not get through.
</TEXT>
