<FIRST>r i AM-AfghanKing     05-03 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan King,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain, India Deny Role In Afghan King Plot</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain and India on Wednesday denied involvement
in any plot to return exiled King Zahir Shah of Afghanistan to
power.
   Independent Television News said Tuesday that Britain, the
Soviet Union and India were involved in a scheme that was foiled by
Afghan rebels who cut off Kandahar airport in southern Afghanistan,
and prevented the king's return. ITV quoted Moslem rebels fighting
the Marxist government in Kabul as its source.
   ``There's no question of us being involved,'' said a Foreign
Office spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with British
custom.
   ``We're not a player of that degree (in the region) and as far
as we're aware no one is.''
   In New Delhi, Foreign Ministry spokesman Aftab Seth said: ``I
would second the comments by (the) British Foreign Office
spokesman.''
   In Rome, where the exiled king lives, his spokesman, Gen. Abdul
Wali, said Tuesday: ``I know nothing about it.''
   The 74-year-old king has lived in Rome since he was ousted in a
1973 coup.
</TEXT>
