<SECOND>AM-Contracting Indictment, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0739,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former D.C. Official Indicted; Some Money Ended Up in Barry Fund</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Barry comment, inserting new 6th graf and eliminating
11th graf pvs, Efforts to</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury on Wednesday indicted two
men, including a former top city official who is a friend of Mayor
Marion S. Barry Jr., on charges they steered $3 million in
contracts to friends.
   Prosecutors alleged that some of the money in what they
described as ``a seamy web of corruption,'' ended up in Barry's
1986 reelection campaign fund, but they didn't say how.
   A source familiar with Barry's 1986 campaign, commenting on
condition he not be named, said the two indicted men organized an
Atlanta fund-raiser for Barry's reelection bid. The indictment does
not mention the Atlanta event.
   David E. Rivers, who formerly served as director of the city's
human services department, and John B. Clyburn, a prominent
contractor, were indicted on charges of conspiring to defraud the
city government by steering health services contracts to friends
and to a company owned by Clyburn.
   Rivers, a close friend of Barry, also faces two counts of
agreeing to accept a bribe, while Clyburn has been charged with
helping to bribe him.
   Barry said in a prepared statement, ``I should remind the public
that an indictment does not automatically mean an individual is
guilty.'' He added, ``I will have no further comment. ... My focus
continues to be on managing the District of Columbia government.''
   The charges come after a 21-month grand jury probe that followed
a two-year undercover FBI investigation into the city's contracting
procedures.
   If convicted of all charges, the two men could face maximum
prison terms of 50 years.
   ``This indictment alleged a seamy web of corruption, of
concealment, of manipulation and of self-dealing by one of the most
senior officials in the District of Columbia government,'' said
U.S. Attorney Jay B. Stephens. ``The investigation is continuing
... and a number of other issues remain in this case.''
   Stephens alleged that both Clyburn and Rivers took ``about 10
percent off the top'' in kickbacks for the 20 contracts and
contract extensions mentioned in the indictment.
   He declined to elaborate on how much money might have been
steered to Barry's 1986 reelection bid, or whether the mayor or any
of his top campaign officials were aware of the situation.
   Rivers was out of town Wednesday, his attorney John Mercer said.
Mercer said before the indictment was announced that he was unaware
of any pending charges.
   The 49-page indictment charges that from 1983 through May 1987,
Rivers and Clyburn influenced the city's contracting process to
steer both sole-source and competitively-bid contracts to their
friends.
   Rivers took a leave of absence from his city job in August 1987
after he became a target of the investigation.
</TEXT>
