<FIRST>r a AM-FamilyPoisoning     05-03 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Family Poisoning,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Formally Overturns Conviction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARCADIA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who freed a man imprisoned for 21
years in the poisoning deaths of his seven children said the
killer's identity may never be known, and raised several questions
about the investigation and prosecution.
   James Richardson, 53, was released from prison April 25 after
Judge Clifton Kelly determined his 1968 trial was unfair. The
former orange picker has moved to a diet clinic run by former
comedian Dick Gregory in Fort Walton Beach.
   A written order overturning Richardson's conviction was filed
Tuesday by Kelly, a retired circuit judge appointed to hear the
case. Kelly offered a long list of unresolved questions in the case.
   Janet Reno, a special prosecutor who found evidence of
substantial trial errors and perjured testimony, still must
recommend whether Richardson should face retrial.
   He was serving a life sentence for first-degree murder in the
poisoning death of his eldest stepdaughter Oct. 25, 1967.
   Kelly's order asked who should be blamed for the unfair trial,
why anyone would have wanted to frame Richardson as the defense
contended, and why three cellmates who testified against Richardson
told contradictory stories.
   The judge also wondered how a wino who lived near the
Richardsons found a bag of the pesticide parathion after an
unsuccessful police search, why former police chief Richard Barnard
was told to stay off the case, how family baby sitter Betsy Resse
served the poisoned meal and why parathion was found in other parts
of the apartment.
   ``At this late date, who really poisoned the children will quite
likely never be known,'' Kelly wrote.
   Prosecutors claimed Richardson poisoned the children to collect
on $1,000 insurance policies, but the jury was never told that the
insurance hadn't been purchased.
   Because Reno and Richardson's attorneys agreed the trial was
unfair, Kelly said, ``It would serve no useful purpose for the
court to now make a detailed finding of fact.''
   Kelly didn't rule on whether prosecutors or investigators
suppressed evidence or committed perjury. Gov. Bob Martinez ordered
an investigation of the allegations of public wrongdoing after
Richardson was freed.
</TEXT>
