<FIRST>r a AM-DancingMom     05-03 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dancing Mom,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mom Arrested, Children Taken After Dancing In Living Room</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palm Springs woman who rushed out of
her shower to dance to a Gladys Knight video and was arrested after
neighbors peering through her window filed a complaint has sued the
police.
   Darleen Scott, who was jailed and lost her two girls to the
state for two days, sued the Palm Springs Public Safety Department
on Tuesday for false arrest, harassment and false imprisonment in
the January 1988 incident.
   ``I was treated like a murderer, like I was no good. I was in my
own house minding my own business,'' said Ms. Scott, a 31-year-old
nurse's aide.
   She said she had asked her daughters to call her out of the
shower if a music video of the song ``Love Overboard'' by Gladys
Knight and the Pips appeared on the television.
   Neighbors peering through a window into her third-floor
apartment thought she was nude when she rushed into her living room
to dance to the song, and filed a child abuse report with the
police. She later told officers she was wearing a brown towel.
   She was arrested on three counts of lewd and lascivious behavior
in the presence of a child _ her two daughters and a 14-year-old
girl looking through the window, said West Palm Beach attorney W.
Trent Steele, who is representing Ms. Scott on behalf of the
American Civil Liberties Union.
   While she spent a night in the Palm Beach County Stockade, her
daughters, aged three and 10 at the time, spent about two days in
separate foster homes.
   The separation was prolonged because social workers with the
state Department of Health and Rehabilitative Services ``couldn't
find one of the girls'' after they placed her in a home, Steele
said.
   The State Attorney's Office dropped all the charges against
Scott in May 1988.
   Palm Springs Village Attorney Donald Kohl declined comment on
the suit, saying he had not seen it.
   Ms. Scott's suit charges the Public Safety Department deprived
her of state and constitutional rights and failed to teach officers
how to handle alleged child abuse cases.
   The complaint also says police ignored accepted practice by not
allowing social workers to investigate before taking the children
away from the mother.
