<FIRST>r i AM-Netherlands     05-03 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Netherlands,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dutch Premier Quits, September Elections Seen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Ruud Lubbers formally
submitted the resignation of his seven-year coalition government
Wednesday, and early elections are being scheduled for Sept. 6 or
13, the government announced.
   Elections had not been due until May 1990.
   The announcement followed a 90-minute visit by Lubbers to Queen
Beatrix late Wednesday, his second of the day, and talks between
the monarch and the leaders of all nine political parties
represented in Parliament.
   In his first meeting, Lubbers submitted the resignation of his
entire 13-minister, center-right Cabinet in a clash over part of a
$3.65 billion plan to clean up the heavily polluted Dutch
environment by the year 2010.
   The plan came under heavy fire from the right-wing People's
Party for Freedom and Democracy, junior partner in his government
since 1982. It objected to Lubbers' proposal to end certain income
tax deductions for Dutch commuters who daily drive long distances
to and from work.
   The party threatened a no-confidence motion, precipitating the
government's fall.
   Lubbers' Cabinet will stay on as caretaker until a new
government is formed.
   Political observers predict Lubbers, of the Christian Democratic
Appeal party, will drop the People's Party for Freedom and
Democracy in a new coalition that would include the left-wing Labor
Party.
   Never in postwar Dutch history has any single party garnered
enough votes in the 150-seat Parliament to form a government on its
own.
</TEXT>
