<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Spy     05-03 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Spy,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Two Men Who Claim They Helped Soviet Spy Escape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men who wrote a book claiming they helped
Soviet spy George Blake escape to Moscow from a London jail 33
years ago were arrested on Wednesday.
   Patrick Pottle, 50, and Michael Randle, 55, went to a London
police sation at the request of the police and were arrested,
Scotland Yard said.
   They were then escorted to their homes, Pottle in London and
Randle in the northern town of Bradford, Yorkshire.
   They were not charged. A police spokesman, speaking anonymously,
said they would be granted bail while a report was sent to the
Director of Public Prosectuions, who is responsible for deciding on
prosecution.
   Officers from Scotland Yard's Special Branch, which deals with
subversion, were searching Pottle's home when a reporter telephoned
him.
   ``They are putting things in bags. I've been expecting this, so
I gathered some items together and they have been in a pile on the
kitchen table for about 10 days, waiting,'' Pottle said.
   Pottle, an antiques dealer, added that he and Randle, a
researcher, expect to go to prison eventually.
   A new book titled ``The Blake Escape'' by the two men and a TV
film about the case described how they harbored Blake after he
broke out of Wormwood Scrubs prison in 1966 and how Randle smuggled
him out of Britain in a camper van to East Germany.
   Sean Bourke, a former fellow prisoner of Blake, directed his
escape by radio messages. Bourke, now dead, later wrote a book
describing how he was invited to the Soviet Union and treated as a
hero by the Soviet KGB secret police.
   Bourke did not mention Pottle and Randle in his book. Last year,
they admitted their part in the case to a reporter.
   Blake was sentenced to 42 years and jailed in 1961 after
pleading guilty to spying for the Soviets throughout the 1950s
while working for MI6, the British intelligence gathering agency.
The sentence _ the longest sentence for espionage ever handed down
by a British court _ was regarded as representing one year for each
betrayed agent.
   At the end of a secret trial, the judge said Blake was suspected
of betraying 42 British agents in Eastern Europe who are believed
to have been killed.
   Pottle and Randle were founder members with the philosopher
Bertrand Russell of the Committee of 100, which protested nuclear
weapons. They met Blake in prison while serving 18-month sentences
for organizing a demonstration at a U.S. Air Force base.
   The two men said they helped the spy escape because they felt a
42-year sentence was inhumane.
   More than 100 lawmakers of the governing Conservative Party
signed a House of Commons paper demanding Pottle and Randle be
prosecuted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
