<FIRST>r a AM-People-JamesBrown     05-03 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-James Brown,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Singer James Brown Spends 56th Birthday in Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soul singer James Brown spent an
apparently uneventful 56th birthday in prison Wednesday, with
corrections officials saying he had no visitors and probably no
birthday cake, either.
   Warden Judy Anderson at State Park Correctional Center said
unless Brown bought a cake from the canteen, he didn't have any
birthday cake. The prison menu included chocolate pudding for lunch
and sweet potato pie for dinner.
   ``He won't have any birthday cake or anything,'' said deputy
warden W.E. Doctor.
   Brown is serving a six-year sentence for aggravated assault and
failing to stop for police during a chase across the Georgia-South
Carolina border on Sept. 26.
   He works on kitchen detail in the mornings and in the evenings,
the ``Godfather of Soul,'' whose gold records include ``Please,
Please, Please,'' and ``Papa's Got a Brand New Bag,'' conducts the
prison choir.
   New York activist Al Sharpton said Wednesday in a telephone
interview from Brooklyn, N.Y., that he was continuing his efforts
to have Brown released from prison.
   ``James Brown has done six months. I think he's done enough
time,'' Sharpton said.
   Sharpton said he would protest the actions of a judge who last
week brought Brown from jail to the Richland County curthouse to
sign autographs.
   ``I think that his judge has underscored the point I was making
for six months, that this is a judicial joke to continue to hold
James Brown,'' Sharpton said of Circuit Judge Frank Eppes.
   In Chapel Hill, N.C., a group known as the North Carolina
Committee to Free James Brown, played tapes in front of a
courthouse as part of the ``Free James Brown Rally'' Wednesday.
   One of the organizers of the rally was Don Stanford, a trial
lawyer in Chapel Hill who loves Brown's music and who said he
thinks Brown is not getting a square deal.
   ``My position is this. I practice criminal law. I think six
years is just way out of line. It is a very harsh sentence,''
Stanford said.
   Brown did not have any visitors Wednesday, said Bennish Brown,
spokesman for the South Carolina Department of Corrections. The
singer's wife, Adrienne, was the only person who would have been
allowed to visit, but she did not show up, the spokesman said.
   The spokesman, who is no relation to Brown, said the Rev. Jesse
Jackson planned to visit the singer in prison Thursday morning.
   Jackson met with the singer in Columbia in February and appeared
before the state parole board on Brown's behalf on March 8.
   Brown will not be eligible for parole until mid-1991, said Tom
Hudson, spokesman for South Carolina Probation, Parole and Pardon
Services.
</TEXT>
