<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-USSub     05-03 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US Sub,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search for Two Missing U.S. Navy Sailors Called Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Japanese ships and planes on Wednesday
gave up the search for two crewmen washed overboard from a U.S.
Navy submarine off southwestern Japan two days earlier, officials
said.
   The Maritime Safety Agency, Japan's coast guard, ended its
search after sunset Wednesday, an agency official said on condition
of anonymity. He said the U.S. Navy told the agency it stopped
searching at noon Wednesday.
   U.S. military officials identified the sailors as Lt. Walter
Gray Womble III, 36, of Tampa, Fla., and James David Lear, 20, of
Washburn, Ill. Lear's rank was not available.
   A U.S. Air Force patrol plane and Navy ship, along with three
Japanese patrol boats and a Japanese plane, had been searching for
the two sailors since an unexpected wave washed three crewmen
overboard Monday from the diesel-powered submarine Barbel.
   One of the sailors was spotted by a plane and rescued by the
2,145-ton submarine. None of the three wore lifejackets, U.S.
military officials said.
   The submarine was off Japan's southernmost main island of
Kyushu, about 650 miles southwest of Tokyo, at the time of the
accident, the U.S. Military Liaison Office in Japan said.
   The Barbel, built in 1956, is equipped with six torpedo tubes
and had a crew of 77, a U.S. military official said on condition of
anonymity.
</TEXT>
