<FIRST>u w AM-BeefDispute     05-03 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beef Dispute,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Partial Resolution of Beef Fight Announced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration on Wednesday announced
a partial resolution of a contentious trade dispute with the
12-nation European Community over the issue of hormones in American
beef.
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills and Agriculture Secretary
Clayton Yeutter said that both U.S. and European negotiators had
agreed to accept the initial recommendations of a task force
studying the dispute.
   That action will allow resumption of sales of about 15 percent
of the $100 million U.S. beef which is normally shipped to Europe.
However, a dispute over the other 85 percent of U.S. beef exports
remains to be resolved, U.S. officials said.
   Under the agreement, U.S. beef producers who wish to export beef
not treated with growth hormones to Europe may do so.
   But American officials said they still maintained that Europe's
ban on imports of beef from cattle raised on growth-producing
hormones represented an illegal trade barrier masquerading as a
health measure.
   American officials had refused to comply with the ban by
certifying Europe-bound beef as hormone-free and instead slapped
retaliatory tariffs on European goods valued at about $100 million,
a sum equal to the lost sales of American beef.
   However, after the tariffs were imposed on Jan. 1 by the Reagan
administration, officials of the incoming Bush administration began
to search for a compromise to the dispute.
   At a meeting on Feb. 18, Mrs. Hills and Yeutter agreed to look
for a way to certify as hormone-free as much U.S. beef as possible.
   At the time, the United States indicated it would reduce its
$100 million in punitive tariffs by the amount of U.S. beef Europe
was willing to accept.
   The agreement Wednesday follows the recommendations of a task
force of officials from both sides established to study the matter.
The partial resolution will cover high quality grades of beef being
shipped to Europe but will not cover the other 85 percent of beef
trade which includes so-called ``variety meats'' such as livers,
tongues and kidneys.
   Mrs. Hills said that the task force studying the situation will
continue searching for ways to include more American beef and will
report back before June 15.
   In a statement, Mrs. Hills called the interim agreement a
``positive step'' toward de-escalating what had become a
contentious dispute between America and one of its largest trading
partners.
   ``To the extent that U.S. beef and beef products are shipped to
the European Community under this measure, we will reduce U.S.
retaliatory measures on imports from the EC,'' she said.
   Yeutter said that while the U.S. position remains the same that
American beef containing the hormones presents no health risk, the
administration did not want to ``stand in the way of producers who
are willing and able to meet the EC's requirements'' for
hormone-free beef.
   Under the agreement, American ranchers who want to export
hormone-free beef to Europe will be given a set of requirements
that they will have to meet by European officials, who will also
establish a monitoring system to insure that the beef being shipped
does not contain hormones.
</TEXT>
