<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-PLO     05-03 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-PLO,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Envoy Says U.S. Likely To Cut WHO Funding If PLO Joins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas Pickering said
Wednesday the United States probably will cut off funding to the
World Health Organization if it admits the PLO, and would do the
same to any other U.N. agency that admits the PLO.
   Pickering told reporters the Palestine Liberation Organization
should withdraw or postpone its application to join the WHO when it
meets in Geneva next week. He said the United States had been
conducting a vigorous lobbying campaign against the membership.
   ``The United States has made known it is not prepared to fund
WHO under these circumstances (PLO membership) because the PLO is
not, by legal definition, a state,'' Pickering said.
   He said PLO membership would harm the WHO and endanger the
delicate peace process in the Middle East by ``polarizing'' the
situation.
   Last week, Secretary of State James A. Baker III said the State
Department would recommend to Congress that WHO funding be
withdrawn if the organization admits the PLO. Pickering extended
the threat to any other U.N. agency that might admit the PLO.
   No other U.N. agencies have indicated they are considering
admitting the PLO as a member.
   The United States donates one quarter of the annual WHO budget,
or approximately $75 million.
   Zuhdi Labib Terzi, the PLO's permanent U.N. observer, said he
had no immediate comment on Pickering's statement about other U.N.
agencies. Earlier, however, he said the PLO would press ahead with
efforts to join the WHO despite U.S. threats.
   To be admitted to the 166-member WHO, the PLO needs a simple
majority vote when the agency meets May 8. Admission would enhance
the PLO's credibility and prestige in the international community.
   ``There is anguish that this is ill-timed,'' Pickering, a former
ambassador to Israel, told reporters. ``This is a wrong and
ill-conceived notion and it is time to try to find a formula or a
way to postpone this.''
   He said the United States would not object if the WHO
established a group to study the question.
   Although the United States decided last year to establish a
dialogue with the PLO, it does not recognize the self-declared
Palestinian state in Israel's occupied territories.
   Pickering said that even some key Arab states do not support PLO
membership because the PLO does not satisfy the traditional
definition of statehood.
   He conceded that a halt to U.S. funding could harm worthy WHO
programs, like those on AIDS and nutrition. But he said there would
be discussions on how the United States could continue to spend the
funds effectively.
</TEXT>
