<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Killer 1stLd-Writethru a0714 05-03 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Killer, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0714,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uproar Over Students' Election of Convicted Cop Killer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to add background. Pick up 10th pvs, `Silcott
and...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To the British public, Winston Silcott is the
leader of a mob that hacked a policeman to death in a north London
riot.
   But to some students at the world-renowned London School of
Economics, his conviction and life sentence are an injustice. By
making Silcott the honorary president of their student union, they
have provoked a furious response from the government as well as
fellow students.
   ``People who come here are supposed to be intelligent. If that
is so, how can they elect this lunatic?'' asked Daniel Kasmir, a
20-year-old social sciences freshman, between classes at the
central London campus on Wednesday. ``It gives the college a bad
name.''
   In Parliament, Education Secretary Kenneth Baker branded
Silcott's election ``shameful and despicable'' and told Parliament:
``This is the loony left hijacking a great institution.''
   But Mike Cronshaw, 23, a post-graduate in economics, said the
union had achieved its aim: to refocus attention on the validity of
the convictions of 49 young men after bloody rioting in the
racially mixed Tottenham district on Oct. 16, 1985, in which a
white policeman was killed.
   ``If we do believe in British standards of justice, the
beyond-reasonable-doubt criterion, then if it is not seen to be
applied by normal standards, there is grounds for a retrial,''
Cronshaw said.
   About 100 left-wing students elected 29-year-old Silcott to the
one-year ceremonial term at the union's sparsely attended Annual
General Meeting Thursday. A bigger turnout tried to reverse the
decision at an angry meeting Tuesday but failed by 26 votes to
achieve the necessary two-thirds majority.
   The National Union of Students announced Wednesday it will hold
a secret ballot of the college's 4,000 students.
   College governors pledged to review the college union's funding,
while the school's Afro-Caribbean Society denounced the vote as
``deplorable, insensitive and patronizing to the black race.''
   Silcott and another black, along with a Turkish teen-ager, were
convicted of murdering Keith Blakelock with machetes, and 43 out of
69 others were convicted and jailed for riot and affray.
   More than 500 youths fought battles with police in and around
the Broadwater Farm housing project in the worst of a wave of
racial unrest in British cities in the fall of 1985. It was the
first riot to claim a policeman's life.
   Shaun Waterman, 24, a spokesman for the Broadwater Farm Defense
Campaign, says the hunt for the killers turned into ``basically a
lucky dip, a lottery.''
   ``The police needed scapegoats, they wanted revenge for the
killing of one of their colleagues,'' he claimed in an interview.
   Civil libertarians have also cast doubt on the fairness of the
trials. Amnesty International, the human rights group, investigated
the case and concluded that the police forced many suspects to sign
confessions and denied them full access to lawyers.
   It said confessions formed the basis of the prosecution evidence
against nearly all defendants charged with felonies.
   While in custody, Silcott denied involvement in the killing and
refused to answer most police questions. Police alleged that in his
final interview, he told an officer, ``You ain't got enough
evidence. Those kids won't give evidence in court. No one will talk
to you. You can't keep me away from them.'' Silcott denied using
those words.
   Silcott's defenders say police also presented conflicting
testimony about his whereabouts during the riot.
   In 1987 a jury found Silcott guilty, and Judge Sir Derek Hodgson
sentenced him to a minimum 30 years in prison, calling him ``a very
evil and a very dangerous man.''
   The judge disclosed that Silcott already was out on bail for
another murder when the riot broke out.
   Lord Gifford, a civil rights campaigner and former judge,
condemned the trials as ``a blot on the reputation of British
justice.'' In a report, he concluded that ``the whole process from
first to last was arbitrary, unfair and not conducive to bringing
guilty people to justice.''
   Gifford told students Tuesday that there was no evidence to
convict Silcott. ``It was a terrible crime, and the more terrible a
crime the greater is the emotion and the danger of prejudice,
particularly racial prejudice.''
</TEXT>
