<FIRST>r w AM-DoleFoundation     05-03 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dole Foundation,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dole Raises $1.2 Million To Benefit Disabled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and his wife Barbara made a
surprise visit Wednesday evening at a fund-raising event that
collected some $1.2 million for a foundation headed by Senate
Minority Leader Bob Dole.
   The Dole foundation assists the disabled and particularly
promotes employment of the disabled. It is headed by the Kansas
senator who was Bush's rival for the Republican presidential
nomination last year.
   In brief remarks, Bush praised the organization's work and its
help in ``mainstreaming'' the disadvantaged.
   He said the organization was ``a shining example for all of
us,'' and called in ``one of the many thousands of points of
light,'' a phrase he uses to refer to private activities that help
make society better.
   The foundation also announced the awarding of $240,000 in grants
for training and job programs for the disabled.
   The announcement came at the foundation's fourth annual
$1,000-a-person reception.
   ``We have helped provide training and placement to over 2,200
people with disabilities in the past three years and we are just
getting started,'' Dole said in a statement.
   The foundation honored the Marriott Corp. for what Dole
described as ``outstanding achievements in hiring people with
disabilities at all levels throughout the company.'' The company
employs more than 6,000 disabled people.
   Dole, who lost most of the use of his right arm and hand because
of wounds in World War II, established the non-profit,
non-political foundation to provide money for training and job
programs for the disabled. It began operating in 1984 and has
provided grants totaling $2.7 million to more than 100 programs in
30 states.
</TEXT>
