<FIRST>u a AM-TankerSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0709 05-03 0797</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0709,0815</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Captain Scheduled For Court Appearance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Hazelwood pleading innocent;
bail set; trial date set, picks up 2nd graf pvs, `The state, ...; DELETES
obsolete 7th graf pvs, `Former tanker ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who was skipper of the tanker
Exxon Valdez when it struck a reef and caused the nation's largest
oil spill pleaded innocent Wednesday to criminal charges, including
operating the vessel while drunk.
   Joseph Hazelwood, 42, entered the plea through his attorney in a
15-minute proceeding before state Judge David Stewart. Hazelwood,
who was silent and declined to answer reporters' questions, was
ushered out a back door of the courtroom immediately after the
hearing.
   Hazelwood, who was fired by Exxon after the accident, is charged
with operating a vessel while drunk, reckless endangerment and
negligent discharge of oil, stemming from the March 24 incident
which dumped more than 10 million gallons of crude into Prince
William Sound.
   His attorney presented a $50,000 check for bail after Stewart
rejected a request to lower the amount to $25,000.
   Stewart scheduled the trial for June 20 in Valdez, but one of
Hazelwood's lawyers, Dan Dennis, said he would seek to transfer the
trial to another area. ``There will undoubtedly be a change of
venue (request),'' Dennis said.
   Stewart also said a grand jury has launched an investigation to
determine whether additional charges should be filed against
Hazelwood. He did not elaborate.
   The state, meanwhile, was under pressure from the federal
government to respond to Exxon's controversial plan for cleaning up
oil-fouled seashore.
   State authorities reported increasing damage on the Alaska
Peninsula and at Katmai National Park.
   ``It's a very thick mousse-type stuff six to eight inches
thick'' hitting in blotches, said Bill Lamoreaux, a state
environmental official. ``It's definitely a difficult type of
clean-up operation. It's close to shore and rolling up on shore.''
   Federal Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner was to inspect
the spill zone, and Vice President Dan Quayle scheduled a visit
Thursday on his return from Asia.
   After the spill, Hazelwood went home to Huntington, N.Y., where
he was arrested on a fugitive warrant, but he returned voluntarily
Wednesday and surrendered, not even waiting for an extradition
hearing. He had been free on $25,000 bail in New York and a
prosecutor said Wednesday he would move to dismiss the fugitive
charge and return the bail money.
   On the night of the spill, Hazelwood allegedly turned over
control of the 987-foot-long Exxon Valdez to an uncertified mate.
The tanker was outside shipping lanes when it rammed a reef and
ripped its bottom, letting the Alaskan North Slope crude oil pour
out.
   Authorities say Hazelwood, who has a history of alcohol-related
driving arrests in New York, had a blood-alcohol level of 0.061
percent nine hours after the crash. The legal maritime limit for
operating a vessel is 0.04 percent.
   State environmental officials, facing a deadline ordered by
President Bush's personal emissary to the oil spill, worked to
decide whether to accept Exxon's plan to remove the crude from
hundreds of miles of shoreline.
   Key state scientists and the head of Alaska's Department of
Environmental Conservation have sharply criticized the oil
company's proposal, which would leave nearly 200 miles of oily
coastline uncleansed and require exemptions from strict
environmental laws to dispose of the sludge and wastewater.
   Lamoreaux described the plan Wednesday as ``more like a briefing
document for the press than a plan for us.''
   Dennis Kelso, Alaska's environmental conservation commissioner,
called Exxon's cleanup and disposal plan ``a few pages of wishful
thinking.''
   A statement issued by Kelso's office said state authorities
would ``insist that Exxon focus all its energies and equipment on
cleaning all the affected beaches, no matter how hard hit.''
   Admiral Paul A. Yost Jr., commandant of the Coast Guard, ordered
state authorities to issue a formal response to Exxon's plan. Yost
must approve the proposal before it is put into effect and said he
would do so within a week.
   Yost also has criticized the proposal, saying it was poorly
drafted and lacked specifics, but he stopped short of formally
rejecting it.
   In an interview Wednesday on ``CBS This Morning,'' Gov. Steve
Cowper said the state may be willing to waive some environmental
restrictions for disposal of the oil if ``that's the only practical
way to get rid of it and it doesn't really cause anything but
temporary changes in the air quality, we might well consider that.''
   Exxon has proposed several methods to dispose of oil wastes.
Salvageable oil would be processed and refined. Oil-laced water
would be sent to a Valdez water-treatment plant that cleans ballast
water from oil tankers. Solid oil wastes would be burned or buried.
</TEXT>
