<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Riot     05-03 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Riot,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pravda Says More Than 100 Arrested in Riot in Turkmenia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pravda reported Wednesday that police arrested
about half of a mob of about 200 young people who attacked stores,
restaurants and parks in the republic of Turkmenia in Central Asia
after May Day celebrations.
   The Communist Party newspaper charged that the crowd in
Ashkabad, the capital of Turkmenia, was led by criminals and said
it was broken up by force on Monday evening after ignoring calls by
police to disperse.
   ``Not less than 100 lawbreakers were detained, and no one was
hurt,'' Pravda said.
   The newspaper said, ``Those who were detained said they acted
because of exorbitant prices of cooperatives and the low quality of
products and services. But as a method of protest, as was seen,
they chose hooliganism.''
   It said the rioters broke windows and damaged cars.
   Pravda quoted Interior Minister Vasily Grinin of Turkmenia as
saying police managed to break up the rampage without using tear
gas or truncheons.
   This apparently was intended to assure readers that no repeat
had occurred of the clash between soldiers and pro-independence
demonstrators in the Georgian republic on April 9. Nineteen people
were killed then and a 20th victim was fatally shot later for
violating a curfew.
   Turkmenia is a southern Soviet republic of 3.5 million people
that borders the Caspian Sea, Iran and Afghanistan. It was the
first such report of trouble in Turkmenia, but religious and civil
unrest were reported previously in the other traditionally Moslem
Central Asian republics of Uzbekistan and Kazakhstan.
   Cooperatives are small, privately owned businesses allowed under
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's economic reforms to provide goods
and services the state-run economy cannot. Many Soviets view the
cooperatives with suspicion.
</TEXT>
