<FIRST>r i AM-Nigeria-Politics     05-03 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nigeria-Politics,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nigerian Political Parties Allowed Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military government lifted a
5-year-old ban on political parties on Wednesday and proclaimed a
new constitution, one of several steps being taken toward civilian
rule in 1992.
   The decision was announced in a nationwide television and radio
broadcast by Maj. Gen. Ibrahim Babangida, the head of state.
   On May 9, Babangida begins a four-day official visit to Britain,
which administered Nigeria until the country's independence in 1960.
   There already has been some clandestine regrouping of political
organizations in expectation of the new move, and they were
expected to come out in the open on Thursday.
   Nigeria is Africa's most populous country, with an estimated
population of 95 million, and it is an important oil producer.
   It has undergone a string of military coups since the first in
1966. The last civilian government under President Shehu Shagari
was overthrown by the army on Dec. 31, 1983, when partisan politics
were banned.
   Under a transition program announced Wednesday night, some
civilian leaders will be elected in local council polls in
December. Elections of legislators and governors for the 21 states
will be held next year.
   The military stated on Tuesday that it would not lay down any
ideology for civilian rule.
</TEXT>
