<FIRST>r a AM-LadleDeath     05-03 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ladle Death,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Accused in Ladle Deaths Was Insane, Defense Lawyer Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Minister's first name in xx graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUSKEGON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of killing his two sons by
locking them into a searing foundry ladle was a mentally ill
religious zealot who spoke of ``trial by fire,'' his attorney said
Wednesday.
   Bartley James Dobbens, 28, is on trial in circuit court on two
counts of murder in the Thanksgiving Day 1987 deaths of 2-year-old
Bartley Joel and 15-month-old Peter David Dobben in nearby Norton
Shores.
   The defendant, who has been diagnosed as a paranoid
schizophrenic, wept during opening arguments when his wife and
children were mentioned.
   Dobben's pregnant wife was waiting for him in their car when he
took the boys into the Cannon-Muskegon Corp. foundry to retrieve a
Bible and show them where he worked.
   In his opening argument, defense attorney Terry Nolan told
jurors he would show Dobben was legally insane at the time.
   Assistant Muskegon County Prosecutor Brett Gardner said the
evidence would show Dobben planned his children's deaths because of
jealousy and ``a bad marriage that existed from the start.''
   Nolan said Dobben stopped taking psychiatric medication and
filed for divorce within two weeks of meeting self-ordained
minister Rood Vaughan in March 1987.
   ``Within two weeks, Bartley Dobben's life turned upside down,''
the attorney said.
   Dobben began taking his children to hear fundamentalist
Christian sermons by Vaughan in the basement of Vaughan's home, and
sometimes kept the children out all night, Nolan said.
   On the day of the slaying, Dobben visited a friend at 1 a.m. and
talked for hours, quoting from the Bible and speaking of ``trial by
fire ... and only fire burns sins away,'' Nolan said.
   Dobben thought he was performing ``a spiritual rite'' when he
took his children to the foundry, put them in a furnace, ``played
with them to make them comfortable,'' lit the gas jets, and set
them at 1,300 degrees, Nolan said.
   The attorney said Dobben's schizophrenia first appeared in high
school, when he appeared to undergo a ``Jekyll and Hyde
transition'' and became obsessed with religion.
   After marrying, Dobben became insanely jealous and later became
obsessed with the idea his children would be killed, Nolan said.
   In 1985, Dobben had psychotic episodes so intense he was
committed to a psychiatric hospital, and endured co-workers' taunts
after his release, Nolan said.
   Nolan is charged with open counts of murder, meaning the jury
sets the degree. If convicted, he could be sentenced to life in
prison.
   The trial is expected to last two to four weeks.
</TEXT>
