<HEAD>`Family Ties' to Feature Unusual Last Episode</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an unusual send-off, NBC's ``Family Ties''
will conclude its television run with a 70-minute episode capped by
a round of emotional curtain calls, the network announced Wednesday.
   The final ``Family Ties'' broadcast on May 14 was set for a
special one-hour length, but NBC told the show's producers they
could include an additional seven minutes of dialogue and three
minutes of spontaneous farewells by cast and crew members.
   The rest of the NBC lineup that night will be delayed 10
minutes, the network said.
   ``Family Ties'' came to the NBC schedule in 1982 and was
partially responsible for the network's climb out of the ratings
cellar. In the situation comedy's final episode, Alex Keaton
(Michael J. Fox) leaves his parents, sisters and brother for a job
on Wall Street.
