<SECOND>AM-Chile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chile's Military Government Scraps Plans For Democratic Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with opposition reaction, details.
ADDS byline. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The right-wing military government said
Wednesday it was scrapping plans for democratic reforms because the
opposition rejected a take-it-or-leave-it proposal.
   Interior Minister Carlos Caceres blamed ``intransigent''
opposition leaders in announcing an end to further talks. He said
the opposition ``closed out the possibility of a realistic
agreement'' on amendments to the 1980 constitution.
   ``Under the current circumstances, there is no possibility
whatsoever of talking again about constitutional changes,'' he told
a news conference.
   Among reform proposals abandoned was one legalizing Marxism.
   The announcement indicated an abrupt hardening in the position
of President Augusto Pinochet's government and a return to an
openly antagonistic relationship between authorities and opposition.
   Patricio Aylwin, president of the centrist Christian Democratic
Party and a leader of a 17-party opposition coalition, told his own
news conference later that the move means reforms will have to wait
until after Dec. 14 elections.
   ``If the government has said it will make no changes at all,
there will be no changes for the time being,'' he said. ``They will
have to be done by the future congress and the future government to
be elected in December.''
   Aylwin is considered the coalition's most likely choice as
presidential candidate.
   The government on Friday proposed 19 changes to the
constitution, including several offered in response to pressures
for reform after Gen. Pinochet lost a referendum last October on
extending his rule to 1997. Some changes deemed essential by the
opposition were left out, however.
   The referendum loss obliged Pinochet to schedule the elections,
and his foes say reforms are needed to make sure the new government
has full democratic powers. Pinochet is legally barred from being a
candidate.
   The government package would have required approval by two
successive senates before the reforms took effect _ a delay of at
least five years.
   The opposition coalition rejected it on Tuesday night as ``a
step backward.'' It wanted the reforms to take effect before the
elections, the first since Pinochet seized power in a violent 1973
coup.
   The government proposal met an opposition call for amending a
constitutional article that outlaws all propagation of Marxist
thought, by individuals or groups. It would retain a ban on
political groups that promote violence or totalitarianism.
   It also allowed for a one-time shortening of the presidential
term to four years instead of the normal eight years. The
opposition wanted the shorter term for the next government, which
it sees as a transition leadership.
   But the government refused to meet an opposition demand that the
entire senate be elected. According to the constitution, 10 members
of the senate's 36 members will be appointed.
   It also rejected opposition calls for erasing a clause that
allows Pinochet to remain as army commander for eight more years.
The same clause applies to the heads of the navy, air force and
national police.
   The 73-year-old Pinochet recently vowed to stay on as army
commander and said the military would keep a role as political
overseers to ensure the country does not fall under leftist control.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
