<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Parliament 1stLd-Writethru a0751 05-03 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Parliament, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0751,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refuse to Nominate Anyone but Gorbachev for President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs to UPDATE with branch of Italian radical party
formed. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly elected parliament members from Moscow
decided Wednesday it would be frivolous to nominate anyone but
Mikhail S. Gorbachev for president of the Soviet Union, a
participant in the meeting said.
   ``We decided the president must be Gorbachev and we will not put
forward an alternative,'' said Mikhail Bocharov, who was elected
from the Butovo district on Moscow's outskirts.
   Leonid Kravchenko, director of the official news agency Tass,
said last week in London the Moscow deputies planned to nominate a
candidate to compete with Gorbachev for the presidenccy, but
Bocharov said it was a ``silly'' idea.
   Gorbachev, who has been Communist Party chief since March 1985,
was elected president unanimously in October by the Supreme Soviet,
replacing Andrei A. Gromyko.
   Political reforms since then change the way the president is
chosen and expand the powers of the office. The new 2,250-member
Congress of People's Deputies will convene May 25 to elect the
president and choose a 542-member working parliament from among its
own members.
   Tass said Gorbachev addressed Wednesday's meeting of Moscow
members, but it did not report what he said. Bocharov said the
Soviet leader answered questions put by some of the 70 to 80
representatives present.
   Others attending included Lev N. Zaikov, the Moscow party chief;
Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov, and party ideologist Vadim A. Medvedev,
Tass reported.
   Bocharov, who runs a building materials factory, said the Moscow
group would meet again May 15 to chose candidates for the working
parliament.
   In another political development, Soviet political activists
said they had formed a branch of the Rome-based Radical Party.
   Alexander Rubchenko, spokesman for the newly formed 70-member
Transnational Radical Party, said the group would campaign for the
elimination of nuclear weapons, more political freedom and
protection of the environment.
   Rubchenko, a political activist, said the new group also was
seeking more economic ties with Western Europe, the lifting of
customs barriers and acceptance of a common European system of laws.
   Soviet law prohibits any political party except the Communist
Party, and the effort to register as an affiliate of the Italian
party apparently was designed to get around that prohibition.
</TEXT>
