<FIRST>r w AM-CanadianEmbassy     05-03 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canadian Embassy,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada Opens New $76 Million Embassy Facing Capitol Hill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Snipping a royal blue ribbon, Canadian Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney on Wednesday formally opened his country's
new, $76 million embassy near the foot of Capitol Hill and declared
that ``the maple leaf comes to Pennsylvania Avenue.''
   Mulroney, who arrived for talks Thursday with President Bush,
and Secretary of State James A. Baker III paid tribute to the close
ties between the United States and Canada, symbolized by the unique
location of the new chancery building.
   It is the only foreign embassy situated on Pennsylvania Avenue,
the ceremonial route lining the Capitol and the White House. The
modernistic building, designed by Vancouver architect Arthur
Erickson, occupies a prized, 1.2-acre site opposite the National
Gallery of Art.
   A smiling Baker held the ribbon draped across the main entrance
to the building while Mulroney clipped it with a pair of scissors
before a crowd of dignitaries that included leading members of
Congress, Supreme Court Justice Harry A. Blackmun and CIA Director
William Webster.
   Baker said the new embassy ``conveys the warmth and openness of
the people of Canada'' and reflects enduring bonds of friendship
between the two countries.
   Mulroney declared the embassy ``open in the service of Canada
and in service of the friendship of our great ally, the United
States of America.''
   Together, they visited Ambassador Derek Burney's glassed-in
penthouse office suite on the sixth floor to admire the view of the
Mall and the Capitol.
   The embassy staff of 327 people moved into the building a month
ago from their previous quarters in two buildings on Massachusetts
Avenue, the city's traditional ``embassy row,'' and rented space in
a downtown office building.
   Burney, who arrived shortly before Bush was inaugurated Jan. 20,
will continue to reside in an elegant, six-story mansion on
Massachusetts Avenue where Canada's envoys had maintained their
offices since 1928.
   The new embassy building, finished in Ontario limestone with
unpolished aluminum pillars, was completed in March, a year behind
schedule, at a cost of $76 million, nearly double the original
estimate.
   The courtyard outside the main entrance features a pool,
terraced greenery and a fountain under a rotunda circled by 12
columns, one for each of Canada's 10 provinces and two territories.
Inside are a 20,000-volume library, a 175-seat theater, a small
exercise room and an art gallery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
