<DOCNO> AP890503-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Panama 2ndLd-Writethru a0795 05-03 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0795,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Predicts Unrest If Fraud Mars Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The speeches...' to UPDATE with report of gunfire.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos PAN4,5,6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100,000 opposition backers
packed one of the capital's main streets Wednesday to hear
candidates predict victory in next week's elections and an end to
21 years of military control.
   Presidential candidate Guillermo Endara, his voice hoarse, told
the crowd Panama was on the eve of ``a new republic of which you
all will be founding fathers.''
   ``I was born free. I am not free. I will be free on May 7,''
shouted Guillermo Ford, the opposition's candidate for the second
of two vice-presidential seats in Sunday's balloting.
   The speeches were interrupted when crowds panicked, once when
security guards stopped people from coming too near the candidates
and again when an alleged government infiltrator, or ``toad,'' was
chased from the area by a mob beating him with sticks. People in
the crowd said they saw an unidentified man fire gunshots into the
air at one point.
   Several people were knocked to the ground. Some fainted and were
carried away, but no serious injuries were reported.
   A group of youths snake-danced through the crowd carrying a
black coffin with the picture of a smiling Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega pasted on the front and a pineapple affixed on top.
``Pineapple face'' is a derogatory name for Noriega, inspired by
his rough complexion.
   First vice-presidential candidate Ricardo Arias Calderon praised
young Panamanians at the rally, saying, ``There are thousands here
who have never known liberty but are here to fight for it.''
   The chanting, flag-waving crowd was packed so tightly on Via
Espana that at times it was impossible to move.
   The opposition has accused the government of trying to rig
Sunday's election. Earlier Wednesday, opposition leaders warned
that Panamanians may react with violence if fraud is evident.
   ``This is the last peaceful opportunity for change,'' Ford told
a news conference earlier in the day. Endara and Arias also
attended the conference.
   Ford said the opposition wants to avoid a confrontation with the
Defense Forces, but ``we fear that if the will of the people is
violated, there will be a spontaneous reaction.''
   Noriega, head of the Defense Forces and Panama's de facto ruler,
is backing his business associate, Carlos Duque Jaen, for president.
   The government also has warned that the elections could turn
violent. Duque has urged his followers ``to take to the streets ...
to defend the vote.''
   The government made a public show of handing out weapons April
30 to the ``Dignity Batallions,'' civilians trained to defend
Panama against a U.S. invasion.
   Arias said official voter rolls show duplicated names and
suspicious increases in the number of voters. He said the
registration in some districts doubled.
   He alleged the number of registered voters on rolls has grown 29
percent since 1984, while the population has increased by only 16
percent.
   Government officials explained the increases by saying
registration procedures have improved.
   Despite the predictions of fraud, Arias said he was confident
the opposition's ``margin of victory will be such that it will
neutralize the fraud, if the fraud is not accompanied by crude
forms of repression.''
   The opposition candidates said there is no hope of democracy in
Panama as long as Noriega, who was indicted in the United States
last year on charges of drug smuggling and money laundering,
remains in power.
   After his indictment, then-President Eric Arturo Delvalle tried
to oust Noriega. Noriega in turn ousted Delvalle.
   Noriega and the government accuse the opposition of being
lackies of the United States, which has imposed economic sanctions
on Panama as part of its attempt to drive him from power.
   Noriega denies the drug smuggling and money laundering
allegations and says the United States is trying to get rid of him
as part of a plan to retain control of the Panama Canal.
   According to a 1977 treaty, the United States is to turn the
waterway over to local control in the year 2000 and remove its
12,000 military personnel from Panama.
   Among the observers expected for Sunday's voting are former
presidents Jimmy Carter, who signed the treaty, and Gerald Ford.
They are part of an unofficial U.S. delegation invited by the
Panamanian government. The government has rejected any official
U.S. delegation.
</TEXT>
