<DOCNO> AP890503-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RedWolfPups     05-03 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Red Wolf Pups,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Puppies Born to Red Wolf, Part of Endangered Species</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLEN ROSE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A red wolf, the second rarest mammal in
the United States, gave birth to three puppies Wednesday at a
wildlife center.
   If the puppies survive, they will be the first Texas-born red
wolves since the mid-1970s, raising the total population to 92,
said officials at Fossil Rim Wildlife Center.
   In 1973, after the passage of the Endangered Species Act, the
entire red wolf population in southeast Texas and Louisiana was
captured to prevent its extinction.
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service captured about 40 red wolves
and began a recovery program in Washington state.
   The black-footed ferret is the only mammal that is rarer than
the red wolf in the United States.
   Fossil Rim, a research and education center that is involved in
the propagation of eight endangered species, received four red wolf
breeding pair in February.
   ``We are sure a second female will produce a litter within the
next week to 10 days,'' said Dr. Evan Blumer, a Fossil Rim
veterinarian.
   The puppies were estimated to weigh about 14 ounces, but Fossil
Rim officials said they would not be sexed or examined until
Thursday or Friday.
   The red wolf is smaller than the grey wolf, with females
weighing 40-60 pounds and males weighing 60-80 pounds.
   The wolf ranged from Texas east to the Atlantic coast and north
to the Ohio valley, but began disappearing because of their
inability to adapt to changes in the land and predator control.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0675 05-03 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,0706</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab Envoys Convince Rival Governments to Abide by Truce</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with shelling at Cypriot ferry.
Pick up 4th pvs, `Aoun's 20,000...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warring factions agreed Wednesday to
implement a cease-fire plan to end the Beirut bloodbath that has
killed 278 people in eight weeks, an Arab League peacemaker
announced.
   ``There is no justification for a single shot to be fired in
Lebanon as of now,'' Algerian diplomat Lakhdar Ibrahimi told
reporters after meeting separately with Lebanon's rival Cabinet
leaders _ Sunni Moslem Salim Hoss and Christian Gen. Michel Aoun.
   Several hours after Ibrahimi's announcement, however, police
reported a new violation of the truce.
   As speedboats began ferrying passengers from the harbor of the
Christian port of Jounieh to the Cypriot-flagged ferry Baroness M,
anchored 15 miles off the coast, three shells fired from
Syrian-policed west Beirut crashed on the Byblos coast nine miles
north of Jounieh, police said.
   They said the captain of the Baroness M refused to enter the
port, 12 miles north of Beirut, because he was skeptical about
guarantees that his vessel would not be shelled.
   A police spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity
according to regulations, said the violation did not interrupt the
transport of about 500 passengers onto the Baroness M to be ferried
to the Cypriot port of Larnaca.
   The ship and another boat, the Larnaca Rose, had evacuated about
15,000 people from the Christian enclave during the fighting. But
both suspended the shuttles April 24 after they became the target
of Syrian and Druse Moslem gunners.
   Earlier, police reported some sniper fire from Moslem west
Beirut into the Christian sector. But a spokesman played down the
violation and said, ``It seems the cease-fire orders haven't been
issued yet.'' No casualties were reported.
   Aoun's 20,000 Lebanese army soldiers have battled Moslem
militiamen and allied Syrian soldiers since March 3. More than
1,000 people have been injured in that time.
   Ibrahimi and Kuwait's ambassador to Syria, Abdel-Aziz Jassem,
arrived in Beirut earlier Wednesday seeking to enforce an Arab
League-brokered truce that began April 28.
   It scaled down indiscriminate bombardment of population centers
in and around Beirut. But it was violated repeatedly after three
days because Aoun rejected the second clause of the accord,
refusing to lift a blockade of three illegal militia-run ports.
   The blockade, through which Aoun wanted to restore government
authority and gather taxes worth $100 million a year, ignited the
latest fighting.
   Druse and Syrian gunners, who outnumber Christian forces by 3-1,
retaliated by firing at Christian ports, then besieged the
Christian heartland and trapped some 1 million Christians in a
310-square-mile enclave.
   Ibrahimi said Aoun now has ``accepted to implement the decision
adopted by the Arab foreign ministers which calls for lifting all
blockades imposed on all air and sea ports.''
   Beirut airport, the country's only international air transport
facility, was closed by Christian shellfire March 12.
   Ibrahimi said Aoun also agreed to reopen road crossings that
link Beirut's Moslem and Christian sectors for three months while
the Arab League brokers a comprehensive settlement.
   ``I can say the cease-fire has taken effect today after the
settlement of the ports dispute. The observer force will begin
arriving soon,'' Ibrahimi said, but did not give a date.
   An aide to Hoss said Ibrahimi proposed deploying Arab observers
at the disputed ports, where Aoun has charged militias also run
guns and drugs. Aoun agreed to the envoy's compromise.
   Kuwaiti Foreign Minister Sheik Sabah Ahmed, who heads the Arab
League panel on Lebanon, stressed Wednesday that the observers will
be sent only after the cease-fire is consolidated.
   ``We are not prepared to sacrifice any Arab brethren in the
continued shelling and exchange of fire,'' he told the Kuwait News
Agency.
   Aoun has welcomed the deployment of an Arab observer team,
saying it also would monitor the 40,000 Syrian soldiers in Lebanon,
whom Christians accuse of breaking a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping
mandate by siding with the Moslems.
   The observers' presence is expected to loosen Syria's grip as
Lebanon's sole powerbroker.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NorthwesternFire     05-03 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwestern Fire,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosion Rocks University Chem Lab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two explosions rocked a chemistry lab at
Northwestern University on Wednesday, injuring two graduate
students and setting off a blaze, fire department officials said.
   The incident apparently resulted from experiments under way,
said Northwestern spokesman Mike Tirrell. The victims had been
working with an ether-type solvent, said Pat Tremmel, another
Northwesten spokeswoman.
   William Finch, 30, a post-doctoral student, was in fair to
serious condition at Evanston Hospital with second-degree burns on
his chest, face and groin, along with a fractured wrist and some
injury from glass fragments, Ms. Tremmel said.
   Laurent Brard, 25, another graduate student, was in good
condition with second-degree burns to the face, chest and arms, and
glass fragment injuries, she said.
   The accident occurred at a second-floor lab in the Technological
Institute, recently the site of heated protests over the use of
animals in scientific research.
   Capt. Sam Boddie of the city fire department said he had heard
nothing to suggest the incident was linked to the protests.
   ``We do have explosions there from time to time. In the last
year, we had one for sure,'' he said.
   Ms. Tremmel later disputed reports of an explosion and described
the incident as ``a small fire,'' but Boddie said there was an
explosion, and firefighters at the scene reported a second, smaller
blast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2207EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w US-Eritrea     05-03 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>US-Eritrea,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eritrean Rebel Leader Urges U.S. To Help End War With Ethiopia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An African rebel leader urged the United
States on Wednesday to help end the protracted war between the
strategically placed province of Eritrea and the Soviet-backed
government of Ethiopia.
   Isaias Afwerki, Secretary General of the Eritrean People's
Liberation Front, said he hoped to convey his views to U.S.
officials and lawmakers, although he declined to say whom he would
be meeting.
   State Department officials, who said Afwerki is the most senior
Eritrean rebel leader ever to visit here, also declined to say
whether they would meet with him.
   Afwerki said he did not have any specific initiatives to offer,
but hoped the United States would ``contribute to a lasting
solution'' for the conflict by helping bring the sides to the
negotiating table.
   U.S. policy rejects Eritrea's demands for secession from
Ethiopia, advocating negotiations between the sides to end what has
become, at 27 years, Africa's longest war.
   State Department officials have occasionally met with members of
the EPLF, the largest of several Eritrean groups. The U.S. also
maintains ties with the government of Ethiopian Military Chairman
Mengistu Haile Mariam, although relations have deteriorated since
Ethiopia switched allegiance to the Soviet Union in 1977.
   Afwerki's visit comes at a time when Mengistu, suffering
economic woes and military defeats to the rebels, is also making
overtures to the U.S. administration.
   ``Ethiopia's prospects are bleaker than ever,'' Afwerki
contended at a seminar sponsored by the Center for Strategic and
International Studies, an independent think tank. The EPLF, which
is backed by several Arab governments but relies mostly on captured
Soviet weaponry, has claimed significant military victories over
the past year.
   U.S. officials believe the organization controls about 75
percent of Eritrea, which overlooks a key water route to the oil
fields of Saudi Arabia, but that the government retains control of
the province's major ports and cities. Officials here say the
government is also under pressure from its main arms supplier, the
Soviet Union, to end the costly war.
   Afwerki said the Soviet Union, despite claims to the contrary,
continues to arm the Ethiopian government.
   Nonetheless, the EPLF is ``among the first who hope to benefit''
from recent cooperation between the U.S. and the Soviet Union in
resolving regional conflicts around the world. Afwerki said such
superpower cooperation, as evidenced by agreements ending the
Soviet occupation of Afghanistan and the Cuban occupation of
Angola, has made his organization optimistic about prospects for
negotiations with Ethiopia.
   The EPLF is still holding out for its 1980 proposal to conduct a
referendum that would determine whether Eritrea remains an
autonomous part of Ethiopia or secedes from it altogether, he said.
   The EPLF has in the past proposed third-country mediation to end
the war with Ethiopia but has spurned proposals for Italy or Sudan
to bring the sides together.
   Afwerki rejected claims that his group is Marxist in nature,
calling that a pretext for past ``U.S. indifference,'' and said the
EPLF represented varying economic views and was committed to a free
economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Aspin-Exon     05-03 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aspin-Exon,1st Ld-Writethru, a0775,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislators Argue Over Who Has the Most Brains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS final graf with two grafs of Exon comments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senator and a House representative waged
verbal war Wednesday over whether a member of Congress is smart
enough to match wits with the Soviet military.
   In the first volley, Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., criticized a
decision by the House Armed Services Committee to hold hearings
with Soviet officials on crafting a U.S. defense budget.
   ``If the Congress can't make decisions on national security
without testimony and advice from Soviet military planners then we
are in more peril than I had envisioned. To use an old wisdom, `we
have indeed met the enemy and it is us,''' said Exon, a member of
the Senate Armed Services Committee.
   Shooting back was Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House
panel, who said Exon apparently ``doesn't believe senators can
handle a public given-and-take with Soviet officials.''
   ``I'm fully confident in the intellectual and political skills
of the members of my committee,'' he said.
   Aspin announced Monday that his panel would hold hearings with
Marshal Sergey Akhromeyev, former chief of the Soviet general staff
and now an adviser to Kremlin leader Mikhail Gorbachev, sometime in
June.
   In addition, the committee's Defense Policy Panel will hold a
hearing May 9 with Soviet officials from the Institute for the USA
and Canada, a Moscow think tank on superpower relations.
   Aspin said putting together a defense budget ``will be hard
enough to do given the deficit. But the problem is compounded by
uncertainty about the Soviet Union.''
   The chairman pointed out that only the executive branch can
negotiate agreements with the Soviets, but a committee ``is in a
better position for expansive given-and-take and exploration of new
ideas.''
   That raised the ire of Exon, who wondered why Congress doesn't
invite Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi ``to give us expert testimony
on stopping terrorism.''
   ``Gorbymania has struck with a vengenance in the halls of
Congress. We have initiated our own phrase to mimic the Soviets _
`parrotstroika,''' Exon said.
   The Nebraska senator also said Congress should not be a forum
for Soviet propaganda.
   In response, Aspin said that if Exon ``fears that hearing what
the Russians have to say _ and putting them through a grilling on
what they haven't talked about publicly _ amounts to making `the
committee process a forum for Soviet propaganda,' I feel sorry for
him.''
   Exon, in a telephone interview late Wednesday, said he didn't
``need help from Soviet military planners. Les believes the Soviets
are here to be grilled. I expect him to be keenly disappointed.''
   Asked if the criticisms would result in any bad feelings, Exon
said, ``No. Les and I are good friends. We've worked together for a
long time. This is not the first time and it won't be the last.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2221EST</FILEID>
