<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2259EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Abbas 1stLd-Writethru a0789 05-03 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Abbas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0789,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rector of Paris Mosque Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sheik Abbas Ben Sheik El Hocine, rector of the
Great Mosque of Paris and considered the top Moslem religious
authority in France, died Wednesday night after suffering a heart
attack, officials said. He was 77.
   Abbas was evacuated by helicopter Wednesday evening from the
Hotel Crillon, where visiting PLO chief Yasser Arafat is staying,
to the Val de Grace military hospital after the heart attack.
   A statement issued by the mosque said Abbas died at 10:30 p.m.,
shortly after being admitted to the hospital.
   It said the rector's body would be returned to his homeland,
Algeria, on Friday.
   Abbas was made rector of the Paris mosque in 1982. He often
acted as a spokesman for French Moslems, a role disputed by some,
and as a liaison between the French government and the Moslem
community.
   As many as 3 million Moslems live in France, making it the
nation's second religion after Roman Catholicism.
   It was not immediately known whether Abbas had met with Arafat
at the Crillon. The Palestine Liberation Organization chairman was
attending a dinner given by Premier Michel Rocard at the close of a
two-day official visit.
   Abbas, with his tinted spectacles and astrakhan hat, was a
well-known figure to the French media, appearing in occasional
television interviews and commenting on political developments
affecting the Moslem community.
   He became for many a soothing and fatherly symbol of a moderate
Islam. At the height of the scandal of Salman Rushdie's ``The
Satanic Verses,'' Abbas advised the French not to pay so much
attention to this ``disrespectful writer.''
   Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini issued a death
sentence on Rushdie, saying he had blasphemed Islam in his book.
   Abbas neither spoke nor understood French when he succeeded Si
Hamza Boubakeur, who for years was a powerful but controversial
figure at the head of the mosque in the Latin Quarter on the Left
Bank.
   From a notable religious family near Constantine, Algeria, Abbas
was educated in North African centers of Islamic learning such as
Kerouan, Tunisia, and Fez, Morocco.
   He worked for religious reform in French colonial Algeria to
help return the North African land to its Arab and Islamic
character. Following Algerian independence, he spent four years as
president of the Supreme Islamic Council.
   As rector of the Paris Mosque, his human qualities soon won him
respect from Algerian Moslems, who make up the largest part of the
French Moslem community. He took to opening the doors of the mosque
in winter to provide shelter for the homeless.
   The mosque, inaugurated in 1926, is the largest place of Moslem
worship in Western Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2240EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-AuctionPrices     05-03 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auction Prices,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warhol's Red Marilyn Sells For $4 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andy Warhol's portrait, ``Red Marilyn,'' a 1964
depiction of Marilyn Monroe, brought $4 million at auction
Wednesday, a record for a work by the artist.
   The previous high for a Warhol painting was $3.9 million, said
Gloria Harris, a spokeswoman for Christie's. That painting sold
last year, also of the late actress, depicted her face 20 times and
is called ``Marilyn Monroe (Twenty Times).''
   ``Red Marilyn'' had a presale estimate value of between $1.5
million and $2 million. The actual selling price was $4,070,000,
Harris said.
   Harris said the auction Wednesday at Christie's fetched $31.7
million for 60 works of art. The auction of contemporary art
continues Thursday.
   ``Colored Alphabet,'' an oil and paper collage by Jasper Johns
sold for $3.5 million, the second highest price bid on Wednesday
but not a new record for a Johns.
   Other artist records at the Christie's auction included:
   _$715,000 for an Ellsworth Kelly painting, ``Black Triangle With
White.''
   _$880,000 for a Robert Motherwell painting, ``Elegy to the
Spanish Republic No. 134.''
   All prices include a 10 percent house commission.
   ``August Day,'' an oil on canvas painting by Franz Kline sold
for $2.7 million.
   A Jackson Pollock triptych, a series of three drip paintings on
three canvasses in black, red and yellow brought $2.2 million.
   ``Things on the Wall'' by Roy Lichtenstein sold for $1,012,000.
   The auction Wednesday at Christie's is the second day of a
12-day selling spree at that auction house and its rival _
Sotheby's. The two houses are expected to sell 4,400 pieces of art
for more than $500 million.
   On Tuesday, record prices were set for 27 contemporary artists
at Sotheby's. Total receipts of $78.6 million there set a record
for a contemporary art auction.
   Another Pollock drip painting, ``Number 8, 1950,'' painting sold
for $11.5 million at the Sotheby's auction.
   ``Triptych May-June,'' done by Francis Bacon in 1973, inspired
by the suicide of the artist's close friend, George Dyer, fetched
$6.2 million.
   Warhol's ``Red Jackie,'' which depicts a ruby-lipped Jacqueline
Kennedy Onassis as First Lady in 1963, sold for $750,000 _ more
than twice its presale estimate.
   On Saturday, a Sotheby's sale of 20th Century decorative arts
will include a two-story town house commissioned in 1950 by Mrs.
John D. Rockefeller III.
   Christie's on May 10 and 11 will feature five Monets, seven
Picassos, 10 Renoir and four works by Degas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2302EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SkyscraperFire     05-03 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skyscraper Fire,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Misdemeanor Charges Filed Against 9 Companies In L.A. High-rise Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year after fire gutted 4{ floors of the
62-story First Interstate Bank tower and killed a worker,
prosecutors filed 12 misdemeanor charges against nine companies
Wednesday in connection with the blaze.
   Two counts of the complaint filed by the district attorney and
city attorney referred to the death of Alexander Handy, 24, a
maintenance man who died May 4, 1988, after riding an elevator to
the 12th floor, where the fire started, to investigate an alarm.
   Forty other people suffered smoke inhalation in the city's worst
high-rise fire, which caused more than $450 million in damage.
   Deputy District Attorney David Guthman said there is a
three-year statute of limitations on filing felony charges. The
decision to file misdemeanor charges, he said, was prompted by the
misdemeanor statute of limitations which runs out Friday.
   If convicted, the defendants face various fines ranging from
$1,000 on municipal violations to $10,000 on state labor code
violations
   Among those charged in the complaint were First Interstate Bank
of California and Pedus Security Services, which was in charge of
security.
   The corporations charged in the misdemeanor complaint included
those owning part of the building or those involved in its security
and maintenance.
   The charges alleged seven violations of the state Labor Code and
five of the Los Angeles Municipal Code, including blocking a fire
exit, failing to maintain fire equipment and failing to maintain an
accident protection program. The charges also allege failure to
call in an alarm and failure to notify the Fire Department of
inoperative equipment.
   Others charged with violations were Equitable Life Assurance
Society of the United States, United California Bank Realty Corp.,
Cosco Fire Protection Inc., Commercial Building Maintenance Co.,
American Building Maintenance, First Interstate Bank Ltd., and
First Interstate Bancorp.
   Cosco was installing fire sprinklers at the time of the fire,
and was charged in connection with the closing of water mains in
the building.
   During the blaze a ring of flame roiled around the 12th through
15th floors for nearly four hours, showering streets with glass and
flaming debris and chasing people to the roof where 10 were plucked
to safety by helicopters.
   Others fled down smoky stairwells. Thirty-seven maintenance
workers and three firemen were treated for smoke inhalation.
   The cause of the conflagration was never determined because the
2,000-degree fire destroyed clues, but investigators eliminated
arson as a possibility.
   The 859-foot-tall building had no sprinkler system because it
was built in 1973, a year before fire codes were modified to
require sprinklers. The 62-story tower was the tallest in the city
at the time of the fire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2319EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Murphy     05-03 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Murphy,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Edwina Murphy, Who Sued Over Tainted Transfustion, Dead of AIDS Complications</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALINAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who sued a hospital after she
contracted AIDS through a blood transfusion has died from
complications of the disease.
   Edwina Murphy, 48, died at her family home last Thursday. She
filed suit against Community Hospital of the Monterey Peninsula in
December 1983 after becoming infected with the virus through
unscreened blood.
   Officials later discovered the blood had been donated by a known
heroin addict who died two months after Murphy received the
transfusion. At least three other people have died from the same
blood, said Murphy's attorney, Terry O'Reilly of Menlo Park.
   Murphy's lawsuit alleges gross negligence and seeks $1.5 million
in damages.
   The hospital had fought to keep the case from going to trial,
arguing it should be decided through arbitration. In September
1988, a California appellate court overturned a lower court
decision ordering the case to trial.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a
virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2303EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-StudentProtests     05-03 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Student Protests,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Protest Defense Research at UMass, Tuition Hikes at CUNY</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to correct overline.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Teaching Assistants, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN W. OATIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   University of Massachusetts students opposing Pentagon-funded
research took over campus offices for the third time in two weeks
Wednesday in one of several college protests around the nation.
   At the University of California-Berkeley, nearly all the 3,200
graduate research and teaching assistants staged a walkout to
demand recognition for their union.
   In New York, students who took over buildings at City University
of New York campuses last week to protest a proposed tuition hike
continued their occupation despite Gov. Mario Cuomo's veto of the
proposal late Tuesday.
   Students, concerned about possible spending cuts, asked Cuomo to
meet them at a ``neutral site'' in Harlem.
   In Atlanta, up to 175 people gathered among ``for-sale'' signs
put up on Mercer University's College of Arts and Sciences for a
24-hour ``read-in'' to protest a decision to close the campus in
June 1990.
   Students at Kent State University in Ohio who say a planned
memorial to the four students slain by National Guardsmen there in
1970 is not big enough planned a protest on the 19th anniversary of
the shootings Thursday.
   In Amherst, Mass., about 150 students marched to the University
of Massachusetts' Graduate Research Center after an afternoon rally
at the Student Union. About half that number pushed aside three
campus police officers trying to block the entrance to the 2{-story
annex to the Graduate Research Towers.
   ``We didn't think we'd be able to get into that building,'' said
organizer Jonathan Leavitt, a 22-year-old junior at the
25,000-student campus. ``We thought they would be smart enough to
see the potential target, and they weren't.''
   Police closed the building to all but faculty members who work
there, and locked a corridor holding the protesters to keep them
from taking over more offices. Officers guarded other buildings.
   As the takeover continued late Wednesday, university
administrators agreed to make public all documents relating to the
research, and said a panel of students, faculty and administrators
would be formed to discuss its future. The announcement followed a
meeting of students, faculty and administrators.
   The two previous takeovers of other campus buildings resulted in
68 arrests.
   The Berkeley walkout by over union recognition came with just
two weeks to go before final examinations.
   ``Hey, hey! Ho, ho! Union busting's got to go!'' sign-carrying
teaching and research assistants chanted as they demonstrated at
every major entrance to the campus.
   Their union, the Association for Graduate Student Employees, is
affiliated with the United Auto Workers. The students say they are
underpaid, overworked and often forced to go without health and
other benefits.
   About 90 percent ot the 3,200 graduate assistants took part in
the walkout, the association claimed. There are about 9,000
graduate students at Berkeley.
   According to a selective survey by the association of 307
classes through Wednesday afternoon, 66 percent were canceled, 25
percent were less than half-full, and 9 percent were at capacity.
   University spokesman Tom Debley said the results were not
necessarily representative of the campus, which has 23,000
undergraduates.
   In New York, students released a list of demands that included
no staff or faculty layoffs in the City University of New York,
more social services for students and amnesty for protesters.
   ``We will not relinquish the buildings at this particular time
because Governor Cuomo has not met all of our demands,'' Abdallah
Muhammad, a student at New York City Technical College in Brooklyn,
said at a news conference at City College. ``One of our major
demands is to meet with Cuomo.''
   Cuomo reiterated he would not meet with students while sit-ins
continued. ``I'll talk to them when they're legal,'' he said in
Rochester. ``If there's anything that education should start with,
the first rule is you live by the law.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
