<DOCNO> AP890503-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2321EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FetusDisposal     05-03 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fetus Disposal,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Carolina Legislature Regulates Fetus Disposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fetuses aborted in North Carolina would be
disposed of only through burial, cremation or approved types of
incineration unless used for research under a bill enacted
Wednesday by the state Legislature.
   The House of Representatives approved the bill 91-0. It cleared
the Senate by a wide margin, and is expected to become law Thursday
when signed by Lt. Gov. Jim Gardner and House Speaker Joe Mavretic.
   The bill was the idea of Sen. Ollie Harris, a funeral director.
He did not introduce the bill because he said he felt it would
appear he had a conflict of interest. It was sponsored by Sen. A.D.
Guy.
   The bill's disposal requirements do not apply to fetuses used
for medical research and development of pharmaceuticals.
   Harris, a leader in the battle to reduce North Carolina's fund
for poor women's abortions, said he never envisoned the
fetus-disposal bill as having any effect on the debate over whether
abortion should be legal.
   The bill directs the state Commission for Health Services to
adopt regulations on fetus disposal in accordance with the
requirement that fetuses ``be disposed of in a manner limited to
burial, cremation or approved hospital type of incineration.''
</TEXT>
