<DOCNO> AP890503-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ABC-Unions     05-03 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ABC-Unions,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC Engineers and Technicians Reject Contract Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An overwhelming majority of engineers and
technicians who work for Capital Cities-ABC voted Wednesday to
reject what the network called its final contract offer, union
officials said.
   The company said it would meet with leaders of the National
Association for Broadcast Employees and Technicians, but only to
reiterate its position.
   ``We want to meet with the union as soon as possible to make
sure the leadership and its members understand that the terms of
our final offer will not be renegotiated,'' said company
spokeswoman Patricia Matson.
   The union's chief negotiator, Thomas F. Kennedy, said he would
meet with company officials, and expressed optimism they would
negotiate further.
   ``That's what the collective bargaining process is all about,''
Kennedy said. ``We're not in a strike-vote situation yet.''
   A dozen of NABET's 18 bargaining units voted to reject the
company's proposal, said union spokesman John Krieger. WLS-AM radio
news writers, who are considered part of a 19th unit, also rejected
the offer.
   All units must ratify a contract before it can take effect,
Krieger said.
   Ms. Matson said the company felt ``sad and dismayed'' about the
rejection.
   The number of workers represented is disputed. Krieger said
there are 2,477 workers, while ABC says there are 2,150. The union
did not release the vote tally.
   Union negotiators had recommended rejection of the offer, which
was made after a month of negotiations that ended March 31.
   About 85 percent of the workers are engineers who handle
cameras, lights and audio equipment and other technical tasks. The
union also represents news writers, mail messengers, receptionists,
wardrobe specialists and others.
   The average engineer makes $47,000 in base pay, Krieger said.
ABC said that with overtime the average engineer earns about
$70,000.
   The rejected contract would have provided a one-time 10 percent
ratification bonus if approved by May 15, in lieu of a raise in the
first year. The bonus drops to 3 percent if the contract is
ratified after May 15.
   The rejected pact also would have provided 3 percent wage
increases in the second and third years and a 5 percent lump sum
bonus in the fourth year.
   The offer also included a virtual guarantee that none of the
about 2,000 full-time television employees would be laid off in the
contract's first three years.
   Capital Cities-ABC said the offer would mean the layoffs of 60
or 70 radio engineers soon after ratification. The union put the
figure closer to 125.
   NABET last struck ABC for 20 weeks in 1977 and for nine weeks in
1967. The union struck NBC in 1987 for 17 weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
