<SECOND>AM-Death Appeal-Scotus,140</SECOND>
<BYLINE>URGENT</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Refuses to Postpone Adams Execution</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON (AP ) - The Supreme Court on Wednesday night reufused
to postpone the execution of convicted child-slayer Aubrey Dennis
Adams Jr., who was scheduled to die Thursday morning in Florida.
   The justices voted 7-2 to reject Adams' emergency request to
delay his execution. The high court also turned down his formal
appeal to review his death sentence.
   Justices William J. Brennan and Thurgood Marshall, who oppose
the death penalty in all circumstances, voted to spare Adams.
   Adams, a former correctional officer at the Marion Correctional
Institution in Ocala, Fla., was sentenced to die for the murder
Jan. 23, 1978, of an 8-year-old Marion County girl.
   His execution was scheduled for 7 a.m. EDT Thursday at the
Florida State Prison near Starke.
</TEXT>
