<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 04,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday, May 4</HEAD>
<HEAD>Why We Save So Little</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One reason why Americans save so little is the
bomb, said the professor. If there's no tomorrow, that is, you'll
just be a gone fool.
   This is the latest contribution to the literature of why
Americans don't save more of their income. It is now a massive
collection and growing; no academic can retain his reputation
without taking a stab at the problem.
   The bomb thesis has been developed by Joel B. Slemrod of the
University of Michigan. Based on his studies of 20 non-communist
nations, the low-saving American registers the highest level of
fear of nuclear war.
   In 1986, he explains, 49 percent of his American respondents
felt there was an ``even or better-than-even chance'' of a nuclear
war within 10 years. At the same time, the U.S. savings rate was
19th. Only France's rate was lower.
   In Japan, on the other hand, only 15 percent of those surveyed
in the same year believed the chance of nuclear war within a decade
was 50 percent or better. Japan's savings rate was bettered only by
Italy and Luxembourg.
   Slemrod believes the evidence might compel a lot of economists
to revise their views of why Americans save relatively little. In
the past, he says, ``a lot of people have been blaming it on taxes
and the social security system.''
   And, you might add, on dozens of other things. On demographics,
for example. A surge of 25-to-34-year-olds has been coursing
through the economy. They must buy furniture, houses, cars,
children's clothing and such with money that otherwise might have
been put into savings.
   According to the theory, as these yuppies become older they'll
transmogrify into couch potatoes. They will sit before their
television sets, content not to keep buying and traveling. They
will save and invest for the future.
   That's just one notion. Among the others is that the methodology
by which savings statistics are amassed is faulty. As some explain
it, Americans use their houses as banks, but the statisticians
don't count that as saving.
   Social Security and private pension plans have been blamed. They
make Americans complacent about their futures, it is said, although
that notion is receiving a severe jolt from the actual, painful
experiences of retirees.
   There is no end to the possibilities that have been seriously
studied at academic institutions, analyzed by elected officials and
speculated on by economists. But there are also some very obvious
reasons that require no study.
   Such as:
   _In America, savings are taxed. It used to be even worse:
Savings were taxed while debt earned the borrower a great tax
deduction. In regard to housing debt it remains so. Even credit
card debt still gets a small deduction. The tax system in many
other countries encourages saving, even exempting some earned
interest from the tax collector.
   That idea caught on strongly in the United States a decade or so
ago with Individual Retirement Accounts. But IRAs have since been
weakened. Taxes on interest earnings are deferred, but no longer is
there a tax deduction.
   _In the United States, keeping up with the Joneses is a much
derided but much practiced philosophy of life. This is a consumer
society, not a saver society.
   If you don't think so, examine the basic theme of many
advertisements: If your neighbor has something why don't you?
Aren't you as good in every way as your neighbor? Then demonstrate
it.
   Consider some of the other themes: One car is not enough.
Neither is one bath in your house. In fact, one house isn't enough;
good heavens, what do you do on weekends?
   Save? Banks are for saving, aren't they? Maybe not, as you might
conclude from examining the literature you receive from them. How
many seek to have you save with them? How many offer you credit
instead?
   The U.S. personal savings rate rarely exceeds 6 percent,
compared with 20 percent or so in Japan. It is indeed puzzling, and
social scientists will question each other about it for many
academic years.
   The answer, however, is far more likely to come directly from
the source _ from the American consumer, who may indeed save little
because of the bomb, but who also might be borrowing more for the
same reason.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday, May 4.</NOTE>
