<DOCNO> AP890503-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 1315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-Zal Adv19-21   05-03 0793</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Zal, Adv 19-21,0810</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, May 19-21, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Roxana Zal Plays Jessica McClure's Mother in ABC Movie</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roxana Zal says she formed a quick friendship
with Cissy McClure after playing the young mother in the ABC movie
``Everybody's Baby: The Rescue of Jessica McClure.''
   ``We were very excited to meet each other,'' said Zal. ``It was
strange at first. A little awkward. Then we got along great. I
think we formed a bond. We write to each other. We're keeping in
touch.
   ``Neither of us had any walls up. We both wanted to help each
other. Jessica took to me, too. She climbed right up on my lap.''
   The two-hour movie, airing Sunday on ABC, is about the rescue of
18-month-old Jessica after she fell down an abandoned well near her
home in Midland, Texas, on Oct. 14, 1987. She was trapped 19 feet
underground in a space only eight inches wide.
   ``It's a real ensemble movie,'' said Zal. ``It shows how the
whole town came together to save the life of this child.''
   Zal said she had talked to Cissy McClure several times on the
telephone before she started the role. ``I think it was better that
I didn't see her until afterward,'' she said. ``I would have been
nervous if she'd been on the set. We tried to make it as accurate
as possible, but there may have been a few dramatic changes.''
   The movie also stars Beau Bridges as Police Chief Richard Czech,
Pat Hingle as Fire Chief James Roberts, Patty Duke as Carolyn
Henry, the victims' assistance volunteer who helped the McClures,
and Will Oldham as Chip McClure, Jessica's father.
   The movie was filmed largely on location in Bellflower, a city
about 12 miles southwest of downtown Los Angeles.
   ``They made it look just like the original site,'' said Zal.
``Rodney Wunsch, the reporter from KMID-TV who plays himself, said
it was so similar it brought back all those terrible thoughts.''
   Zal, who won an Emmy in 1984 for her role in ``Something About
Amelia,'' said she had followed the story of Jessica McClure and
was interested when her agent called about the offer.
   ``My first thought, however, was that it might be difficult,''
she said. ``Some films based on news events sound great, but the
scripts don't always work out. I knew it would be difficult to turn
those 56 hours into a good movie. But the script turned out well,
and I liked it. I like the role, too, because I get to play a
mother. I've always played daughters and teen-agers before.''
   Zal worked on the role while continuing her studies as a
second-year student at UCLA.
   ``I'm studying world arts and cultures,'' she said. ``I switched
from theater arts. I get dance, music, art history and
anthropology. My theater major had too many technical classes and
labs. You had to take all the production courses first before you
got to the fun stuff. I'm more interested in acting, directing and
playwriting. I'm trying to develop my writing skills.''
   Her most recent project was ``Goodbye, Miss 4th of July'' for
the Disney Channel. It was based on the true story of Niki Janus, a
member of a Greek immigrant family who fought back against
discrimination by the Ku Klux Klan in West Virginia in 1917. The
movie also starred Chris Sarandon, Chantal Contouri and Louis
Gossett Jr.
   She made her film debut as Jon Voight's daughter in ``Table for
Five.''
   She was also in ``Testament,'' ``River's Edge,'' the CBS
Schoolbreak Special ``God, The Universe and Hot Fudge Sundaes'' and
played the daughter of an alcoholic in the ABC movie ``Shattered
Spirits.''
   ``After the commercial I was in a pilot,'' she said. ``Then I
decided I didn't want to do a series and prayed it would not go. I
really don't want to do a series. I wouldn't be able to go to
college if I was in a series.
   ``I started acting when I was 11. I'd wanted to start when I was
8, but my parents wouldn't let me. Finally an aunt told them to let
me try it or I'd grow up resenting them. I can pick and choose my
roles. My parents have provided very well for me and I don't have
to take anything just to pay the bills.''
   She said she was considering several things for the summer.
``It's so hard to find a good script and the competition is so
tough,'' she said. ``That's why it's good to be in school. I'm not
just sitting around waiting for the telephone to ring.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, May 19-21</NOTE>
