<FIRST>s a BC-TestingWorkers-Lousig-Nont Adv07   05-03 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Testing Workers-Lousig-Nont, Adv 07,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 7, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Drugs and Ripoffs a Blessing To This Test Developer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wire</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Testing Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug abuse has been very, very good to Gregory
Lousig-Nont.
   So has theft.
   Lousig-Nont has built a career out of finding people who steal
and use drugs _ and helping prospective employers steer clear of
them.
   With a doctorate in industrial psychology, Lousig-Nont has
developed a series of tests he says help companies screen job
applicants based on their own admissions of attitudes and behavior.
   Last year Lousig-Nont &amp; Associates Inc. sold 300,000 honesty
tests, and business is booming.
   ``There's been a tremendous influx this year because of the
anti-polygraph legislation,'' he said, referring to a recent law
that bans most private employers' use of lie detector tests.
   With sales exceeding $1 million last year, Lousig-Nont's
business has grown at an annual average of 57 percent since he
began selling a comparatively crude version of his now-patented
honesty tests in 1978. He predicts sales will double by 1990.
   Lousig-Nont was a police officer in Peoria, Ill., in the 1970s
when he developed a reputation for interrogating suspects by using
a low-key, straightforward approach. His 95 percent confession rate
made him a stand-out, he said in an interview.
   ``I was sort of blown away by the fact that if I asked someone a
question, they'd usually give you the answer,'' he said. ``If they
lied to you, they became so guilty looking and would start pulling
at their collar or something that it was obvious.''
   It was that same approach that led him to develop the tests now
used by companies nationwide.
   Persistently surprised at how much people would tell him if he
asked, Lousig-Nont's first test contained 100 true-false questions.
Since then it has been refined and now is laced with what
Lousig-Nont called ``control'' questions to help determine whether
the applicant is generally truthful.
   He said the tests provide an assessment of a prospective
employee by measuring his or her ``propensity to become involved in
job dishonesty.''
   The tests, available in English and Spanish, sell for between $6
and $15 each, including the cost of an evaluation analysis by
Lousig-Nont's company. It is substantially cheaper than a urine
test to detect drug use.
   Now 40 and a millionaire, Lousig-Nont is one of a few
individuals who can go up against much larger test marketers such
as Stanton Corp., London House and Reid Psychological Systems.
   His tests have been used by National Convenience Stores, Radio
Shack and Wackenhut Corp., the national security firm, which has
certain rights to market the tests.
   Wackenhut has ``intros into a lot of companies I couldn't get my
foot in the door,'' Lousig-Nont said.
   Lousig-Nont's next project, he said, is to develop a personality
profile that will help determine whether an individual is suited
for a particular job. For example, an accountant doesn't have to be
an extrovert, but the trait certainly is useful for a publicist.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, May 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
