<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-03 0857</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0899</SECOND>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles billionaire Marvin Davis has
agreed to put his hostile $2.7 billion bid for Northwest Airlines'
parent on hold in exchange for confidential information on the
nation's fourth-largest airline.
   Under an agreement announced Tuesday by the airline company and
Davis, the oilman's offer will remain outstanding but he will
postpone buying more NWA Inc. shares until June 30.
   Davis also agreed to stop soliciting shareholder proxies in an
attempt to unseat the company's board of directors at the annual
meeting set for May 15.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government reported that sales of new
homes dropped 5.5 percent in March after plunging 10.5 percent in
February, as higher interest rates took their toll in the housing
market.
   Tuesday's report was the first time sales of new single-family
homes posted back-to-back declines since they fell five times in a
row in the months surrounding the October 1987 stock market crash.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government reported that orders to U.S.
factories for manufactured goods increased 0.7 percent in March,
but analysts still saw signs in the report that the economy was
cooling off.
   Orders for durable and non-durable goods rose to a seasonally
adjusted $232.9 billion in March after dropping 2 percent in
February and 1.2 percent in January, the Commerce Department said
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Banking Committee voted 49-2
approval of President Bush's proposal to spend $157 billion over 10
years to bail out the savings and loan industry from what has been
described as the worst financial crisis since the Depression.
   The bill approved late Tuesday also would put S&amp;L regulators
under more direct administration control, spend $75 million a year
on investigating and prosecuting fraud at S&amp;Ls and, in the key
reform, require S&amp;L owners to risk more of their own money when
they make loans.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the United Mine Workers strike
against Pittston Coal Group Inc. turned violent on the picket
lines, union and company officials agreed to sit down with federal
mediators.
   The announcement was made Tuesday in Richmond by Virginia Gov.
Gerald L. Baliles and Lt. Gov. L. Douglas Wilder. Baliles had asked
both sides to enter mediation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp.'s first-quarter earnings rose 91
percent from last year's depressed level, pushing profits for the
Big Three to a quarterly record.
   Chrysler said Tuesday it earned $351 million, or $1.50 a share,
during the first three months of the year, compared with $183.7
million, or 83 cents a share, during first quarter of 1988.
   Revenue rose 16 percent to $9.95 billion from $8.56 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO pledged to direct a nationwide
boycott of AT&amp;T if union members strike later this month. The
strategy could cost the long-distance giant millions of dollars
while giving union business to a non-union company.
   The labor federation's governing body on Tuesday approved the
plan, which asks the 14 million members of the AFL-CIO and its
affiliated unions to route their long-distance calls via non-union
US Sprint Communications Co.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. took pains to avoid competition
with Eastman Kodak Co., the chairman testified in the opening of
testimony in a trial over damages Kodak should pay for infringing
on its rival's instant-photography technology.
   In the first day of testimony in U.S. District Court, Polaroid
Chairman William J. McCune Jr. on Tuesday began to outline the
steps that led to head-to-head competition with Kodak.
   Polaroid is seeking $12 billion in damages from Kodak for
infringing on instant photography patents. An earlier court
decision found infringement occurred.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, who has argued for eliminating
trade subsidies, approved U.S. subsidies for the sale of 1.5
million tons of wheat to the Soviet Union in a major trade and
foreign policy decision.
   The sale approved Tuesday amounts to half the amount initially
proposed by the Agriculture Department and backed by farm-state
members of Congress. The subsidies apply to wheat intended for
delivery this month and in June.
   It was the first time Bush has directly approved subsides under
a 1985 law, the Export Enhancement Program, permitting export
subsidies to help U.S. farmers compete in international markets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Co. Chairman Paul A. Bilzerian used
trickery and deceit to build a phony reputation as a corporate
raider, a federal prosecutor told jurors at Bilzerian's securities
fraud trial.
   Bilzerian, 38, of Tampa, Fla., is accused of conspiracy,
violating securities and tax laws and making false statements in
connection with four failed takeover attempts in 1985 and 1986.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Prices dipped lower in dull and directionless trading on Wall
Street Tuesday as many investors stayed on the sidelines. The Dow
Jones average of 30 industrials fell 12.10 points to 2,402.86.
   The dollar finished higher against several key currencies. Gold
weakened slightly.
   Bond prices regained ground as oil prices declined and the
government issued two reports suggesting an economic slowdown.
   Petroleum futures prices dropped sharply; grain and soybean
futures dropped; precious metals closed lower; and livestock and
pork prices rallied.
</TEXT>
