<FIRST>r f PM-24-HourTrading     05-03 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-24-Hour Trading,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Exchange Chairman: No Current Need for 24-Hour Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Stock Exchange will implement
computerized off-hours trading if companies and investment firms
want it, but no such demand exists now, says the chairman of the
Big Board.
   John J. Phelan Jr. said Tuesday there has been no interest among
New York stock market participants to extend trading at the world's
second-largest exchange beyond the current 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m.
hours.
   ``The reason we have not done it is that our customers have said
they don't want it,'' Phelan told a meeting of the Society of
American Business Editors and Writers.
   But, he added, ``If there is any sign of interest out there at
all we will try at least some off-hours trading.''
   In 1986, the NYSE surveyed securities brokerages and companies
listed on the exchange, Phelan said, and ``99 percent of all those
people said, `For God's sake, don't do it. We are not interested in
that now.'''
   The 197-year-old NYSE, second in size to the Tokyo Stock
Exchange, recently announced it would meet with customers, traders,
institutional investors, listed companies and securities firms to
re-gauge demand for off-hours trading.
   Under such a system, securities theoretically can be bought and
sold when the exchange floor is shut down via computers that
automatically match buyers and sellers from points around the world.
   The tiny Cincinnati Stock Exchange last month announced plans to
start computerized 24-hour trading in the next 19 months. Chicago's
two futures markets also have announced they are developing
after-hours trading systems.
   Phelan played down fears expressed by some securities industry
experts that markets in foreign countries could siphon away
business from New York. He said the idea of a global market had not
yet taken hold, and that overseas ``there's more potential than
actual'' competition.
   ``Global markets and 24-hour markets, despite all the trendy
talk, are not there because the customers don't want them,'' he
said.
   ``In the off-hours market there's not going to be a heck of a
lot of orders,'' he added. ``Most pension funds are not going to
wait until two o'clock in the morning to make a trade. The major
pool of liquidity is going to be when this market opens.''
   But Phelan conceded that Japanese investors buying more stock in
American companies listed on the Tokyo exchange could some day pose
a threat. He said 90 U.S. companies currently trade in Tokyo.
   ``It's new money that's never been in this market before.
European money has been in this market for years. Japan's money has
never been in this market,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Bilzerian     05-03 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bilzerian,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Opens Securities Fraud Case Against Singer Chairman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors at the securities fraud trial of Singer
Co. Chairman Paul A. Bilzerian are getting a short course in
corporate takeovers, tender offers and other Wall Street
terminology.
   Before defense and prosecution lawyers began their opening
statements to the jury Tuesday, U.S. District Judge Robert J. Ward
took 10 minutes to explain to the jurors a number of financial
terms that will come up repeatedly during the trial.
   The education was to continue today with a securities law expert
expected to be the first government witness.
   In his opening statement Tuesday, Assistant U.S. Attorney David
E. Brodsky claimed that in 1985 and 1986, when he emerged on the
corporate takeover scene, Bilzerian ``sought to build a reputation
for himself as a corporate raider'' through a series of lies.
   ``He lied to the Securities and Exchange Commission, he lied to
the Internal Revenue Service and he lied to the investing public,''
Brodsky told the jury at federal court in Manhattan.
   ``In the past his lies brought him lots of money,'' said
Brodsky, pointing at Bilzerian. ``Today they bring him to the bar
of justice.''
   Bilzerian, 38, of Tampa, Fla., is accused of conspiracy,
violating securities and tax laws and making false statements in
connection with four failed takeover attempts in 1985 and 1986.
   Ward dismissed one felony count last month but 11 other counts
remain.
   None of the charges involves Bilzerian's $1.06 billion takeover
of Singer last year after a lengthy struggle.
   Brodsky said another prosecution witness would be former West
Coast stockbroker Boyd Jefferies, who was implicated by convicted
stock speculator Ivan F. Boesky, pleaded guilty to violating
securities laws in 1987 and has turned government informant.
   The indictment alleges that Jefferies secretly held stock for
Bilzerian in four unsuccessful takeover transactions involving
Cluett, Peabody &amp; Co., Hammerhill Paper Co., H.H. Robertson Co.,
and Armco Inc.
   The ruse allegedly was used to help Bilzerian secretly
accumulate large stock positions in companies he later would
attempt to take over.
   But defense attorney Arthur Mathews contended his client was on
trial because ``Mr. Brodsky's bosses made a dumb deal with an
admitted felon,'' Jefferies.
   Mathews, who did not mention Boesky by name, theorized that
Jefferies _ in order to avoid more serious charges _ ``implicated a
few scapegoats,'' including Bilzerian, because he had no higher-ups
on whom to inform.
   ``The government is straining to try and justify the bad bargain
they made,'' said Mathews.
   If convicted, Bilzerian faces a maximum penalty of five years in
jail and a $250,000 fine on each count.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
