<HEAD>Volvo Expands Investment In Hertz</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKLEIGH, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Volvo North America Corp. says it has
agreed to pay $30 million in cash for an additional 6 percent of
Hertz Corp.'s parent company.
   The purchase announced Tuesday of additional shares in Park
Ridge Corp. will bring Volvo's total stake in Hertz, a car rental
company, to 26 percent, said Bjorn Ahlstrom, president and chief
executive officer of Volvo.
   Volvo will buy its new equity in Park Ridge from Ford Motor Co.,
with the transaction expected to close in June, Volvo said in a
news release.
   ``Volvo's investment in Hertz has been an unqualified success,''
Ahlstrom said. ``Not only has it been profitable, it has also
exposed thousands of drivers to our cars for the first time.''
   Volvo bought its initial 20 percent stake in Park Ridge from
Ford in August 1988. Volvo North America is a subsidiary of AB
Volvo, based in Gothenburg, Sweden.
