<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was trading in a narrow, mostly
higher band in Europe late this morning, supported by bullish
sentiment but checked by fear of central bank intervention,
currency dealers said.
   Gold prices slipped.
   Trading was thinned by a national holiday in Japan and an
approaching holiday in Europe where many markets will close
Thursday for Ascension Day.
   Traders said there were concerns the central banks would step
back into the market, following Tuesday's joint action in which
they reportedly sold $300 million to $400 million.
   Markets were closed in Japan today for Constitution Day. In
London, the dollar was quoted at 134.20 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.8896 West German marks, up from 1.8875; 1.6820
Swiss francs, up from 1.6805; 6.3865 French francs, up from 6.3735;
2.1320 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1270; 1,382.75 lire, up from
1,379.50; 1.1815 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1830
   In London, the British pound fell slightly to $1.6838 from
$1.6845 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at $376 a troy ounce, down from $377.50
bid late Tuesday. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $376.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $376.60, down from $377.30 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 63 cents to close at a bid
$377.55.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.62 a troy
ounce, down from Tuesday's $5.65.
