<HEAD>London Share Prices Weaker At Midday In Dull Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were weaker at midday Wednesday, amid
continued lack of interest among institutional investors.
   At about 12:15 p.m., the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index was down 10.7 points, or 0.5 percent, at 2,092.4,
just 0.1 point above its lowest level. At its best, the index was
down 3.7 points at midmorning.
   By midday, 234.7 million shares had changed hands, compared with
166 million shares at the same time Tuesday.
   ``It's an extremely dull day. There just isn't anything going
on,'' said one equities salesman.
   But there also was a distinct lack of selling pressure, he noted.
   ``It's more a case of lethargy than anything else,'' he said.
