<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0816EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GoldTax     05-03 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gold Tax,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nevadans Approve Tax To Cash In On Gold Bonanza</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nevadans overwhelmingly approved a $52
million tax on miners who are now unearthing a gold bonanza that
rivals production during this state's famed Comstock Lode era.
   Voters also approved a plan to double the money Nevada can
borrow for new construction.
   With all votes counted in Tuesday's special election, the
two-year mining tax hike won 107,679 to 30,663. The other question
won by 74,418 to 63,228.
   Voter turnout was a low 36 percent. Election officials around
the state had predicted turnouts ranging from 30 percent to 40
percent of the more than 383,000 people eligible to vote.
   Nevada is the nation's leading producer of gold. During the past
eight years, mines here have produced more than 12 million troy
ounces of gold with a value of about $5 billion.
   At today's prices, that's equal to the value of all the gold and
silver unearthed in Virginia City during the two-decade Comstock
Lode era that began in the late 1850s.
   The mining tax plan was submitted to voters after bitter debate
in which Democratic Gov. Bob Miller accused mining industry
lobbyists of deceit in trying to derail his proposal for $118
million.
   The industry accused him of playing ``mine games.'' Miller
responded that the industry was trying to give the state ``the mine
shaft.''
   Casino owners, often targeted for tax hikes because gaming is
Nevada's largest industry, also got into the fray, arguing that
it's time to change the tradition in which the mining industry did
not pay its fair share of taxes.
   After Miller's plan was rejected in the Senate, the $52 million
plan was endorsed by most of the people who had fought over any
higher payments.
   Miller joined in an advertising campaign with mining industry
leaders to say that without approval, the state would face fiscal
chaos.
   Had the measure lost, the leaders said, the Legislature would
have needed to remain in session an extra month to slash budgets
and raise taxes.
   ``I think it's a positive thing for the state to have these
revenues available,'' Miller said late Tuesday. He added he planned
to meet with legislative leaders before deciding whether any more
tax revenues are needed from the miners.
   Assemblyman Marvin Sedway, Democratic chairman of the Ways and
Means Committee, had opposed the $52 million plan.
   ``The amount they would be paying is just a drop in the bucket
to what they should be paying,'' said Sedway. ``It (gold) is a
non-renewable resource, and will be gone forever.''
   The measure allows the state to impose a 5 percent tax on the
net proceeds of mines during the next two years. The question
resulted from an agreement during the 1987 Legislature between the
mining industry, lawmakers and then-Gov. Dick Bryan.
   Jim Gourdie, president of the Nevada Mining Association, said he
hoped passage would end this year's tax raising efforts in the
Legislature.
   ``I'm delighted with the outcome,'' he said. ``I think the
people have realized this is a reasonable and fair tax.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
