<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0829EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-S&amp;Ls 1stLd-Writethru f0020 05-03 0869</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0020,0892</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Gets Tougher S&amp;L Standards in Banking Panel Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf, It also, to CORRECT figure to $75 million sted
$75 billion and make it annual</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is getting everything he wanted
and more from the House Banking Committee to prevent S&amp;Ls from
tapping the taxpayers for another bailout, but only in exchange for
new low-income housing initiatives.
   On a 49-2 vote just before midnight Tuesday, the committee
approved Bush's $90 billion savings and loan plan _ the largest
financial bailout in the nation's history _ after spending four
days toughening capital standards on the industry and adding a pair
of housing components.
   Only Reps. Joseph Kennedy, D-Mass., and Jim Leach, R-Iowa, voted
no. Kennedy said the bill did not have enough housing support for
the poor and complained about the panel's rejection of his
provisions attacking lending discrimination. Leach said he wanted
still tougher capital standards.
   As it now stands, the House bill would require the nation's
3,000 thrifts to put up at least $20 billion in new capital over
the next five years _ twice as much as a version approved by the
Senate two weeks ago _ to fulfill Bush's promise of ``Never again.''
   It also would divorce what critics had called a too-cozy
relationship between S&amp;L regulators and the industry and devote $75
million a year to investigating and prosecuting fraud that is
blamed for a major portion of the crisis.
   On a party-line vote, committee Democrats overrode
administration objections to set aside some of the property the
government is inheriting from failed S&amp;Ls for low-income housing.
They also voted to require the industry to subsidize below-market
mortgage rates for low-income families.
   Still, the overall package won praise from the administration.
   ``This committee exceeded everyone's expectations,'' Assistant
Treasury Secretary David Mullins said. ``They've achieved something
very close to what we asked for.''
   The biggest victory for the administration is a requirement that
S&amp;L owners over the next five years reach a level of having at
least $3 of their own money in ``tangible'' capital at risk for
every $100 they lend.
   ``We've moved legislation that will deal with a significant part
of the problem ... and passed tough capital standards _ better than
the Senate bill and, I would argue, better than the Bush bill as
well,'' said Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.
   The bill still has to go through three other committees _
including one where the erection of a formidable roadblock is
anticipated later this month _ before a final vote by the full
House.
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, the banking committee's
chairman who spearheaded the administration's drive for the tougher
capital requirements, said industry lobbying efforts to weaken them
already have shifted there.
   And after that, new fights over the housing subsidies that were
rejected in the Senate as ``social engineering'' are expected to
erupt in a conference of leading lawmakers from both houses before
a final version is sent to Bush this summer for his approval or
veto.
   As proposed by Bush and now approved by both the House Banking
Committee and the Senate, the plan will pump $50 billion over the
next three years into a federal insurance fund to pay off
depositors whose money was lost through speculative and often
fraudulent lending by some 300 to 500 S&amp;Ls.
   Another $40 billion to cover the losses of institutions closed
in the past two years plus anticipated failures over the next
decade _ and also shore up the insurance fund _ will come largely
from new or increased fees on the industry.
   Altogether, the bailout costs _ including interest _ are
expected to total $157 billion by the year 2000 and $275 billion by
the year 2020.
   The government share will be raised through a complex financing
plan that keeps the problem off the federal budget and avoids a tax
increase, but at an interest cost to taxpayers of $150 billion to
$200 billion over the next 30 years.
   That arrangement is likely to be questioned at least one more
time by the tax-writing House Ways and Means Committee, one of
three panels yet to review the package.
   However, the next big showdown will not occur until the bill
reaches the House Rules Committee, which controls what issues can
be revisited on the House floor.
   The rules panel's chairman, Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla., said in
a letter last week he strongly opposes parts of the new capital
requirements.
   Industry and government records indicate that 14 S&amp;Ls in Florida
would have to raise a total of $700 million to $800 million in new
capital over the next five years or shrink in size.
   Rep. Steve Bartlett, R-Texas, said he expects the housing
provisions in the bill to be attacked on the House floor, along
with what he called one ``crystalizing amendment'' to stretch out
the implementation of the tougher capital standards.
   But he predicted the fights there will be few and short.
   ``Everybody in the country and the Congress realizes we need to
get this enacted and behind us,'' Bartlett said. ``The bill should
be signed by the president by the Fourth of July.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
