<DOCNO> AP890503-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 0857EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessOutlook     05-03 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Outlook,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed's Heller Sees Slower Growth, Steadying Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve's tight-fisted monetary
policy can curb inflation and prolong economic growth, but only if
business leaders exercise some patience, a central bank official
says.
   ``It takes time for monetary policy to relieve pressure on
prices,'' Federal Reserve board member H. Robert Heller told the
mid-year meeting of The Conference Board Tuesday. ``What is needed
now is a bit of patience to allow the policy that is in place to
work.''
   Heller, in a luncheon address to about 100 executives, said the
Fed is not out to take the ``proverbial punch bowl away.''
   ``We would just like everyone to drink a bit more slowly so that
the party can last a longer time.''
   Heller, who has been on the Federal Reserve's seven-member board
of governors since 1986, defended the tight rein the Fed has kept
on the nation's money supply this year.
   That monetary policy has forced interest rates up in an effort
to ease inflationary pressures by slowing business expansion.
   Recent economic data have indicated the economy is cooling down,
but the inflation picture is more clouded. Sharp rises in wholesale
and consumer prices earlier this year, along with a more recent
surge in oil and gasoline prices, have prompted some economists to
predict a new wave of strong inflation.
   The most pessimistic analysts see both recession and inflation
ahead.
   But Heller foresees neither.
   In general, he said, the overall outlook ``is for modified
growth and subdued inflationary tendencies.''
   ``Put simply, I just do not believe that the preconditions for a
sustained acceleration in inflation are now in place,'' he said.
   On the possibility of a recession, he added, ``the imbalances
which traditionally precede a recession are not visible and
indications are that the current expansion will continue.''
   And on the inflation front, he said a second year of drought in
the Corn Belt is unlikely and agricultural output should return to
normal this year, bringing down food prices.
   Despite the rise in crude oil prices from about $17 to more than
$20 a barrel since Jan. 1, ``recent history of the global oil
market suggests that prices beyond $20 a barrel will probably not
hold for long,'' Heller said.
   Although economic growth is slowing, he said, the vigorous pace
of corporate investment in plant and equipment expenditures is an
encouraging sign, as is the promise of a bipartisan congressional
agreement for the fiscal year 1990 federal budget.
   Reducing the federal budget deficit is essential for continued
economic growth, Heller said.
   ``Looking beyond the coming year, it is important that this
progress will be sustained in future years as well until fiscal
responsibility is again the norm.''
   The Conference Board is an international network of more than
20,000 senior business executives.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
