<FIRST>r f PM-Obit-Kirkland 1stLd-Writethru f0038 05-03 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Kirkland, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0038,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Fashion Editor at Life Magazine Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to CORRECT to more than 20 sted more than 30 years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sally Kirkland, the fashion editor of Life
magazine for more than 20 years, has died at age 77.
   Mrs. Kirkland died Monday of emphysema at St. Vincent's Hospital.
   Mrs. Kirkland was the fashion editor of Life from 1947 to 1969,
making the general-interest weekly influential in international
fashion. She received the Order of the Star of Solidarity from the
Italian government in 1954 for her reports on Italian clothes and a
Neiman-Marcus award in 1955 for contributions to fashion.
   After graduating from Vassar College in 1934, she went to work
in the college shop at Lord &amp; Taylor. Five years later, she became
assistant to the editor of Vogue Magazine. She joined Life as
fashion editor.
   After she left the magazine, she wrote a book about designer
Claire McCardell and contributed articles to the RAM Report, a
monthly trade journal.
   She is survived by a daughter, actress Sally Kirkland of Los
Angeles, and a brother, Robert T. Phinney of Santa Fe, N.M.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
