<FIRST>u f PM-Northwest-Davis 1stLd-Writethru f0010 05-03 0822</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest-Davis, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0010,0846</SECOND>
<HEAD>Davis Makes Offer Friendly; New York Firm May Make Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with New York buyout firm indicating
interest in buying NWA; EDITS to conform; picks up 6th graf pvs, ``I think...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles billionaire Marvin Davis has
agreed to put his hostile $2.7 billion bid for Northwest Airlines'
parent on hold in exchange for confidential information on the
nation's fourth-largest airline.
   Under an agreement announced Tuesday by the airline company and
Davis, the oilman's offer will remain outstanding but he will
postpone buying more NWA Inc. shares until June 30.
   Separately, the New York leveraged buyout firm of Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. indicated an interest in acquiring Northwest's
parent, NWA Inc., the Wall Street Journal reported today.
   KKR formally told Northwest of its interest in a bid, the
Journal reported, quoting unidentified people familiar with the
takeover battle. The notification came as part of a bidding
procedure NWA had set up in response to Davis's proxy challenge,
the Journal said.
   If KKR pursues a bid, it would be the firm's largest known
buyout effort since it bought RJR Nabisco Inc. for $25 billion in
February, according to the Journal.
   Spokesmen for KKR and NWA refused comment on KKR's apparent
interest, the newspaper said.
   KKR's disclosure came in response to a deadline set by NWA's
investment banker, First Boston Corp., the Journal said. Bidders
will next get access to confidential company data as well as
meetings with company management.
   In the the agreement reached Tuesday between Davis and
Northwest, Davis also agreed to stop soliciting shareholder proxies
in an attempt to unseat the company's board of directors at the
annual meeting set for May 15. Analysts generally agreed that it
may put Davis in an improved position.
   ``I would assume that he is no longer hostile. He's been folded
into the process,'' said analyst Kurt Rivard for Minneapolis-based
Dain Bosworth Inc.
   Earlier, the NWA board rejected Davis' $90-a-share offer as
financially inadequate.
   ``I think it puts him in a position to make an educated bid for
the company. He's going to have access to information he didn't
have before,'' Rivard said. ``Who knows? Mr. Davis may look at the
information and run away from the deal.''
   In a statement, NWA said, ``The agreement affords Mr. Davis the
opportunity to participate in NWA's process for exploring
alternatives designed to enhance stockholder value.
   ``Davis will be treated on an equal basis with all other bidders
in connection with the procedures which are established by NWA for
bids in connection with a possible sale of the company,'' added a
statement from Davis Acquisition, the company Davis formed to
acquire NWA.
   ``Davis will be permitted to make its best bid to the board of
directors for a negotiated acquisition after reviewing the
non-public information,'' Davis Acquisition said.
   But it doesn't mean Davis and NWA are on good terms, Rivard said.
   ``The psychology is he probably hasn't won any friends at
Northwest the way he has handled the deal. He's been aggressive,
aggressively hostile to the board,'' the analyst said.
   Davis said the restrictions will end immediately if NWA
announces the sale of the company or a non-sale alternative,
including no transaction at all, before June 30.
   Davis also said NWA agreed to give him 10 days notice if it
decides to pursue certain non-sale alternatives.
   NWA shares closed Tuesday at $101.75 in consolidated New York
Stock Exchange trading, down 25 cents. The Davis accord was
announced after the market closed.
   From the beginning of the takeover battle, Northwest officials
said they were willing to accept queries from every potential
bidder willing to sign a confidentiality statement, Rivard said.
   ``I think effectively what it does is it takes Davis from the
outside and moves him to the inside,'' he said. As for NWA, Rivard
said, ``It saves them the proxy fight ... although I think it was a
long shot for Davis.''
   Under the agreement, all pending litigation between the parties
will be put on hold. But Davis said he will continue his action in
U.S. District Court in St. Paul to overturn a Thursday order by
state Commerce Commissioner Michael Hatch that prohibits Minnesota
shareholders from selling their NWA shares to Davis.
   Under the state's anti-takeover law, Hatch has said Davis must
explain how he would operate the airline company in light of the
large sum he proposes to borrow to buy it.
   Davis has said he does not intend to sell the the airline's
strategic assets, reduce payroll or move the headquarters from
suburban Eagan, but his lawyers have indicated he may refinance or
sell NWA's Tokyo real estate, reduce travel agent commissions or
change Northwest's in-flight service.
   Davis contends disclosure of his specific plans for operating
the airline, as Hatch requested, would put him at a competitive
disadvantage with other suitors.
</TEXT>
