<FIRST>u f PM-Ozone 1stLd-Writethru f0030 05-03 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ozone, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0030,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference Split Over Aid For Developing Countries</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with split over 3rd World financing.
No Pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATTI HUUHTANEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 90 countries agreed today to
support a ban on ozone-destroying chemicals by the year 2000, but
they split over how to help Third World countries pay for safer
technology.
   Delegates from 86 countries and nearly 100 non-governmental
organizations at the U.N.-sponsored conference adopted a resolution
calling for industrial countries to help developing nations replace
equipment emitting harmful chlorofluorocarbons. But it made no
specific funding proposals.
   Mostafa K. Tolba, head of the U.N. Environment Program, proposed
an international climate fund to help Third World countries comply
with the program to phase out chemicals that deplete the earth's
shield of ozone.
   But industrial countries led by Britain, the United States and
Canada objected, favored a bilateral approach.
   British Environment Minister Nicholas Ridley dismissed Tolba's
idea as ``simplistic.''
   ``It has not been suggested who would run such a fund, how it
would operate, on what criteria its funds would be raised, and from
whom, and what would happen if they did not contribute,'' Ridley
told the conference.
   Norway, the only country to make a solid proposal, offered to
contribute 0.1 percent of its gross national income _ about $88
million _ to the climate fund, if other industrial nations do the
same.
   Tolba suggested a working group from the 48 countries that
ratified the 1987 Montreal Protocol draw up a specific funding plan
and submit it next year.
   While politicians discussed finances, scientists questioned
whether alternatives are at hand to replace the most harmful
chemicals _ the chlorofluorocarbons used for refrigeration,
insolvents and other industrial processes.
   Kevin J. Fay, of the Alliance for Responsible Chlorofluorocarbon
Policy, said the Montreal Protocol was based on the assumption the
chemicals could be substituted by hydrochlorofluorocarbons and
other new and presumably safer variations. The new compounds are
the best known replacements, but ``we don't know enough about
them,'' Fay told reporters.
   ``They cannot be used until we have the answers to questions for
their safety for the environment,'' said Fay, whose alliance is a
coalition of hundreds of U.S. industries cooperating in the search
for alternatives.
   ``There's no way that the deadlines can be met'' if the new
chemicals are found to be unusable, he said.
   Non-governmental organizations said Tuesday's declaration ``does
not go far enough,'' according to David Doniger of the Natural
Resources Defense Council in Washington. They called for a ``crash
program'' to eliminate the chemicals by 1995.
   The four-day conference, the First Meeting of the Parties to the
Montreal Protocol, was to update the 1987 document requiring
signatories to halve by 1999 their production of five
chlorofluorocarbons and three halons, which break down ozone and
increase the risk of skin cancers and eye disease.
   Annual chlorofluorocarbon production is 1.14 million tons,
two-thirds of which is produced by the United States and Western
Europe. Japan produces 12 percent and the Soviet Union about 10
percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
