<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Spiegel     05-03 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Spiegel,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports 7 Percent Drop In Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAK BROOK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spiegel Inc., the nation's largest
mail-order retailer, Wednesday reported its first-quarter profit
fell 7.4 percent, largely due to the costs of acquiring Eddie Bauer
Inc. and Honeybee Inc.
   The Oak Brook-based company said its after-tax income totaled
$6.34 million, or 12 cents a share, in the three months ended March
31, down from $6.85 million, or 15 cents a share, for the same
period a year before.
   Revenue for the quarter amounted to $324.5 million, a 37 percent
increase over $236.7 million in the first quarter of 1988.
   Operating income rose 13 percent, to $24.2 million from $21.4
million, Spiegel said in an prepared announcement about its
financial results.
   The company said it paid about $6 million, before taxes, in
interest during the quarter to finance its purchases of Eddie
Bauer, a mail-order sportswear and outdoor-equipment company, and
Honeybee, a chain of women's apparel stores.
   Both acquisitions were announced in 1988.
   John J. Shea, Spiegel's president and chief executive, said the
company's profit margin on net sales rose to 33.2 percent from 32.7
percent in 1988's first quarter. He attributed the improvement to a
lower level of goods sold at marked-down prices, a result of better
inventory management.
   ``The outlook for the coming months is promising,'' Shea stated.
``Apparel sales have strengthened and home furnishings remain
strong. We are well-positioned to continue to fulfill our
customers' needs in both of these areas.''
</TEXT>
