<HEAD>Wheat Prices Drop Despite Sale to Soviets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade, with the announcement of a
wheat sale to the Soviet Union having little effect on wheat prices.
   A slight drop in wheat futures in early trading came as somewhat
of a surprise.
   Wheat was expected to open higher following yesterday's White
House announcement that the United States will sell 1.5 million
metric tons of wheat to the Soviet Union.
   ``The market has had a fairly good gain over the last few days
and apparently has already factored in the wheat sale,'' said Joel
Karlin, an analyst for Research Department Inc., in Chicago.
   Corn and soybean prices were mixed, with the prospect of more
rain in the Midwest weighing on the market.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 2{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.26 a bushel; corn was \ cent
lower to \ cent higher with May at $3.73} a bushel; oats were 1}
cents to 2 cents lower with May at $1.82\ a bushel; soybeans were
1} cents lower to 4 cents higher with May at $7.38 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent to .40 cent higher with June at 72.35
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .03 cent to .62 cent higher with
May at 76.75 cents a pound; hogs were .17 cent lower to .25 cent
higher with June at 47.25 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.05 cent lower to .13 cent higher with May at 31.70 cents a pound.
   Livestock and pork futures settled higher Tuesday.
