<FIRST>u f PM-UMW-Pittston 1stLd-Writethru f0011 05-03 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UMW-Pittston, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0011,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union, Company Agree To Mediation as Coal Strike Turns Violent</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to update with peaceful picketing today;
edits throughout to tighten</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking United Mine Workers resumed
picketing today after union and Pittston Coal Group Inc. officials
agreed to sit down with federal mediators but disagreed on a
seven-day cooling-off period.
   By midmorning the picket lines remained peaceful, unlike Tuesday
when strikers pelted company coal trucks with rocks. Several miners
and truck drivers were injured.
   Also Tuesday, 125 demonstrators were arrested at the company's
Moss No. 3 coal preparation plant at St. Paul. Those arrested, some
of them miners' wives, sat in front of plant entrances to block
coal trucks. They were charged with trespassing, a misdemeanor,
said State Police Lt. C.F. Eaton.
   About 1,500 miners in southwestern Virginia and West Virginia
have been on strike since April 5. The miners had been working
without a contract since February 1988.
   The mediation agreement was announced Tuesday in Richmond by
Virginia Gov. Gerald L. Baliles.
   UMW President Richard Trumka said the union was committed to
bargaining around the clock beginning immediately for seven days.
Trumka also suggested a seven-day cooling off period during which
Pittston would cease production and the union halt its
demonstrations.
   But Pittston President Michael Odom said he did not want his
company, a division of the Pittston Co. of Greenwich, Conn., to be
bound by a seven-day period for mediation.
   ``We strongly believe ... the mediator assigned to the dispute
should have some opportunity to become familiar with the very
complicated issues involved,'' he said.
   Odom also said he saw no reason for a cooling-off period.
   ``Lawful and peaceful picketing is not an impediment to the
process. It is the union's violence that brings disruption to the
coalfield communities,'' he said.
   The injuries occurred at a coal processing plant near McClure,
where coal trucks were being driven by workers from Jamb Coal Co.
under contract to Pittston.
   State Police spokesman Charles Vaughn said troopers told him the
injured strikers were in a parked vehicle that was hit by a coal
truck when the driver attempted to flee ``a hailstorm of rocks
thrown by miners.''
   But miner Larry Stanley said about 20 miners were standing
around watching the coal trucks drive around a tree downed in the
road when the driver of an escort vehicle rammed into the crowd.
   ``He done his best to run over all he could,'' said Stanley.
   Debbie Hall, nursing supervisor at Russell County Medical Center
in Lebanon, said five strikers were treated there and released and
two others were admitted. One truck driver was admitted and another
was transferred to Humana Hospital in Richlands, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
