<FIRST>u f PM-TWA     05-03 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TWA,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>TWA Pilots Will Appeal Breach Of Contract Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pilots for Trans World Airlines said today they
would appeal a New York state Supreme Court justice's decision that
upheld the actions of TWA Chairman Carl C. Icahn in taking the
company private last year.
   Justice Michael Dontzin Tuesday rejected a challenge by the
pilots, which said the October transaction violated labor
agreements.
   Dontzin, ruling after a trial held in December, found that the
going private transaction was accomplished in accordance with TWA's
labor agreement, the airline said after Tuesday's ruling.
   Pilot Capt. Thomas Ashwood said the appeal seeks to improve the
financial condition of the New York-based carrier by forcing
compliance with contractual commitments intended to assure the
profitable growth of TWA.
   ``The most recent TWA ... financial statement filed with the
Securities and Exchange Commission confirms our reasons for filing
this suit and the absolute necessity of pursuing it through the
appellate process,'' Ashwood said in a prepared statement today.
   The ALPA agreements were entered into in late 1985 and early
1986 when Icahn assumed control of the airline, said TWA, which is
based in suburban Mount Kisco, N.Y.
   ``I am gratified that the actions of TWA in accomplishing the
going private transaction have been vindicated and found to be
totally consistent with my commitment to my unions,'' Icahn said in
a statement issued late Tuesday.
