Wednesday with Airbus Industrie for eight new aircraft and options
for four more jetliners in the largest order the European aircraft
maker has ever received from a charter airline.
   TEA, of Belgium, will take delivery on the eight A310-300,
wide-bodied planes beginning in late 1990, an Airbus statement said.
   The plans will seat 275 passengers in an all-economy layout.
   The total price of the deal was not disclosed, but Airbus said
each of the jetliners costs about $62 million.
   TEA took delivery of the second Airbus aircraft ever built, an
A300B1. The plane is still in service.
   To date, 543 A300 and A310 aircraft have been sold to 65
customers, Airbus said.
