<HEAD>HP Says Apollo Purchase Clears Federal Review</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hewlett-Packard Co.'s agreement to
acquire Apollo Computer Inc. for $476 million in cash has cleared a
federal antitrust review, the company said Wednesday.
   The deal for Chelmsford, Mass.-based Apollo, announced last
month, will give Hewlett-Packard the largest share of the $4
billion market for workstations, which are speedier cousins of
personal computers with better graphics.
   ``The prompt regulatory clearance is a very positive and
reassuring sign to customers, employees and shareholders,'' said
John A. Young, Hewlett-Packard's president and chief executive
officer.
   ``We're confident our customers will benefit from the combined
marketing, technology and product capabilities we will bring to the
fastest-growing segment of the computer industry,'' Young said.
   Hewlett-Packard spokeswoman Marlene Somsak said a deadline for
antitrust review by the Justice Department and Federal Trade
Commission expired at midnight Tuesday without Hewlett-Packard
receiving any requests for more documentation about the acquisition
plan.
