<FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales     05-03 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Sales,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Three Car and Truck Sales Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs version planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car and light truck sales by the nation's Big
Three automakers in late April dropped 3 percent, compared with the
same period a year ago when sales were moderately strong, the
companies said Wednesday.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. said
they sold cars and light trucks at an average daily rate of 41,487
during the April 21-30 period this year compared with a rate of
42,772 during the same time last year.
   A 6.2 percent drop in car sales was offset partially by a 2.7
percent increase in light truck sales by the Big Three.
   For the entire month, when each of the companies offered
wide-ranging incentive packages, car and truck sales were up 6.3
percent this year over last April. For the year through April,
vehicle sales were down 5.7 percent compared with the same period
last year.
   The companies have been looking closely at sales results after
the usually strong March and April buying season got off to a slow
start. The incentives are aimed at boosting vehicle sales, which
sagged below expectations during the first three months of the
year, and at forestalling production cuts later in the year.
   However, analysts have said they expected the companies to trim
their production rates during the second half of the year, mainly
through extended model-changeover times during the late summer and
early fall.
   Ford's car sales suffered the most during late April, running
7.4 percent behind last year. Ford's cars sold at an average daily
rate of 7,980 this year, compared with a rate of 8,619 during the
period last year. For the month, Ford's car sales were up 12.9
percent, and through the first four months of this year, car sales
were 0.1 percent over last year's pace.
   The company's light trucks sold in late April at a rate 6.2
percent below the same period last year and through the first four
months of the year sold 2.9 percent under the pace of a year ago.
   GM said its car sales were off 6.1 percent in late April, going
to a daily rate of 13,666 this year from a rate of 14,560 last
year. Sales for the entire month were up 1.2 percent this year, and
GM car sales since Jan. 1 were off 10.7 percent.
   Sales of GM's light trucks ran 14.3 percent ahead of the pace
the company set during late April last year, and for the year,
truck sales were off 1 percent.
   Chrysler showed the smallest decline in car sales in late April,
dropping 4 percent to a daily rate of 4,127 this year, compared
with 4,299 last year. Chrysler's car sales for all of April ran 2.9
percent behind last year's level and for the entire year 17 percent
behind.
   Truck sales by Chrysler were down 1.3 percent in late April and
up 2 percent for the entire year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 1554EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-TestingWorkers Adv07 1stLd-Writethru 05-03 1152</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Testing Workers, Adv 07, 1st Ld-Writethru,1184</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, May 7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Honesty Tests Increasingly Used To Identify Undesirable Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf to show figures are based on government and private
estimates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The interview went well, but before Alfonso Morris got his
clerk's job at a Stop 'N Go store in Dallas, he had to spend an
hour taking a test aimed at determining whether he's a liar, thief
or substance abuser.
   It wasn't the first time. In the past two years, Morris, 26, had
been asked by three prospective employers to submit to a
paper-and-pencil grilling about whether he'd used drugs or stolen
any money or merchandise.
   His experience reflects a nationwide quest to create a
drug-free, theft-free workplace, which has increased employer use
of honesty and integrity tests designed to identify potential
problem workers.
   ``They told me they give the survey to everyone before they hire
them, basically to screen you,'' Morris said of Stop 'N Go, which
hired him in March. ``I didn't think too much about it _ I know I'm
a good person and should screen well.''
   But critics complain the tests amount to a written version of a
lie-detector or polygraph exam, violate privacy, aren't scientific
and encourage lazy hiring practices. Some contend the tests can be
designed to detect political beliefs or union sympathies.
   Others fear honest applicants mistakenly will be denied jobs,
although test creators warn against using their questions as the
sole determinant of employment because the tests aren't 100 percent
foolproof.
   Many businesses have reason to suspect workers. Government and
private estimates suggest substance abuse costs about $177 billion
a year in absenteeism, lower productivity, lower work-quality and
higher benefits costs, while employee theft accounts for estimated
losses of $40 billion a year.
   Honesty tests range in cost from $6 to $15 each, including an
evaluation of the results by the test creators. For identifying
drug abusers, they are becoming an attractive alternative to urine
tests, which can cost up to $50 each, are often considered
unreliable and face growing legal challenges.
   A law that took effect in December barring most private
employers from administering polygraph tests also gave written
honesty tests a boost.
   ``As soon as polygraph testing was banned, a bunch of
entrepreneurs got in the act and developed tests that do not
specifically violate any laws and act against other mechanical
forms of testing,'' said Loren Siegel, an attorney for the American
Civil Liberties Union in New York.
   The first honesty or integrity tests were developed in the 1960s
by a company now called Reid Psychological Systems, but their use
has multiplied in the past few years. In 1986, an estimated 2.3
million honesty tests were administered; the number is expected to
jump to 5.5 million by next year.
   The tests are surprisingly straightforward. They might ask
whether the applicant has ever stolen anything from an employer, or
how many times in the past month the applicant has used drugs.
   William Rognas, a Kentucky Fried Chicken franchisee with five
stores in Illinois, for the past two years has required applicants
to take an honesty test. Results are startling.
   Rognas said his food costs have dropped about 4 percent because
employees aren't stealing, and labor costs are down the same amount
as efficiency improved.
   ``We hired one guy without the test and asked him to take it
later. He failed, and we ended up firing him because he was
stealing. It works,'' Rognas said.
   The nationwide crusade against drugs is considered a major
catalyst pushing employers into the nebulous frontier of employee
privacy. ``A lot of this stuff would not be possible were it not
for ... the drug scare that exists,'' Siegel said. ``People are
willing to sacrifice some very fundamental rights'' of privacy.
   With the federal government conceding the drug problem's awesome
magnitude, some experts say a ``policing function'' has been
shifted to business. Siegel said employee testing represents ``the
privatization of law enforcement.''
   Who would admit to drug abuse or theft? Gregory Lousig-Nont,
whose Las Vegas-based company develops and markets honesty tests,
said he continually is surprised at how forthright applicants are
about past transgressions.
   Of 10,723 people applying for work at a national convenience
store chain that took his test last year, 777 admitted to having
shoplifted a total of $26,190 in merchandise, 902 said they think
about shoplifting, and 290 admitted having stolen $67,579 in
merchandise from previous jobs.
   Of 10,440 people tested for the same company, 1,142 admitted to
overdrinking, 739 said they used cocaine and 37 said they sold
amphetamines.
   Questions are designed to prevent a person who used marijuana
once 5 years ago from being lumped into the same ``risk'' category
as one who sold cocaine last week, Lousig-Nont said.
   Experts say some people confess outright because it describes
behavior that has become normal for them. Others are likely to be
tripped up by questions that probe attitudes toward stealing and
taking drugs.
   Employees have no recourse but to submit to testing, even though
experts say court challenges to the tests are inevitable.
   ``If you don't take it, they won't hire you, and there's nothing
you can do about it. That's the bottom line,'' the ACLU's Siegel
said.
   The vast majority of people don't object. Reid Psychological
statistics showed 92 percent of test takers accepted the test while
only 3 percent resented it and the rest had no opinion.
   ``They're user-friendly, uncomplicated and non-stressful,'' said
Robert McCrie, an assistant professor at John Jay College of
Criminal Justice in New York.
   ``Often people are told it's just part of the screening
process,'' he said. ``They're very revealing _ an individual that
could never ask about integrity in a face-to-face interview gets
(information) from people who quite willingly provide it.''
   Nonetheless, the tests are coming under scrutiny. Last October
the House Education and Labor Committee requested a study on the
tests' validity and the ethical implications of their widespread
use. The study, conducted by the Office of Technology Assessment,
is expected to be completed this summer.
   Committee member Rep. Pat Williams, D-Mont., said the tests are
epitomized by a country-western song that goes, ``If you hang `em
all, you get the guilty.''
   Businesses, particularly small ones, ``appear to find it easier
to throw a very wide net than to specifically try to do legitimate
and appropriate personnel screening,'' Williams said.
``Paper-and-pencil tests may not be valid, but they're a hell of a
lot cheaper than personnel departments.''
   The American Psychological Association is studying whether the
tests conform to research standards, since virtually all test
studies have been conducted by the companies that sell them.
   ``The publishers say the tests are valid 80 percent of the time
... there seems to be some skepticism, but basically the jury's
still out,'' said Wayne Camara, the association's director of
scientific affairs.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, May 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
