<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-03 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0258</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed higher
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, with wheat prices up
strongly following the White House announcement of additional
subsidized grain sales to the Soviet Union.
   Wheat opened lower at the start of trading, surprising the
market, which expected a strong start for wheat futures.
   ``There were a lot of people who thought the Russian business
was already reflected in prices,'' said Rich Feltes, an analyst
with Refco Inc., in Chicago. ``Today's action showed that any kind
of business outside the United States will be positive'' for the
market.
   The Bush administration has agreed the United States will sell
1.5 million metric tons of wheat to the Soviet Union. The
announcement of the sale was made Tuesday.
   Soybean futures rallied after mid-session, helped along by
continued strength in May soybean demand.
   ``With farmer preoccupation with field work, there is not a lot
soybeans moving to processors or to exporting channels,'' Feltes
said.
   Corn was up modestly, with fairly good rains in Western corn
producing states weighing heavily on the market.
   Wheat closed 1 cent to 11 cents higher with the contract for May
delivery at $4.37{ a bushel; corn was { cent to 2{ cents higher
with May at $2.76 a bushel; oats were { cent to 2} cents higher
with May at $1.87 cents a bushel; soybeans were 6 cents to 13 cents
higher with May at $7.47 a bushel.
