<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Steady In Europe, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar closed narrowly mixed in light
European trading Wednesday. Gold prices rose.
   Foreign exchange dealers said that on the eve of the Ascension
Day holiday, when most European markets will be closed, the dollar
held firm despite intervention by central banks, including the U.S.
Federal Reserve.
   The central banks have been acting concertedly for days to sell
dollars to keep the currency's exchange rate down.
   One London dealer said the dollar's firm tone reflected investor
buying but others wondered how long the dollar can continue to
resist central banks' intervention.
   Dealers said the dollar's short-term direction could be
determined by the release on Friday of the U.S. unemployment
figures for April, an indication of the condition of the U.S.
economy last month.
   While markets in Japan were closed for the Constitution Day
holiday, the dollar strengthened against the Japanese yen in
London, trading late at 133.93 yen, up from Tuesday's closing
133.85 yen in Tokyo.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6847 late Wednesday, more
expensive for buyers than Tuesday's late $1.6845.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared to Tuesday's
late rates: 1.8900 West German marks, up from 1.8875; 1.6830 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6805; 6.3725 French francs, down from 6.3735;
2.1270 Dutch guilders, unchanged; 1,379.20 Italian lire, down from
1,379.50; and 1.1830 Canadian dollars, unchanged.
   Gold bullion gained nearly $2 in Zurich, The late bid price was
$379.00 a troy ounce, up from $377.30 late Tuesday. The late bid
price in London was $377.95 an ounce, up from $377.50.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $376.55 an ounce, up from
$375.95.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid price of $5.65 a
troy ounce, unchanged.
</TEXT>
