<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 1607EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-MinimumWage     05-03 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minimum Wage,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Renews Threat to Veto Minimum Wage Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House said Wednesday that President
Bush will veto compromise legislation worked out by the House and
Senate to raise the mimimum wage from $3.35 to $4.55 an hour by
1991.
   Reacting to Tuesday's agreement between House and Senate
negotiators on legislation to change the wage rate for the first
time in eight years, White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater
said Bush continues to believe the figure is too high.
   ``The president's position is the same, and he reiterated that''
during a meeting with Republican senators, the spokesman said.
``His first proposal (for a $4.25 top rate) was his last proposal.
... He is prepared to veto the bill if they send it up.''
   Bush's stance sets up the first showdown on domestic policy
involving the new president and the Democratic-controlled Congress.
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole several weeks ago told Bush there
were enough Senate supporters of his position to sustain a veto. An
override of a presidential veto requires two-thirds of those
present and voting in both the House and the Senate.
   Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas also said Bush would
hold to his earlier promise to veto the bill.
   ``I just want to set the record straight _ the president will
not yield on this,'' Dole said. In reaching consensus on a final
bill so swiftly, Dole said, Democrats pushing the legislation ``in
effect asked for a confrontation with the president.''
   It took less than an hour Tuesday for the conferees to complete
their work, thanks in large part to staff negotiations conducted
during last week's congressional recess.
   Also contributing to the speedy resolution was that the major
elements of the House and Senate bills were the same. Each called
for raising the hourly minimum wage from $3.35 to $4.55 by October
1991 and for allowing employers to pay some new workers a
subminimum training wage for two months.
   On the subminimum, the final product contains language very
close to the Senate version, allowing employers to pay new hires 85
percent of the minimum wage if the newcomers have not held a job
for more than 60 days. Once an individual held a job for 60 days,
he or she would never again be eligible to be paid the training
wage.
   The legislation could reach the White House within two weeks,
after passage by the separate houses.
   Bush has said $4.25 an hour is the highest minimum he will
accept, and even that support hinges on a six-month subminimum that
could be paid to all new hires regardless of past job experience.
   Democrats sponsoring the legislation said they were prepared to
confront Bush with the measure and would attempt to override his
expected veto, although they concede Bush currently has more than
enough votes to stymie an override effort.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Colbert-Courses Adv07   05-03 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Colbert-Courses, Adv 07,0867</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, May 7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Switch from Pro to Proprietor A Big Step</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Colbert once earned a living by artfully
whacking a little ball across expansive green lawns and sandy
gullies, seldom thinking about the battles with Mother Nature that
go into golf course designs.
   Now that he's switched from pro to proprietor, he thinks of
little else.
   Today, Jim Colbert Golf Inc. owns or operates 14 public and
private golf courses from California to Florida, with the number
expected to expand into the 20s by the end of the year.
   Colbert is rolling now, but he's learned the hard way that
weather can make or break a good golf operation.
   ``This whole business evolves around water,'' Colbert, 48, said
in an interview. ``You may be plagued with too much or too little.
Once a course is built, the only thing left is drainage, drainage,
drainage _ whether it's yours or the Lord's.
   ``With our courses in Louisiana, the problem is too much water.
In Las Vegas, it's too little.''
   The exception was in 1984, when a rare Las Vegas flood swamped a
course where Colbert's fledgling company had spent $1 million in
remodeling work.
   ``It took $1.5 million and two years to fix it up,'' Colbert
said of damage to the old county-run Winterwood Golf Course. ``That
was our welcome to the golf course business.''
   Today Colbert's company has 500 employees at courses in nine
states.
   Colbert credits a bad back and a decade of duty on the 10-member
PGA Tour Policy Board with nudging him into the golf course
business.
   He served with the leaders of giant corporations, learning how
to build companies and golf courses. By the time he left the board
in 1984, the organization had built 12 TPC (The Players Club)
courses.
   The courses are used as a PGA tournament course once a year, and
the remainder of the year as public or private courses. They are
operated by the PGA tour and ``are very good profit centers for the
tour,'' Colbert said.
   ``Being involved in the building of these courses peeked my
interest in golf courses,'' Colbert recalled.
   Colbert won his first pro title in 1969. By the time nagging
back problems forced him to the sidelines 18 years later, he had
won eight tournaments and more than $1.5 million in prize money.
   ``I didn't play half the time,'' Colbert said of a four-year
span beginning in 1976, when the back problems intensified. ``It
looked like my career was over.''
   A native of Elizabeth, N.J., Colbert grew up in the Kansas City
suburb of Prairie Village, Kan. and attended Kansas State
University in Manhattan on a football scholarship from 1959 to
1964, honing his golf skills as well.
   He called on old friend Ron Fogler, who'd run the Manhattan
Country Club for 23 years, when he cut a deal with the city of Las
Vegas to take over the city course in 1981.
   ``I'd been a touring pro,'' Colbert said. ``I didn't know much
about the operational end of things.''
   Fogler, who had twice served as PGA vice president, took over
the management of the company, concentrating on construction and
remodeling of courses. He remains a key to the company's
operations, utilizing four decades of expertise in the golf course
business.
   The company took on its second project in 1983, Clark County's
Winterwood course. It spent $1 million remodeling the course,
located on the east side of Las Vegas. A disastrous flood that
swamped Las Vegas in 1984 caused $1.5 million damage to the course,
and left a two-year rebuilding challenge.
   ``The second one almost killed us,'' Colbert said. ``We had to
get No. 3 (Phoenix), No. 4 (San Dimas, Calif.) and No. 5 (Tulsa) to
pay for No. 2. It was kind of like Murphy's Law took over. Whatever
could go wrong did.''
   Today Colbert's company owns or operates courses in California,
Florida, Nevada, Louisiana, North Carolina, Kansas, Tennessee, West
Virginia and Arkansas. He declined to give a dollar value of his
company.
   Besides long hours in his Las Vegas office and trips around the
country checking out new course opportunities, he also serves as
sportcaster analyst for the ESPN network at 18 golf tournaments a
year.
   ``We look for problems,'' Colbert said his search for new
properties. ``We look for shortcomings. If we can identify and
solve them, we're a serious buyer. We think more of a product, many
times, than the people who own it.
   ``The art of this trade is buying something and making a profit.
We'll take a bad facility as long as we know we can make it
better.''
   Did he ever dream he'd be a major player in the golf course
business?
   ``I wish I could say I was that smart, but too many people know
me,'' Colbert laughed. ``I saw a tiny hole and I went through that
door.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, May 7</NOTE>
