<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-WallStreet-Layoffs Adv07   05-03 1071</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Wall Street-Layoffs, Adv 07,1101</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 07</HEAD>
<HEAD>Advance for release Sunday, May 7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wall Street Firms in New Round of Post-Crash Cutbacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic in AP Access under WALLEMPLOY</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen months after the stock market crashed
and took thousands of jobs with it, Wall Street still is feeling
the aftershocks.
   Investor mistrust and high interest rates have triggered a
recession in the securities industry, forcing a second wave of
cutbacks at firms awash in profits in the mid-1980s.
   Despite rising prices that have pushed many stocks to post-crash
highs, securities firms have reported weak first-quarter earnings
or outright losses and slashed payrolls by about 2,600 workers in
the last month.
   The cutbacks have pushed Wall Street layoffs to more than 25,000
since the Dow Jones industrial average plunged 508 points on Oct.
19, 1987, the largest single-day decline in New York Stock Exchange
history.
   ``At long last after a year of much lower levels of
profitability, they realized they have to take the bulls by the
horns and do something,'' said Perrin Long of Lipper Analytical
Services Corp. ``It's just like when you and I get a toothache, we
take a day or two before we go see the dentist.''
   The staff reductions are blamed on slow business in all
segments, from low volume on the New York Stock Exchange, to a dive
in stock and bond underwriting, to declining merger activity.
   They also represent what Wall Street strategists like to call a
``correction'' _ a counter-reaction to a hiring frenzy from 1982 to
1987 in which securities firms expanded by 20 percent to 30 percent
annually and fresh-faced business-school graduates made six-figure
salaries.
   ``Some firms expanded a couple years ago like it was never going
to end,'' said Lawrence Eckenfelder, who follows Wall Street for
Prudential Bache Securities Inc. in San Francisco. ``There's too
much capacity and we're going through this painful retraction.''
   Business is so bad that the Wall Street Journal, diary of the
financial world, recently published a five-part series titled
``Wall Street's Recession,'' illustrated by cobwebs on a street
sign in lower Manhattan.
   Some symptoms of Wall Street's malaise:
   _Total employment by NYSE-member brokerages has fallen from a
peak of 262,100 employees in September 1987 to about 236,000 today,
according to the Securities Industry Association, a trade
association of brokerages. The firms had hired more than 100,000
workers from the end of 1981 to the crash.
   _Average daily trading volume on the NYSE was 159 million shares
in March, compared with a 1987 average of nearly 189 million shares
and 1988 average of about 162 million shares.
   _Merger activity, an important source of business for Wall
Street, has fallen to its lowest level in more than two years,
according to IDD Information Services Inc., a financial reporting
service.
   In the first quarter of 1989, 708 deals worth $49.6 billion were
completed, vs. 996 deals worth $101.7 billion in the previous
quarter, IDD figures show. Even discounting last year's $25 billion
RJR Nabisco Inc. buyout, the biggest takeover in history, the value
of completed deals was off about 25 percent.
   _Fees generated by underwriting new issues of corporate stocks
and bonds have plummeted. In the first quarter of 1989, 305 new
issues generated fees of $554.7 million, less than half the 692 new
issues and fees of $1.35 billion in the same 1988 period, according
to Securities Data Co.
   _Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. is selling its entire retail
brokerage division of 2,300 workers, partly because of its bad
image from an insider trading scandal but more from generally bad
business. Further large cuts are expected in Drexel bond units.
First Boston Corp. laid off 200 employees, Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
dropped 30 professionals and Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. reportedly has
let go dozens of bond traders.
   Analysts forecast another 5,000 to 10,000 layoffs in coming
months.
   ``We are in the midst of a very serious, chronic crisis,''
Salomon Brothers Inc. Chairman John Gutfreund, whose firm lost $28
million in the first quarter, told a recent meeting sponsored by
the Investment Association of New York.
   Some analysts said the public also has learned from the 1987
crash _ which Wall Streeters euphemistically have taken to calling
a ``market break'' _ the lesson that the volatile nature of the
market may not be worth the risk.
   With yields of 9 percent or more on money market funds and
certificates of deposit, individual investors are steering clear of
the riskier stock market. But for securities firms, commissions on
money market investments made for customers are far lower than for
stocks.
   ``Now we're just not addressing the issue of overcapacity. Now
the revenues just aren't coming in,'' said Jack Barbanel, senior
vice president of Gruntal &amp; Co., a midsized New York securities
firm.
   Overall, Barbanel said commission-generated revenues are down
about 35 percent across the board.
   ``The public has generally decided to stay on the sidelines and
take advantage of the high yields with the minimum amount of
risk,'' he said. ``If you can get 9 or 10 percent on a risk-free
basis, there's no point for someone with limited resources to
speculate in the stock market.''
   James Cloonan, president of the American Association of
Individual Investors in Chicago, said the average stock holding
among the 105,000 members of his organization has fallen 6 percent
in the last two years, to about 29 percent of portfolios.
   ``The industry just kept spinning on their best day and best
month and that's not how the world works,'' he said.
   But if business is so bad, why have some stock-market price
barometers reached post-crash highs, with the Dow Jones industrial
average poking through the 2,400 mark?
   Analysts attribute the rise to a strong dollar luring foreign
investment into the market and to cautious trading by investors
still participating. Also, they said recent corporate mergers and
takeovers have sharply increased the value of some stocks.
   A still-strong economy has put corporate earnings about where
they should be, analysts said. But without large numbers of
transactions, Wall Street's firms don't necessarily profit. Higher
rent and salary costs from the boom days also have hurt securities
firms.
   ``There is less volume in firms that have higher overheads,''
said Robert Brusca, chief economist with Nikko Securities
International Inc. ``They find their profit margins on each trade
are even lower than before. Ouch! Ouch!''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, May 7</NOTE>
