<FIRST>r f BC-India-Carbide     05-03 0124</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-India-Carbide,0130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arguments On Validity Of Bhopal Disaster Law End</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Wednesday concluded
hearing arguments on the legality of a law that empowered the
government to represent all victims of the Bhopal gas disaster,
news reports said.
   A five-judge panel, headed by judge Sabyasachi Mukharji, did not
say when it will give its verdict on a group of petitions that
sought to strike down the Parliament-approved law on grounds of
unconstitutionality.
   The government, armed with the law, reached a $470 million
settlement on Feb. 14 with Union Carbide Corp. For compensation to
the victims and survivors of the disaster.
   The settlement will be scrapped if the panel upholds the
petitions and declares the law unconstitutional.
</TEXT>
