<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 1636EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     05-03 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Late Buying Surge Sends Oil Futures Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil and wholesale home heating oil futures
finished higher Wednesday, lifted by a late spurt of buying on news
that the disruption in North Sea oil production will last longer
than than previously expected.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the June contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, gained 30
cents to settle at $20.10 a barrel, after a loss of 86 cents on
Tuesday.
   Heating oil for June delivery was buoyed by the crude oil buying
and ended the session up 0.25 cent at 47.86 cents a gallon. The
contract had slipped 1.85 cents in the previous session.
   Among other refined petroleum products traded on the exchange,
the June contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline settled 1.86
cents lower at 69.39 cents a gallon following Tuesday's loss of
1.36 cents.
   Market participants were in a selling mood for much of the day
and prices were weak.
   But, as the session was drawing to a close, Shell Exploration
and Production Co. said repairs on its Cormorant Alpha platform in
the North Sea were likely to take longer than anticipated, delaying
the resumption of operations until later this month.
   Shell's platform was damaged by an explosion April 18, causing
the shutdown of a transportation and production system for Brent
crude, a key international grade of crude oil. The disruption has
taken about 470,000 barrels a day off the world crude market.
   Shell said that May 26 was a reasonable date on which to expect
operations to return to normal but a resumption could take place as
early as May 18. There had been speculation in the market that the
resumption might occur next week.
   Jerry Samuels, an energy broker at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.,
said crude and heating oil futures also derived strength from
continued selling in the gasoline futures pits.
   Gasoline prices had been bid steadily higher recently in
anticipation of possible shortages due to the Exxon oil spill off
the Alaskan coast in March and the seasonal increase in demand.
   Samuels said trading volume Wednesday was moderate.
</TEXT>
