<FIRST>r f BC-FirstBoston-MetLife     05-03 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-First Boston-Met Life,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Met Life Buys 10 Percent of Investment Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CS First Boston Co. said Wednesday that
Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. has bought about 10 percent of the
investment firm.
   The value of the sale was not disclosed by the privately held
New York-based investment firm. It said the shares being sold are
part of a 30.5 percent holding of Saudi Arabian investor Suliman
Olayan.
   CS First Boston was formed in a $1.1 billion merger of First
Boston Inc. and Financiere Credit Suisse-First Boston of London.
   ``The transaction is a strategic investment which we expect will
substantially extend our global reach as part of our long-range
plan to develop a worldwide business and investment capability,''
Met Life Chairman Robert G. Schwartz said in a statement.
   The Swiss banking conglomerate Credit Suisse owns 44.5 percent
of the new entity, giving it effective control and the largest
foreign stake in a major Wall Street securities house. Management
partners of First Boston own 25 percent.
   First Boston and Credit Suisse created Financiere Credit
Suisse-First Boston as a joint venture, in 1978.
   Met Life, one of the nation's largest insurance and financial
services companies, manages more than $120 billion in assets.
</TEXT>
