<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-03 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar firmed Wednesday against most major
currencies in quiet worldwide trading even though central banks
intervened to push down its value.
   Gold prices moved higher. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted a troy ounce of gold bullion at $377.40 as of 4 p.m. EDT, up
$1.05 from late Tuesday.
   Currency dealers said reported dollar selling by a handful of
central banks, including the Federal Reserve, failed to dampen the
market's overriding bullish sentiment toward the U.S. currency.
   ``At best you can say it's holding the dollar from going
higher,'' said Earl I. Johnson, a dealer at Harris Trust &amp; Co. in
Chicago. ``What we have here is a confrontation between the market
and the central banks.''
   Worldwide demand for the dollar has been high in recent weeks
due to the continued strength of the U.S. economy and relatively
high American interest rates, which make dollar-denominated
investments more attractive.
   Some dealers said the short-term direction of the dollar could
be determined later this week, with Friday's release of April
unemployment data.
   The markets were closed Wednesday in Japan for the Constitution
Day holiday. But in London the dollar strengthened against the
Japanese yen, trading at 133.93 yen, up from Tuesday's closing
133.85 yen in Tokyo. Later, in New York, the dollar rose to 134.295
yen from 134.275 Tuesday.
   Most European markets will be closed on Thursday for the the
Ascension Day holiday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6847, more expensive for
buyers than Tuesday's late $1.6845. Sterling fetched $1.6820 in New
York, up from $1.68055. Other late dollar rates in New York
compared to Tuesday's rates, included: 1.89325 West German marks,
up from 1.8919; 1.68705 Swiss francs, up from 1.68425; 1.18415
Canadian dollars, up from 1.18125; 6.3905 French francs, down from
6.3950; and 1,383.05 Italian lire, down from 1,383.25.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared to Tuesday: 1.8900 West
German marks, up from 1.8875; 1.6830 Swiss francs, up from 1.6805;
6.3725 French francs, down from 6.3735; 2.1270 Dutch guilders,
unchanged; 1,379.20 Italian lire, down from 1,379.50; and 1.1830
Canadian dollars, unchanged.
   On the Comex in New York, gold bullion for current delivery rose
to $378.40 a troy ounce from $377.80 Tuesday.
   Gold rose in London to $377.95 an ounce from $377.50, and in
Zurich, to $379.00 an ounce from $377.30.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $376.55 an ounce, up from
$375.95.
   Silver prices were mixed. On the New York Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery rose to $5.635 a troy ounce from $5.617
Tuesday. But silver was unchanged in London at $5.65 an ounce.
</TEXT>
