<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 1934EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Milken     05-03 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Milken,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousand Salute Indicted Wall Street Wizard for Charity Donations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indicted financier Michael Milken
was honored Wednesday for multimillion-dollar donations to charity
at a celebrity-studded lunch sponsored by a group that helps
children.
   Milken, who lost his job as top bond trader for Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. because of his alleged role in a staggering
securities-fraud scandal, was praised as one who gives unstintingly
_ not just with money but his own time.
   He also has become a personal friend of many children aided by
the H.E.L.P. group, said the organization's founder, Barbara
Firestone.
   ``Michael is the kind of guy who is always giving and not
demanding anything in return,'' Ms. Firestone said at the lunch.
   Milken, one of the nation's most dynamic and wealthy financiers,
was indicted March 29 on 98 federal counts of racketeering, fraud
and stock manipulation stemming largely from the confessions of
now-imprisoned insider trader Ivan Boesky.
   Charged along with Milken are his brother, Lowell, and Drexel
trader Bruce Newberg. All have asserted their innocence and vowed
to fight the charges.
   Before his appearance at the Beverly Hilton Hotel lunch, Milken,
who has portrayed himself as the target of overzealous prosecutors,
told a reporter who asked about his public image: ``What you see
here is reality.''
   Among the approximately 1,000 attending the luncheon were
comedian Whoopi Goldberg, actor Dennis Weaver, Los Angeles Dodgers
baseball manager Tommy Lasorda and California state Controller Gray
Davis.
   The gathering was held in the same ballroom used for the
``Predators Ball,'' an annual Drexel conference on the value of
junk bonds. Milken, credited with creating the multibillion-dollar
market in those high-yield, high-risk bonds, missed this year's
Predators Ball a few weeks ago for the first time in 10 years
because of his legal problems.
   H.E.L.P. provides group homes for children who have physical,
mental or emotional problems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
