<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-03 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Prices Respond To Soviet Grain Purchase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed higher Wednesday on the
Chicago Board of Trade, with wheat prices up strongly following the
White House announcement of additional subsidized grain sales to
the Soviet Union.
   On other markets, cotton prices rose, energy futures were mostly
higher, livestock futures were up and pork futures were mixed.
Precious metals also were mixed.
   Wheat settled 1 cent to 11 cents higher with the contract for
May delivery at $4.37{ a bushel; corn was { cent to 2{ cents higher
with May at $2.76 a bushel; oats were { cent to 2} cents higher
with May at $1.87 cents a bushel; soybeans were 6 cents to 12}
cents higher with May at $7.46} a bushel.
   Wheat opened lower at the start of trading, surprising a market
that expected a strong start for wheat futures.
   ``There were a lot of people who thought the Russian business
was already reflected in prices,'' said Rich Feltes, an analyst
with Refco Inc. in Chicago. ``Today's action showed that any kind
of business outside the United States will be positive'' for the
market.
   The Bush administration announced Tuesday the United States will
sell 1.5 million metric tons of wheat to the Soviet Union under the
export bonus program.
   Soybeans futures rallied after mid-sesssion, helped along by
continued strength in May soybean demand.
   ``With farmer preoccupation with field work, there is not a lot
of soybeans moving to processors or to exporting channels,'' Feltes
said.
   Corn was up modestly, with fairly good rains in Western
corn-producing states weighing heavily on the market.
   Cotton futures prices rose sharply on New York's Cotton Exchange
on reports of severe damage to the Soviet Union's cotton crop.
   The rally also was stimulated by commission house and local
buying, said Ernest Simon, a cotton specialist for Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in New York.
   The Soviet news agency Tass reported the Central Asian Republic
of Uzbekistan suffered losses in crops and livestock following four
days of heavy rain and snow.
   ``This particular Russian problem has been with us for two
weeks,'' said Simon. ``But the news services have just begun to
point it out and strengthened new crop orders.''
   Cotton settled 1.04 cents to 1.33 cents higher with May at 66.33
cents a pound.
   Energy futures were mostly higher on the New York Mercantile
Exchange as gasoline prices came under pressure in the wake of a
American Petroleum Institute report of increased imports.
   ``People were taking profits,'' said Jim Ritterbusch, an analyst
with Carson Petroleum Co. in Chicago.
   Crude was off in sympathy with gasoline prices early in the
session, but rebounded.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 30 cents to 49 cents
higher with June at $20.10 a barrel; heating oil was 1.34 cents
lower to .41 cent higher with June at 47.86 a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was 1.86 cents lower to .89 cent higher with June at 69.39
cents a gallon.
   Livestock prices were higher and pork futures were mixed on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Cattle futures rose as higher cash prices were reported at
recent stock auctions.
   Hogs were mixed on continued light demand, although warehouses
were doing a some buying, said Dale Benson, an analyst with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Live cattle settled .25 cent to .50 cent higher with June at
72.47 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent lower to .97 cent
higher with May at 76.55 a pound; hogs were .02 cent lower to .25
cent higher with June at 47.22 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .58 cent lower to .10 cent higher with May at 30.82 cents a
pound.
   Gold and silver futures were mixed in quiet trading on New
York's Commodities Exchange.
   ``The firm dollar was a negative,'' said Fred Demler, a metals
economist for Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York, adding the
market is waiting for new economic data due out later this week.
   Gold settled $3.60 lower to 60 cents higher, with May at $378.40
a troy ounce; silver was .1 cent lower to 1.8 cents higher with May
at $5.635 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
