<DOCNO> AP890503-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Airlines     05-03 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Airlines,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Reports Widening of First-Quarter Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am Corp. reported Wednesday its
first-quarter loss widened to $151.1 million from $83.3 million a
year earlier, due in part to the bombing of its Flight 103 over
Lockerbie, Scotland, in December.
   Pan Am said the attack on Flight 103, in which 270 people were
killed, raised passenger concern about terrorism, and led to a 16
percent drop in Atlantic traffic at the corporation's main
subsidiary, Pan American World Airways.
   Revenue from the Pan Am Shuttle and Pan Am Express jumped 46.4
percent to $59.9 million from $40.9 million, Pan Am said. The
shuttle benefited from the troubles at Eastern Airlines, which
culminated with a Machinists strike near the end of the quarter.
   The parent company reported $733.5 million in revenue for the
first three months of 1989, down from $763.9 million a year earlier.
   Pan Am, which has suffered losses for several years, said its
labor expenses increased despite cost-cutting contracts with its
unions.
   However, the company said that aside from the drop in Atlantic
traffic its results were about as expected.
</TEXT>
