<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ControlData     05-03 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Control Data,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Control Data Discussing Selling ETA Assets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED STYCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Control Data Corp. is discussing with
``several parties'' the possible sale of assets of its defunct ETA
Systems supercomputer subsidiary, the president told shareholders
Wednesday.
   ``In the case of ETA, we are currently meeting with customers
and vendors,'' President Larry Perlman said at Control Data's
annual meeting. ``We are also in very preliminary discussions with
several parties to attempt to sell ETA assets and technology.''
   If Control Data tries to sell ETA assets to a Japanese company,
some analysts say it would raise concerns in Congress that valuable
U.S. technology would be handed over to a foreign country.
   Meanwhile, Control Data Chairman Robert Price told shareholders
that last month's decision to close ETA and streamline the
company's Cyber Systems mainframe business was painful but
``essential to the continued successful implementation of the
company's strategic focus.''
   Control Data said the restructuring would result in charges of
$490 million and layoffs of 3,100 employees, including 800 at ETA,
which failed to make money in its six-year history.
   Price said the restructuring should result in a profitable
second half and set the stage for sustained growth.
   Price said he is ``cautiously optimistic'' that Control Data can
arrange new credit of somewhat over $100 million to cover
short-term cash needs until later this year, when the company
expects to complete the sale of some assets.
   The company took a step in that direction Wednesday, announcing
that it had sold Action Data Services to Primerica Corp. Terms of
the sale were not disclosed.
   St. Louis-based Action Data Services, which had revenues of
$23.3 million in 1988, provides data processing and support
products to consumer credit companies and other financial services
institutions, including Primerica's Commercial Credit Co.
subsidiary.
   Several shareholders criticized company management for a
severance agreement that gave retired executive Norbert Berg nearly
$4 million, although Control Data reported profits of only $1.7
million in 1988.
   Berg, who still serves on the board of directors and acts as a
part-time consultant to the company after serving as one of Control
Data's key executives during his 29-year tenure, received scattered
boos when introduced to the shareholders at the start of the
meeting. He did not address the group.
</TEXT>
