<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 1825EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-AmericaWest     05-03 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-America West,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>America West Confident about Purchase Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America West Airlines, which has grown in
six years to the 10th-largest air carrier in the nation, has no
qualms about extending itself to the Northeast.
   ``We consider this one of the most profitable opportunities in
our industry,'' Chairman Edward Beauvais told a news conference
Wednesday after announcing a $726 million offer for Eastern
Airlines' Northeast shuttle operation.
   Beauvais estimated his airline would need to hire 800 employees
to run the shuttle. He said he expected annual revenue of $300
million to $400 million from the operation.
   America West offered $390 million cash for the shuttle, with the
balance in cash and debt assumption on 10 Boeing 757 aircraft, a
press release said. However, Beauvais said the other $336 million
included 21 Boeing 727s.
   America West does not want the 727s but would dispose of them as
a credit back to Eastern or in other ways, Beauvais said.
   The offer had to be made in haste, because U.S. Bankruptcy Judge
Burton R. Lifland had scheduled a May 12 hearing on the $365
million offer for the shuttle from New York developer Donald Trump,
Beauvais said. Eastern filed for Chapter 11 protection March 9, and
Lifland must approve any sale of assets.
   If successful in its bid, America West would operate the shuttle
from its headquarters in this Phoenix suburb.
   ``This would improve our visibility on the East Coast, and it
fits right into our specialty, which is high-frequency service in
high-density markets,'' Beauvais said.
   America West is the nation's largest airline without any
union-represented employees, and Beauvais said the operation would
be ``an America West operation, with America West employees.'' He
said Eastern employees would be interviewed for possible rehiring.
   Asked if he expected opposition from labor, Beauvais said he
didn't think so, because the 800 jobs represent only a fraction of
Eastern's workforce.
   ``I think Eastern employees would be very enthusiastic,''
Beauvais said, ``because, first, the fringe benefits at America
West compare favorably with Eastern's, and, second, the environment
at America West is very good.''
   In the last year, America West has applied for service to Japan
and Australia and has ordered 25 Boeing 737-300s or 757s for
delivery between 1992 and 1995. Despite the $800 million order,
Beauvais said America West was far from over-leveraged.
   The firm's New York investment banker, Wertheim Schroder &amp; Co.,
has assured company officers that the financing could be
accomplished, he said.
   ``This seems like a large chunk. It's not,'' Beauvais said.
``This is a $900 million company ... We've always been adequately
financed, and we've never had a cash problem. We're well suited to
take advantage of these opportunities.''
   Started in mid-1983 with 280 employees and three 737s, America
West today has about 8,500 employees and 70 planes. It serves 47
cities.
   It carried 12.7 million passengers last year, turning a $9.4
million profit on revenue of $775.7 million. In the first quarter
of 1989, America West posted a $10.1 million profit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
