<FIRST>u f AM-ColtSale     05-03 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colt Sale,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union to Explore Possible Buyout of Colt Firearms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union officials announced plans Wednesday
to pursue an employee buyout of strike-plagued Colt Firearms, which
was put on the market last week by Colt Industries Inc.
   Springfield, Mass.-based Smith &amp; Wesson Corp., a Colt
competitor, has also expressed interest in buying the division.
   Robert Madore, president of Local 376 of the United Auto
Workers, said the company had hired the Waterbury-based Naugatuck
Valley Project, which has assisted in other employee buyout
attempts, to conduct a feasibility study.
   The project asked Morgan Stanley &amp; Co., the New York investment
banker hired by Colt Industries to sell the firearms division, to
supply financial information about Colt Wednesday morning, Madore
said.
   ``We are firmly commited to pursuing at whatever lengths the
feasibility and possibility of making an offer,'' Madore said. ``We
don't see any other manufacturer ... buying Colt Firearms with a
commitment to staying in Connecticut.''
   Madore predicted that any other company that bought Colt
Firearms would sell off its assets, take control of its patents and
close its Hartford and West Hartford plants.
   New York-based Colt Industries announced Friday it wanted to
sell the troubled firearms division to concentrate on its
aerospace, automotive and industrial services operations.
   Colt has not put a price on the division, but industry analysts
have said it probably is worth $150 million to $200 million.
   The UAM represents about 1,100 workers who walked out three
years ago. The firearms division has staffed its Hartford and West
Hartford plants mostly with non-union replacement workers, although
some union members have crossed picket lines and returned to work.
About 800 workers remain on strike.
   About 650 strikers voted unanimously Tuesday night to pursue the
buyout, Madore said.
   Andrew W. Brecher, deputy commissioner for the state Department
of Economic Development, said the department has specialists who
can advise employees on how to obtain financing for such buyouts,
although he warned the buyouts face enormous difficulties.
   ``The track record is spotty,'' he said. ``There haven't been
that many successful ones in Connecticut. The ingredients really
require that you have a very patient seller, a seller that for one
reason or another is motivated to work with employees.''
</TEXT>
