<HEAD>New Coleman Co. President Named</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coleman Co.'s former president, Lawrence M.
Jones, was brought back by the new owner of the outdoor recreation
products manufacturer Wednesday to take that post again.
   Sheldon Coleman, grandson of the founder of the company,
announced Tuesday that Wall Street takeover strategist Ronald O.
Perelman had fired him as president, chief executive and board
chairman. A Coleman Co. prepared statement Wednesday said Sheldon
Coleman resigned.
   Jones, 58, left Coleman in January 1988 to become vice chairman
and chief financial officer for the Fleming Cos. in Oklahoma City.
He was chairman of the Coleman executive committee from 1985 to
1987 after serving as president from 1971.
   Jones is a former chairman of the Kansas Board of Regents and
was an unsuccessful candidate for the Republican nomination for
governor in 1986.
   Jerry Levin, executive vice president of MacAndrews &amp; Forbes
Holdings Inc., was appointed Coleman chairman Wednesday. He said he
would serve as liaison with MacAndrews &amp; Forbes, which is wholly
owned by Perelman and is Coleman Co.'s new parent corporation. The
investment firm also owns Revlon Inc.
   Perelman bought Coleman Co. six weeks ago for $545 million.
   Coleman's offices will remain in Wichita. Levin will keep his
office at MacAndrews &amp; Forbes' Midwestern headquarters in
Minneapolis, he said.
   Coleman is the world's top manufacturer of outdoor recreation
products, including Coleman lanterns. Record sales of $657.9
million and record earnings of $24.5 million were recorded in 1988.
</TEXT>
