<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Ogilvy     05-03 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Ogilvy,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ogilvy First-Quarter Earnings Up 10.6 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ogilvy Group Inc., the advertising agency
holding company under threat of a hostile takeover, said Wednesday
its first-quarter profit rose 10.6 percent over the same 1988
period.
   Ogilvy reported net income of $3.8 million, or 26 cents a share,
on revenue of $197.7 million. That compared with earnings of $3.43
million, or 24 cents a share, on revenue of $191.1 million in the
first quarter last year.
   The New York company attributed the gains to strong overseas
performances. It said foreign advertising revenues increased 12.6
percent while domestic advertising revenues were flat.
   WPP Group PLC of London, which owns J. Walter Thompson, the big
New York advertising firm, made an unsolicited $730 million bid for
Ogilvy last week. Ogilvy, parent company of Ogilvy &amp; Mather
Worldwide, said it wants to remain independent.
   Ogilvy, the world's fifth-largest ad holding company, said
quarterly advertising revenues increased 5 percent to $123.6
million from $117.7 million a year ago. Its public relations
division, which includes Adams &amp; Rhinehart, showed a 30 percent
revenue rise, to $12.99 million.
   Its marketing research division revenue declined 10 percent,
while other areas suffered a 23 percent drop, principally from
divested operations.
</TEXT>
