<FIRST>r f AM-Textiles     05-03 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Textiles,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Textile Caucus Forms Task Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional allies of the textile industry,
undaunted by setbacks in recent years, formed a task force
Wednesday to search for new means to combat foreign inroads in the
U.S. market.
   ``We know that the textile and apparel workers that we represent
need their jobs,'' said Rep. Marilyn Lloyd, D-Tenn, chairman of the
Congressional Textile Caucus. ``We will have to find creative
legislative solutions to slow the flood of imports that is
threatening their jobs.''
   Lloyd said President Bush already has made it clear that he will
not back omnibus legislation to aid the textile industry. Congress
has passed such measures in recent years but sponsors have been
unable to muster enough votes to override presidential vetoes.
   Instead of putting all of their efforts into one bill, Lloyd
said, textile lawmakers would ``pursue many avenues to assist the
textile and apparel industry ... Our legislative activities will be
much more diverse than they have been in recent years.''
   As examples, she cited a bill introduced by Rep. Ed Jenkins,
D-Ga., that would eliminate a scheduled 50 percent cut in tariffs
on textiles and apparels imported from Caribbean Basin Initiative
countries.
   Rep. Bill Hefner, D-N.C., may offer measures involving military
apparel, Lloyd said in a statement released by her office.
   Besides Lloyd, other members of the task force are Reps. Butler
Derrick, D-S.C.; Frank Horton, R-N.Y., and Joseph Moakley, D-Mass.
</TEXT>
