<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-USTrade 1stLd-Writethru f0084 05-03 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-US Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0084,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Cites 42 U.S. Trade Barriers; Criticizes 1988 Trade Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Its release ...,' to CORRECT that U.S. report
released Friday, sted Tuesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The EEC Commission Wednesday released
its 1989 report on U.S. trade barriers, singling out 42 regulations
and trade practices that it said impedes imports from the 12
European Economic Community nations.
   The barriers include quantitative restrictions, export
subsidies, customs barriers, public procurement policies,
countervailing duties, anti-dumping procedures and tax policies,
the EEC report said.
   Its release came five days after the U.S. administration
released its report on foreign trade practices it considers unfair.
   EEC Commission spokesman Claus Ehlermann said the timing of the
release of the EEC report was not linked to the U.S. report. He
said the EEC report was an annual event and its release simply
``coincided'' with the report by the Office of the U.S. Special
Trade Representative.
   The EEC report criticized the 1988 U.S. Fair Trade Practices Act
which, it said, will ``make it more likely that unilateral action
will be taken to redress allegedly unfair trade practices,''
   ``Such unilateral action...without authorization from the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade is illegal.''
   The report also cited the ``Buy American'' provision of the U.S.
Trade Act that ``has created permanent discrimination in favor of
U.S. products.''
   The clause provides for action by the U.S. Administration
against foreign countries which discriminate against U.S. products
or services in government procurement, including a ban against
``offending'' countries.
   Another category of restrictions includes U.S. measures which
have been found to violate international trading rules, and in
which the United States has neither modified nor offered
compensation to its trade partners for trade damage caused.
   As examples the report cites the ``U.S. failure'' to implement
findings of the GATT on the illegality of the ``Superfund'' oil
levy and the ``non-conformity'' of the U.S. system of customs
users' fees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0308 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CableTV 1stLd-Writethru f0228 05-03 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cable TV, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0228,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Press For Regulation Of Cable TV Industry</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `But with ...,' to RESTORE dropped word `percent'
after 99.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Connecticut lawmakers, declaring that
cable television has turned from a luxury into a ``psychological
necessity'' for millions of Americans, vowed Wednesday to press for
consumer protections against fast-rising rates.
   Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman, D-Conn., and Rep. Christopher Shays,
R-Conn., introduced legislation to place regulations on an industry
that they say has been riding roughshod over consumers since it
began setting its own rates 2{ years ago.
   ``It is time to return consumer protections to cable
television,'' Lieberman said. ``We're not trying to punish the
cable TV industry. We're just saying `Let's be fair'.''
   Congress barred state and local governments from setting cable
TV rates in most jurisdictions effective Dec. 29, 1986. The move
was designed to foster growth in the relatively new industry. Cable
companies had complained that their basic rates were kept
artificially low by local officials who were subject to election
pressures.
   But with virtually no competition _ more than 99 percent of the
nation's cable systems enjoy a local cable monpoly _ basic service
prices have risen 32 percent since deregulation, Shays said. The
Commerce Department estimates that rates will increase by about 14
percent this year, according to Lieberman.
   Shays said the monthly service fee on the basic package in his
southern Connecticut district has increased from $4.50 in 1984 to
$19.95 today.
   ``It is one thing for the government to foster the growth and
development of a fledgling industry ... and quite another to allow
a powerful industry to continue extracting monopoly prices from the
nation's consumers,'' the senator said.
   ``You can't have it both ways,'' Shays said at a news
conference. ``There's either got to be competition or regulation.''
   Lynn McReynolds of the National Cable Television Association
argued that cable TV operators do not have monopolies because the
$13.8 billion industry competes with commercial television as well
as video rentals, satellite TV and movie theaters.
   ``Cable is a competitor in the entertainment marketplace and
there's lots of competition,'' she said.
   McReynolds said basic service fees have increased by about
one-third since deregulation because those fees had been set by
local officials. Other special services, which were never
regulated, have seen only slight increases and in some cases
decreases since December 1986, she said.
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics said overall cable fees increased
by 6.6 percent in the first year of deregulation and 7.9 percent
last year, according to McReynolds.
   Industry representatives also argue that cable TV is a luxury
that consumers can choose to buy, and therefore should not be
regulated like power companies.
   ``We'd like to get to the point that we're a necessity, but
we're still a long way from that,'' McReynolds said.
   The lawmakers, however, argued that cable TV has become more and
more of a necessity as cable companies buy up rights to sporting
events and other programming that previously was available on
traditional commercial television.
   ``It's become an essential part of our lives,'' said Shays.
   Lieberman said many Americans, especially the elderly, rely
heavily on cable programs for their news, entertainment and even
shopping. He called cable ``a psychological necessity.''
   The bill would allow local governments to set cable rates,
require 60-day notices for service changes and allow regulators to
adjust rates as a result of any changes. The measure also seeks to
limit concentration of ownership and encourage cable systems to
provide local stations.
   The issue of re-regulating the cable industry emerged in
Congress last year during hearings held by Sen. Howard Metzenbaum,
D-Ohio, but Lieberman and Shays are unsure of their prospects for
success in this session.
   ``Most legislators would like this issue to go away,'' said
Shays, pointing to the conflict between consumer interests and a
well-financed industry.
   McReynolds urged Congress to hold off on any action until the
Federal Communications Commission submits a report at the end of
1990 analyzing the impact of cable deregulation.
   Nearly 55 percent of all TV households in the nation get cable
television.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0309 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-USAir-McDonnell     05-03 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USAir-McDonnell,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>USAir Buys Up To 40 Planes from McDonnell Douglas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir Group Inc. announced a $1.3 billion deal
Wednesday with McDonnell Douglas Corp. to buy 20 of its MD-82
aircraft and take options on 20 more.
   The first two of the new planes would be delivered in September
1992 and the remainder of the firm orders and options, if taken,
would be delivered to USAir at the rate of one per month starting
in January 1993.
   The planes will carry about 143 passengers, including an
eight-seat first-class section.
   Washington-based USAir, the nation's ninth-largest airline, is a
long-time operator of McDonnell Douglas aircraft.
   USAir's fleet currently includes 31 Md-80s acquired through the
1988 merger of Pacific Southwest Airline, and 74 smaller DC-9's,
which also were made by McDonnell Douglas.
   Last month, USAir ordered 18 Boeing 737 jetliners and took
options on 36 more in a deal with a potential value of about $1.7
billion.
   That transaction brings USAir's current Boeing 737 orders to 68
aircraft, which will be delivered between now and 1992, plus 96
options, which would be delivered between 1992 and 1995, USAir said.
   USAir also has ordered 20 Fokker 100 jets and holds options on
20 more. First delivery is scheduled for June. Fokker is a Dutch
aircraft manufacturer.
</TEXT>
