<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 2118EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Northwest     05-03 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: KKR Interested In Northwest Airlines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York leveraged buyout firm Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. has indicated an interest in acquiring NWA
Inc., the parent of Northwest Airlines, according to a report
published Wednesday.
   KKR formally told Northwest of its interest in a bid, the Wall
Street Journal reported, quoting unidentified people familiar with
the takeover battle. The notification Tuesday came as part of a
bidding procedure NWA set up in response to oil billionaire Marvin
Davis' offer, the Journal said.
   If KKR pursues a bid, it would be the firm's largest known
buyout effort since it bought RJR Nabisco Inc. for a record $25
billion in February, according to the Journal.
   Spokesmen for KKR and NWA refused comment on KKR's apparent
interest, the newspaper said.
   KKR's disclosure came in response to a deadline set by NWA's
investment banker, First Boston Corp., the Journal said. Bidders
will next gain access to confidential company data as well as
meetings with company management in return for signing a
confidentiality agreement.
   Also on Tuesday, Davis put his hostile $2.7 billion bid for
Northwest on hold in exchange for confidential corporation
information from the nation's fourth-largest airline.
   Davis' offer will remain outstanding but he will postpone buying
up shares prior to June 30. He also agreed to stop soliciting
proxies from shareholders in an attempt to unseat the company's
board of directors at the annual stockholders meeting May 15.
   The NWA board has rejected Davis' $90-a-share offer as
inadequate. NWA stock closed Wednesday at $101.50, down 25 cents on
the New York Stock Exchange.
   Davis said the restrictions will end immediately if NWA
announces the sale of the company or a non-sale alternative,
including no transaction at all, before June 30. He also said NWA
agreed to give him 10 days notice if it decides to pursue certain
non-sale alternatives.
   Meanwhile, Northwest and its 5,000-member pilots union continued
negotiations Wednesday, according to Jim Halvorson, spokesman for
the Air Line Pilots Association. The talks resumed Tuesday for the
first time in about two weeks and were expected to continue through
Friday.
</TEXT>
